<FIRST>u i AM-Egypt-Libya     05-31 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Egypt-Libya,0344</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mubarak Meets Libyan Emissary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Hosni Mubarak and high-ranking
Libyan official Ahmed Gaddaf Dam met on Wednesday to discuss
improving relations between their two countries, the state-run
Middle East News Agency reported.
   It said the meeting is a continuation of conciliatory talks that
started between Mubarak and Libyan leader Col. Moammar Gadhafi at
last week's Arab League summit at Casablanca, Morocco.
   Gaddaf Dam is a cousin of Gadhafi and Libya's intelligence
chief. He came to Cairo Tuesday.
   The agency gave no details on the meeting or elaborate on the
duration of the visit.
   The summit was Egypt's first since 1976. Cairo's relations with
the Arab League plummeted in 1977 with the late President Anwar
Sadat's visit to Jerusalem. Egypt's league membership was suspended
and most Arab states cut diplomatic ties in 1979, after Sadat
signed a peace treaty with the Jewish state.
   Libya is among the last to soften its attitude toward Egypt.
   Mubarak told Egyptian journalists before Wednesday's meeting
that Egyptian-Libyan relations ``are on the threshold of a new era
based on a right foundation of frankness.''
   On Monday, Egypt reopened its borders with Libya for the first
time in more than a decade. The land route is used mainly by
thousands of Egyptians working in Libya. During the years the
border was closed, Egyptian workers had to travel between the two
countries by way of Greece or some other point.
   Negotiations are under way between a Libyan civil aviation
delegation and Egyptian authorities for restoring direct air
service between Cairo and the Libyan capital Tripoli.
   Egyptian-Libyan relations had been strained since 1972, when
Sadat rejected a bid by Gadhafi ffor an immediate merger of the two
countries. They fought a brief border war in 1977.
   Mubarak's government has charged Gadhafi with several atttempts
to assassinate Libyan dissidents in Egyptian exile. It suspected
Libya of laying mines in the Gulf of Suez and Red Sea that damaged
20 ships in the summer of 1984.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
