<FIRST>u a AM-NuclearSabotage 3rdLd-Writethru a0844 05-31 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nuclear Sabotage, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0844,0591</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four Environmentalists Arrested on Nuclear Sabotage Charges</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with founder of radical group among those
arrested, background on group, quotes, other details. Adds byline. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MEL REISNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A radical environmental group's founder and three
other people were arrested Wednesday on charges they conspired to
sabotage two nuclear power plants and an Energy Department bomb
factory in the West, the FBI said.
   Two men were arrested early Wednesday while trying to use a
propane torch to cut down a utility-line pole leading from an
electrical substation in Wenden, Ariz., FBI officials in Washington
and Phoenix said.
   A woman was arrested in Prescott, nearly 80 miles northeast of
Wenden, in the alleged plot, the FBI said.
   A third man was arrested in Tucson on charges of conspiring with
th others to sabotage commercial nuclear power plants at
Wintersburg, Ariz., and near San Luis Obispo, Calif., as well as
the federal government's Rocky Flats Nuclear Weapons Plant near
Golden, Colo.
   The FBI said the defendants were members of a radical
environmentalist group calling itself the Evan Mecham Eco-Terrorist
International Conspiracy.
   The organization, which took its name from the former Arizona
governor who was impeached last year, has sent communiques to news
organizations in the Southwest claiming responsibility for criminal
acts, the FBI said.
   The FBI said the arrests resulted from a three-year undercover
investigation that began after vandals cut power lines at the Palo
Verde Nuclear Generating Station in Wintersburg, 50 miles west of
Phoenix, in May 1986.
   David Foreman, 42, who founded Earth First! _ the exclamation
point is part of the name _ in 1979, was arrested in Tucson on a
charge of conspiracy. He appeared before a federal magistrate there
and was ordered held without bond.
   The other three appeared in Phoenix and also were ordered held
for an appearance Friday in U.S. District Court.
   Mark L. Davis, 39, and Marc A. Baker, 37, both of Prescott, were
charged with conspiracy to sabotage a nuclear facility as well as
destruction of an energy facility, destruction of property used in
interstate commerce and destruction of government property.
   The FBI said they were arrested while trying to cut down a
utility pole supporting a power line that links an electrical
substation with two irrigation pumping stations of the Central
Arizona Project, a multibillion-dollar canal system bringing
Colorado River water to Phoenix and Tucson.
   Margaret ``Peggy'' Katherine Millett, 35, of Prescott, was
arrested and charged with the same crimes, the FBI said.
   The FBI also investigated acts of vandalism against ski-lift
equipment at a Flagstaff ski resort and the cutting of power-line
poles at three uranium mines last year in northern Arizona, the
bureau said.
   Foreman is a co-founder of Earth First!, said Rod Mondt, a
spokesman in the Tucson office of the group's journal.
   The loosely organized group, which has no officers or formal
membership, didn't plan the attack, Mondt said, but added:
   ``Some of us support the right to do those kinds of things.''
   Earth First! was inspired in part by ``The Monkey Wrench Gang,''
a novel by the late Edward Abbey about a trio of
environmentalalists who try to blow up the Glen Canyon Dam.
   Mondt said he was unaware of an organization called the Evan
Meacham Eco-Terrorist International Conspiracy, but noted that the
organization's acronym would be EMETIC, a word defined as a
medicine or other substance that causes vomiting.
</TEXT>
