<FIRST>r a PM-Homeless-Amnesty     05-31 0310</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Homeless-Amnesty,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Homeless Featured in Anti-Death Penalty Commercial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new public service announcement against
capital punishment features an unusual cast of characters: the
homeless.
   The Amnesty International television commercial, to be offered
soon for international broadcasts, uses 50 homeless people.
   ``I didn't want people that were well-fed, happy human beings,
to try to pull off the roles of people all over the world who have
been imprisoned for long periods of time,'' said commercial
director Tony Bill, who co-produced ``The Sting'' and directed ``My
Bodyguard.''
   ``The homeless are disenfranchised people, and they are people
who are, in effect, oppressed,'' said Bill, who like others donated
work for the project.
   The black-and-white ads cast the homeless as prisoners facing
execution, their heads covered in bags before an imaginary killing.
The 30- and 60-second commercials conclude with the shot of a
falling guillotine blade.
   Bill said the faces of the homeless, unlike those of
professional actors, naturally are filled with hopelessness and
defeat.
   ``I think by seeing them on the screen, your attention is drawn
to them,'' Bill said. ``We're talking about a larger issue. The
homeless people sort of represent people in prison.''
   Bill, who runs the Venice restaurant, selected his cast from the
crowds of people who gather for a free meal the restaurant provides
every Tuesday. Those cast were paid $40 for the one-day commercial
shooting and given lunch.
   ``The saddest thing was to see them leave at the end of the
shoot,'' said producer Clare Baren of Riverrun Films. ``It was
horrible to think where they were going back to. They were just
really terrific people.''
   The commercial's makers hope television stations across the
country and around the globe will broadcast the spot. It also will
be shown at the commercial competition at Cannes starting June 19.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
