<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--LegislativeIntrusion     05-31 0120</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Legislative Intrusion,0121</SECOND>
<HEAD>Masked Intruders Disrupt Parliament Session</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COPENHAGEN, Denmark (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This country's parliament has a
tradition of free public access, so it wasn't much trouble for
about 50 masked intruders to barge into the chamber and rip up
documents as legislators looked on.
   The intruders, said by police to be members of a radical
squatter's organization, fought briefly with unarmed parliament
guards during Tuesday's raid. Police said they arrested about 30,
but the rest escaped.
   It was the first time demonstrators had disturbed a session of
the Folketinget, or parliament, police said
   Parliament's chairman, Erik Ninn-Hansen, said afterward that the
intruders would be prosecuted and that security in Christiansborg
Palace, which houses the parliament, would be reviewed.
</TEXT>
