<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--UnusualStrike     05-31 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Unusual Strike,0185</SECOND>
<HEAD>Italian Strikers Give Tourists a Break</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tourists got an after-hours look at the Roman Forum
and free tours of the ancient ruins, the Palatine Hill and the
Coliseum because of an unusal work protest by the caretakers.
   The Forum is normally closed on Tuesday afternoon, but the
caretakers chose instead to work overtime and give away free
tickets as a way of protesting work conditions and ``Cultural
Ministry bureaucracy.''
   The workers said they want more money and they want the ministry
to train them and offer guided tours of the Forum. They also want
the ministry to hire more people and to keep the site open for more
hours.
   Tourists in Italy often miss the chance to see archeological
sites and musems because of limited visiting hours and recurrent
strikes.
   The unusual protest was designed to gain public support, said a
woman employee who asked not to be identified.
   ``If we stopped work, we would just get a bad press. This way we
can show people that we are also interested in them,'' she said.
</TEXT>
