<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 0057EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-India-USTrade     05-31 0737</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-US Trade,0763</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government, Business Baffled By US Trade Warning</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   By accusing India of unfair trade
practices, the United States may have dealt a major setback to
Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi's cautious efforts to open the vast
Indian market to foreign goods.
   In a nation that has long aspired to self-sufficiency and thrown
up a bewildering and costly barricade of red tape to foreign
investment, the few U.S. brand names to reach consumers have
achieved overnight popularity.
   Wrangler jeans, CBS music cassettes and Chesterfield cigarettes
are among American goods that entered India after Gandhi's
government started easing the protectionist policies of his mother
and predecessor, Indira Gandhi.
   Pepsi is poised to follow.
   All are manufactured in India under license and in association
with local partners, with the foreign share limited to 40 percent.
   The opening of Indian markets started in 1985, a few months
after Gandhi took office. But observers say last week's citing of
India under the U.S. Omnibus Trade Act could hurt the process.
   ``The U.S. perception seems to be that it can open up Indian
markets with a crowbar,'' said industrialist Hari Shankar
Singhania. ``From the logical point of view, it is better to use
goodwill.''
   ``Maybe they got impatient. I doubt whether the intended results
will follow _ and maybe contrary reactions will set in,'' he added.
   In an editorial entitled ``A Super Folly,'' the pro-government
Hindustan Times said: ``By branding India as an unfair trade
partner at a time when the country is attempting to move towards
more open trade, the U.S. runs the risk of reversing the tide of
opinion building up in favor of liberalization.''
   A U.S. Embassy official acknowledged India had eased its trade
restrictions but said much remains to be done.
   ``There has definitely been some liberalization, but there is a
considerable distance to go,'' he said, speaking on condition he
not be identified further.
   Washington accused India of violating the 1988 trade act by
impeding direct foreign investment and closing its insurance market
to foreign companies. The law allows the United States to impose
tariffs of 100 percent on goods from India if negotiations fail to
remove the barriers within 18 months.
   Despite its tentative reforms, India still levies customs duties
in excess of 200 percent on some foreign goods and industrial
components.
   The government has yet to respond to the American invitation for
negotiations. Its only comments have been that the U.S. action is
unfair and irrational.
   ``Negotiations cannot be held under threat. How can you expect
any self-respecting country to do it?'' said Singhania, who led a
delegation to the United States earlier this month to try to ward
off the citing of India under the Omnibus Trade Act.
   A U.S. delegation also came to New Delhi earlier this month for
discussions with Indian government officials.
   ``We justified our restrictions because of our balance of
payments constraints,'' said Anwarul Hoda, a Commerce Ministry
official who took part in the talks. ``But even while offering
justifications, we are liberalizing. Our trade has never been so
liberal.''
   Hoda and Singhania noted that India's trade surplus with the
United States has been declining, from $1 billion in 1987 to $700
million in 1988.
   They said Washington's tough measures were unjustified since
India was responsible for less than 1 percent of the United States'
overall trade deficit. Japan, which also was cited, is responsible
for 44 percent. Only one other nation was singled out _ Brazil.
   Both Hoda and Singhania acknowledged the tremendous appeal of
U.S. goods and services for India's 880 million people.
   ``U.S. brands, techniques and marketing systems are the best in
the world,'' said Singhania, president of the J.K. Organization,
which makes synthetic fabrics, paints and cosmetics.
   Among consumer items, U.S.-franchised stereo cassettes hold a
virtual monopoly in India's Western music market.
   ``CBS cassettes sell very well,'' said Kishore, a salesman at a
New Delhi music shop who declined to give his last name. ``Since
they came in the market, Music India (the major local company) has
dropped.''
   Another indicator of the appeal of American goods is the U.S.
Embassy's semiannual sale of obsolete equipment.
   A weekly news magazine, India Today, said recently that buyers
bid feverishly for 10-year-old air conditioners, sometimes offering
more than the price of a new Indian model, because ``of the strong
mystique of the foreign brand.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
