<FIRST>r a PM-Secchia     05-31 0694</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Secchia,0720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Controversial Ambassador Nominee Is Respected in Hometown</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents grafs 8-11.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LISA PERLMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People at George Bush's campaign
rallies in southwestern Michigan last year heard first from his
foremost cheerleader, Peter Secchia.
   The outspoken and sometimes abrasive state Republican party
leader positioned himself at the podium for more than an hour
before Bush's arrival and led thousands of supporters in songs
taunting Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis.
   As Michigan's national committeeman since 1980, Secchia never
has been at a loss for words.
   Until now.
   After months of tireless work on Bush's behalf, Secchia was
rewarded with a nomination as ambassador to Italy.
   It initially appeared the 52-year-old Italian-American lumber
magnate would sail through Senate confirmation, but Secchia's
propensity for coarse humor and off-color remarks have haunted him.
   For example:
   _ A few days after Bush's selection of Dan Quayle to run as vice
president, Secchia defended Quayle amid rumors linking him
romantically to a former female lobbyist. ``If that's the only
thing you can say about a 41-year-old man _ that he danced close
with a good-looking woman _ then I think he'll make one hell of a
vice president.''
   _ Secchia doesn't deny he made an offensive hand gesture to a
political foe in the basement of a bar, but after it was reported
called it good-natured political sparring.
   _ A January 1988 Harper's magazine article about the Michigan
GOP portrayed Secchia as a sexist and quoted him as making vulgar
remarks about the size of a woman's breasts. Secchia says he was
misquoted.
   _ In August 1988, Secchia said of his political adversaries, ``I
know what sodomy is because that's what Democrats are always doing
to me.''
   Secchia complains his comments have been misinterpreted, and
that some of the people now judging him in Washington don't
understand his humor.
   There's been grumbling in Italian newspapers over Bush's
selection of an ambassador who is an expert fund-raiser with a
sharp tongue but little foreign policy experience.
   In the Senate, Secchia's confirmation vote was stalled until at
least Wednesday because of concerns of Sen. Malcolm Wallop, R-Wyo.
   The delay caused Secchia, the grandson of Italian immigrants, to
miss Bush's visit to Italy last week.
   ``He's certainly not pleased ... with reports that the Senate
wants to make him twist in the wind as punishment for so-called
past sins,'' said Jeff Davis, a Secchia employee fielding media
calls. Secchia has declined all requests for interviews since his
confirmation was stalled two weeks ago.
   The Senate Foreign Relations Committee approved Secchia's
nomination, but Chairman Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., warned that
Secchia might be an embarrassment.
   At home in Grand Rapids, those who know Secchia well see him
primarily as a generous, hard-working, good-hearted community
leader _ who just happens to put his foot in his mouth occasionally.
   ``He's a street fighter,'' said businessman Charles Yob, a close
friend and political associate. ``When he wants something, he goes
for it.''
   Even his political foes acknowledge Secchia has been a driving
force in the state Republican Party.
   As chairman and chief executive officer of The Universal Cos.
Inc., the father of four has turned the Grand Rapids business into
a $400 million lumber, restaurant and real estate empire, the
fourth-largest building products distributor in the country.
   He has vowed to tone down his rhetoric when he takes on his new
job in Italy.
   But some of his political adversaries are dubious.
   ``I never suspected I would hear the name Peter Secchia in the
same sentence with the word diplomat,'' said Mark Fox, a Lansing
attorney and deputy state director of Dukakis' campaign.
   ``His mouth works faster than his mind. ... I don't think it'll
be long before he'll put his foot in his mouth when he gets over to
Italy,'' Fox said.
   But others believe Italy will be disarmed.
   ``I get the feeling that he is moving on to a different phase of
his life, where he going to learn and practice the art of
diplomacy. But I know it probably won't come easy,'' national GOP
Committeewoman Ronna Romney said.
</TEXT>
