<FIRST>r a PM-RestaurateurRetiring     05-31 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Restaurateur Retiring,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Duke of (</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By F.N. D'ALESSIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a city where pork bellies have made commodity
traders rich, it took a European, Chef Louis Szathmary, to master
the art of turning goose livers into gold.
   After 26 years, Chef Louis next month is closing his North Side
restaurant called the Bakery.
   ``I grossed more than $1,300,000 a year for 26 years, and that's
only five dinners a week _ no lunch, no bar and no `early birds,'
'' Szathmary said.
   ``Some restaurants give a discount for diners who arrive before
5 p.m., but I never did that because my meat supplier couldn't
guarantee quality that early.''
   The income estimate is even more remarkable in that the Bakery
has never seated more than 170 people at one time, and all of its
five-course dinners had a fixed price: from $5 in 1962 to $25 this
year.
   When Szathmary opened the Bakery, it was one of Chicago's first
restaurants outside of the downtown area to feature classic French
cuisine. Resembling an unpretentious European inn, it also was one
of the first where the food got top billing over the decor.
   It was also a place to sit down and listen to Szathmary
philosophize about food. Every night he was in town, he visited
each table, talking with patrons as he doled out his fresh country
pate.
   ``We have every day fresh flowers, and sometimes the silver
matches, but the important thing is the food on the plate,'' he
said.
   And the food on the plate often is beef Wellington. It may be a
haute cuisine cliche now, but Szathmary made his first hit by
smearing beef with goose liver pate and baking it in a pastry shell.
   ``The food writers joke about beef Wellington now, but they all
raved about it once, and I know 50 percent of our sales after 26
years is still beef Wellington.''
   Other popular items at the Bakery have included pork loin
stuffed with Hungarian sausage and roast duck served with cherry
sauce.
   On his retirement at age 70, Szathmary is giving his
24,000-volume cookbook library to the University of Iowa. Other
items in the collection will go to Johnson &amp; Wales University in
Providence, R.I.
   ``Some of my cookbooks go back to the late 1400s and they may be
important in teaching the history of food,'' he said.
   Some of his more modern works, though, were written by Szathmary
himself, who is the author of ``The Chef's Secret Cookbook,''
``American Gastronomy,'' ``The Chef's New Secret Cookbook,'' ``The
Bakery Restaurant Cookbook'' and the 15-volume ``Cookery
Americana.''
   A native of Transylvania, Szathmary came to this country in
1951, and spent 11 years in food research before becoming a
restaurateur.
   ``I could not do it now,'' he said. ``The restaurant business
has changed too much. ...
   ``One thing I am proud of, though,'' he added. ``I never served
one kiwi fruit.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
