<DOCNO> AP890531-0018 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 0043EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-CollegeDesegregation     05-31 0668</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-College Desegregation,0690</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Official Issues Final Recommendations in Louisiana Desegregation
Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN SAYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A special official appointed to draft an
integration plan for Louisiana's higher education system
recommended Tuesday that no universities be closed or merged and
that they be governed by a powerful unified board.
   The final recommendation by Paul Verkuil, who was appointed by a
three-judge federal panel, contained few changes compared to his
preliminary proposal April 18, said John Kennedy, an attorney with
Gov. Buddy Roemer's administration.
   ``I don't think this is a cosmetic plan,'' Kennedy said at a
news briefing Tuesday night. ``I think you will look on the
landscape of higher education in five years and it will not be the
same. The changes will be fundamental _ quality and desegregation.''
   The court will have the final say on the plan. Kennedy said he
did not know if the judges would hear further comment from the
parties in the case _ including the predominantly black Southern
University System, the U.S. Justice Department and Grambling State
University's alumni association _ before deciding whether to
approve it.
   Kennedy said Roemer, who had pushed for a single board with
authority to implement desegregation plans, was pleased by
Verkuil's recommendation.
   ``The single board is the linchpin of this whole thing,''
Kennedy said.
   State Sen. William Jefferson of New Orleans, an attorney for the
Southern University System, said he had not seen the recommendation
and declined to comment immediately. Other parties were not
available for immediate comment.
   Verkuil was appointed to draw up a new plan after the court
ruled last year that a 1981 desegregation agreement between the
state and the Justice Department had failed. The plan called
primarily for spending millions of dollars to upgrade faculty,
programs and facilities at Southern and Grambling.
   The dispute began 15 years ago when the Justice Department filed
a lawsuit against the state accusing it of operating a dual system
of higher education for blacks and whites.
   Under the plan recommended Tuesday by Verkuil, president of
William and Mary College in Virginia:
   _ The single governing board would consist of 17 members,
including at least seven blacks. Verkuil said the board should show
a geographic balance, represent all schools and include a student.
   Board members would be appointed by the governor and confirmed
by the state Senate. Members would not have to come from existing
boards.
   Black leaders had said a unified board would be insensitive to
the needs of historically black Southern University and Grambling.
   _ All current university systems would be abolished in favor of
one system under the unified board. A new president for higher
education would be selected and an interim president would be
appointed during the search.
   _ Louisiana State University would be the state's flagship
institution with the greatest number of graduate programs and the
toughest admission standards. Currently, all Louisiana colleges
have an open-admissions policy.
   _ A second tier of schools _ Louisiana Tech, Southern University
at Baton Rouge, the University of New Orleans and the University of
Southwestern Louisiana _ would also offer graduate programs, but
fewer than LSU. Those schools would have less stringent admissions
standards.
   Kennedy said Verkuil's recommendation would allow the new board
to add other schools to the second tier.
   Other four-year colleges would have still less restrictive
admissions and limited graduate degree programs.
   _ Two-year community colleges would offer open admissions and be
responsible for most remedial education.
   _ The state must continue to spend money to enhance Southern and
Grambling. Verkuil did not recommend a dollar amount.
   Previous agreements between Grambling and Louisiana Tech to end
program duplication should be carried out, while the LSU and
Southern law schools in Baton Rouge should agree to let students at
one school take courses at the other, Verkuil said.
   Kennedy said Verkuil recognized the state's financial
difficulties, including a projected deficit of more than $700
million for the next fiscal year and possible cuts to higher
education.
</TEXT>
