<FIRST>r a PM-BroadwaySeason     05-31 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Broadway Season,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>A Record for Broadway</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Higher ticket prices, strong long-running
musicals, several acclaimed new plays helped Broadway end its
season with a record box-office take.
   Theaters took in $262 million, up 4 percent over the 1988-89
season's total of $253 million, according to figures released
Tuesday.
   The League of American Theaters and Producers also said
attendance was 8 million, off slightly from last season's record
8.1 million but still higher than the 7 million of two years ago.
   ``It was a good season. It had strong box-office dollars and
solid attendance,'' said George Wachtel, the league's director of
research. ``There were fewer musicals but there were more plays.
Over the last four years, it was one of the best seasons,
attendance-wise.''
   Much of the box-office strength came from long-running musicals
particularly ``The Phantom of the Opera'' and ``Les Miserables,''
each grossing more than $500,000 a week, and other veteran hits
like ``Cats'' and ``Me and My Girl.''
   The only new musical to demonstrate much box-office muscle is
``Jerome Robbins' Broadway,'' which has been running at slightly
under capacity since it opened in January. The compilation of dance
numbers from some of the choreographer's biggest hits has been
grossing about $520,000 a week.
   It also has a top ticket price of $55.
   The average ticket price rose from $31.10 to $33.90, up 6
percent from last year, the league said. Much of the rise, Wachtel
said, was because theatergoers were paying full price for tickets
to hot shows like ``Phantom'' and ``Les Miserables,'' which are not
available at half-price discount.
   Only seven musicals _ including a revival of ``Ain't Misbehavin'
'' _ opened on Broadway during the 1988-89 season, compared with 15
the previous year. They included such flops as ``Legs Diamond,''
``Chu Chem'' and ``Welcome to the Club,'' as well as such
still-running shows as ``Black and Blue'' and ``Starmites.''
   ``For a variety of reasons, it's becoming increasingly difficult
to mount a large musical,'' Wachtel said. ``But I do look to the
fact that there were two seasons fairly recently when there was as
many as 20 musicals. You have to be optimistic to be in this
business and we are.''
   Twenty-one plays, including nine revivals, opened on Broadway
during the 1988-89 season. Among the biggest successes were Neil
Simon's farce, ``Rumors,'' and Wendy Wasserstein's ``The Heidi
Chronicles,'' which is the favorite to win the best play Tony on
June 4.
   Box-office receipts also climbed for touring productions in the
United States and Canada, jumping to a record $255 million. It was
a 14 percent increase from the previous season's $223 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
