<FIRST>r i PM-China-Revolution     05-31 0595</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Revolution,0612</SECOND>
<HEAD>Authorities Use Memories of Cultural Revolution to Fight Students
^Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In their gloves-off campaign to end the
pro-democracy movement, authorities are tapping the painful
memories of the chaotic Cultural Revolution to turn public opinion
against the students.
   But students reject any comparison of their campaign with the
ultra-leftist 1966-76 movement, during which the nation was plunged
into turmoil by young Red Guards unleashed by Mao Tse-tung in a
power struggle.
   Conservative leaders including Premier Li Peng and senior leader
Deng Xiaoping in recent days have increased pressure on students to
stop their 6-week-old protests.
   The Communist Party newspaper, the People's Daily, on Tuesday
published a letter from seven unidentified intellectuals who
chillingly warned of a new Cultural Revolution if the protests did
not cease.
   ``Our middle-aged generation who walked away from the Cultural
Revolution purgatory still can painfully and clearly remember the
lawlessness and turmoil of those 10 years,'' they wrote.
   ``The national economy was on the verge of ruin ... there was no
peace in the party, the country or anywhere.''
   ``We ask all comrades who in those 10 years of catastrophic
terror lost loved ones, wasted their youth and suffered hardship to
call on their sense of responsibility to history and society,'' the
letter said. ``Warn your sons and loved ones not to allow a repeat
of this tragedy of history.''
   Chinese in their 30s and older have vivid memories of communist
China's darkest decade, when Mao mobilized millions of youth to
save his revolution from entrenched bureaucrats.
   His Red Guards ruled the streets for two years before the army
was called in to restore order. Gangs of youths tore down temples
and churches, burned books, seized government ministries, ransacked
homes and persecuted intellectuals.
   Estimates of deaths from political turmoil during the decade are
as high as 1 million. Millions more were persecuted and their lives
destroyed.
   Students who have joined this spring's protests are quick to
point that their approach is different.
   This year's demonstrations have been peaceful. Students have
gone out of their way to ensure their marches and sit-ins are
orderly. Beijing's citizens have reacted not with fear but with
heartfelt support, donating money and food to the protesting
students.
   ``We have been calm and orderly,'' said a 22-year-old senior
from Nanjing Polytechnic College. ``If there's turmoil, you can say
it's created by the government.''
   The government cracked down on the protests by declaring martial
law on May 20, but leadership divisions over how to deal with the
students created a bitter power struggle.
   The conservatives appear to have toppled moderate Communist
Party leader Zhao Ziyang, who reportedly is under house arrest. A
diplomatic source says party documents accuse Zhao of helping
incite demonstrations and of using the student movement in a bid to
seize power.
   The student protesters reject comparison to the Red Guards, who
were called to the streets by Mao as his followers.
   ``I think that up to now, our student movement has not been
exploited by anyone,'' said a senior from Puyang Teachers Academy
in Anhui province. He and other students argue their movement is of
the masses, not of a government faction.
   Although all Chinese share horrific memories of the Cultural
Revolution, not all share the concern that history is poised to
repeat itself.
   ``This time the people want democracy,'' said a 41-year-old
mathematics professor from Beijing Normal University who was in
Tiananmen Square to support the students. ``A second Cultural
Revolution can't come. I am not afraid.''
</TEXT>
