<FIRST>r a AM-PipelineExplosion     05-31 0351</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pipeline Explosion,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Loses Bid to Block Resumption of Pipeline Operation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN BERNARDINO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge Tuesday rejected a request
by city officials that he prohibit a pipeline company from resuming
operation of a fuel line that blew up in a deadly fireball last
week.
   City Attorney James Penman said San Bernardino County Superior
Court Judge Ben Kayashima's decision had been expected.
   Penman attorney has unsuccessfully sought to block the Calnev
Pipe Line Co. from resuming pipeline operations or to persuade
Calnev executives to relocate the 14-inch diameter fuel line away
from city residents.
   The devastating explosion, fueled by unleaded gasoline being
pumped through the line, killed two people and injured dozens more
last Thursday.
   A federal investigation into the cause has focused on the
possibility that the pipe was damaged by the wreck of a Southern
Pacific freight train, which derailed in the same area May 12.
   Calnev attorney Charles Diamond said the federal government, not
local government, has sole authority to regulate interstate
commerce, including products shipped by pipeline. Calnev has moved
aggressively to establish federal jurisdiction in the case.
   James J. Manning Jr., another Calnev attorney, told Kayashima
that the fuel company had every intention of abiding by regulations
set by the federal Office of Pipeline Safety. The company will not
open the pipeline without OPS approval, Manning said.
   Penman complained, ``We're having a very difficult time trying
to get Calnev to comply with federal laws and to get OPS to comply
with federal laws.''
   But in issuing his decision, the judge said the 1979 Hazardous
Pipeline Safety Act of 1979 gives the Office of Pipeline Safety
authority to determine pipeline safety.
   In a related development in Los Angeles, Calnev sought a U.S.
District Court order that would effectively force the city to allow
the company to reopen the pipeline in accordance with federal
regulations.
   Over the weekend, Calnev obtained a similar federal order
prohibiting city officials from interfering with the repair and
replacement of the damaged 14-inch diameter pipeline.
   Penman vowed to continue the fight, but conceded the city faces
an uphill battle.
</TEXT>
