<FIRST>r w PM-US-Soviet-Military Bjt   05-31 0770</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Soviet-Military, Bjt,780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Experts Say Soviets Still Understate Military Spending</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN BRUMLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev has
disclosed a level of military spending nearly four times as high as
the Kremlin has admitted in the past, but U.S. analysts say his
estimate is still low though likely to rise as economic reforms
continue in Moscow.
   ``The Gorbachev figure seems quite short,'' said Abraham Becker,
a RAND Corp. analyst who has published numerous studies on Soviet
military spending.
   Another U.S.-based expert on the Soviet economy, Jan Vanous of
Planecon, says Gorbachev's figure is ``kind of low'' and ``raises
more questions than it answers.''
   Gorbachev, in what was hailed in Moscow as a breakthrough for
``glasnost,'' or openness, said the Soviet Union spends 77.3
billion rubles, or $118 billion per year at the rate of exchange
set by the Kremlin, compared with the figure of $32 billion
announced by Soviet officials last October.
   The Central Intelligence Agency estimates Soviet defense
spending at 115 billion rubles to 125 billion rubles, and says that
roughly equals the $300 billion that the Pentagon spends annually,
according to Richard Kaufman, an expert with the Joint Economic
Committee of Congress.
   That committee annually publishes the authoritative U.S.
analysis of the Soviet economy by the CIA and the Pentagon's
Defense Intelligence Agency.
   Converting the ruble figure directly to dollars is virtually
meaningless, the experts said, because the Kremlin uses several
rates of exchange and the Armed Forces have access to materials and
devices that are simply not available to civilian enterprises.
   Moreover, they said, the ruble estimate likely will increase
considerably when the Soviets carry through long-promised changes
in wholesale prices.
   Becker, Vanous and other experts predicted that Gorbachev's
announcement would fuel Soviet discussion on military spending,
producing yet higher estimates and a lively political fight between
reformers and conservatives.
   ``The most important thing about the figure offered by Gorbachev
is not the number itself but the debate that it is going to start
in the Soviet Union,'' said Ed Hewett of the Brookings Institution
in Washington.
   Hewett compared arguments raging over the Soviet spending
deficit, which was disclosed for the first time last October after
the Kremlin for years had claimed to have a balanced budget. Since
last fall, the figure has been revised upward by several noted
Soviet economists, none of whom appear to have definitive figures,
said Hewett.
   Gorbachev did not break down Soviet military spending by
category, and his number did not appear to include research and
development costs, estimated at more than 11 billion rubles by
Vanous.
   The biggest discrepancy, said U.S. analysts, is that Soviet
military prices are based on artificially low production costs
rather than the true market value of goods.
   ``The Soviets have an acute shortage of micro-computers,''
Vanous said by way of example. ``It is impossible to get them in
the civilian sector. If there was a meaningful market, the price
would be quite high.''
   ``The micro-computers that go into MiG (fighters) don't cost
very much, but there are enterprises in the civilian economy that
would be willing to bid five or six times as much'' as the military
pays for them, said Vanous, a Czechoslovakian emigre whose firm
specializes in Soviet Bloc economies.
   The military also consumes expensive metal alloys that simply
are unavailable to the rest of the economy, he said.
   Moreover, there are numerous hidden military costs, such as
armaments sold to client states on favorable terms or the extensive
civil defense system, including hardening of some subway lines
against nuclear attack, which are not included in the defense
budget, said Vanous.
   Gorbachev's ``number makes it clear that the government lied in
the past,'' said Vanous. ``It lied a lot in the past and now it
will lie a little bit. Gorbachev's announcement has legitimized
debate on this issue.''
   Soviet reformers have been pressing the Soviet Defense Ministry
for more than a year to provide a more accurate accounting.
   Gorbachev said defense spending would be cut by 13 percent and
the savings channeled into social services, a course advocated by
the reformers.
   According to the figure provided by Gorbachev, the Soviets spend
about 9 percent of their gross national product on defense. The CIA
estimates that the Soviets spend 15 percent to 17 percent of GNP,
compared with 6 percent for the United States. Because the U.S.
economy is twice as large as that of the Soviet Union, the
superpowers' spending is not far apart, said Kaufman.
   The CIA makes its estimates by observing Soviet military
production and activities, then calculating what they should cost,
said Kaufman.
  
</TEXT>
</DOC>
