<FIRST>r w PM-Bush-Congress     05-31 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-Congress,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democrats Wax Enthusiastic About Bush Arms Overtures</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CONNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic congressional leaders who had
fretted at the slow pace of the new administration's foreign policy
formulation now are singing President Bush's praises for his
initiatives on arms control at the NATO summit.
   What had been a chorus of criticism turned into a crescendo of
applause Tuesday as Bush emerged from Brussels, Belgium, with the
NATO alliance solidly behind the new U.S. proposal on conventional
arms cuts, and united again on short-range nuclear missile strategy.
   ``We may be at an important turning point in history, one in
which the security environment in Europe can be transformed,'' said
Senate Majority Leader George Mitchell of Maine.
   ``The specter of war which has haunted that continent throughout
the 20th century may be receding,'' said Michell, who previously
had criticized Bush as slow to respond to Soviet President Mikhail
Gorbachev's disarmament initiatives.
   ``The president hit all the right chords with his proposals on
conventional arms reductions in Europe,'' said Rep. Les Aspin,
D-Wis., chairman of the House Armed Services Committee.
   Aspin said, ``the agreement seems to guard against
denuclearization of Europe, which was his and (British Prime
Minister) Margaret Thatcher's greatest fear.''
   Aspin, long a watchdog of Pentagon spending, added there could
be ``substantial'' savings for U.S. taxpayers if Bush convinces the
Soviets to buy his plan for deep troop cuts in Europe.
   Senate Armed Services Committee Chairman Sam Nunn, D-Ga., said
Bush's proposal underscores ``the dangerous Soviet conventional
(weapons) advantages'' and gives NATO a ``sound negotiating
position.''
   Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., chairman of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee, said, ``I applaud and very much support the
president's decision to move along this path.''
   ``I trust that this proposal will be approved by our NATO allies
and by the Soviets,'' said Pell.
   Sen. Carl Levin, D-Mich., said Gorbachev and Bush now have
created ``a once-in-a-century opportunity to transform the
East-West security relationship.''
   ``With his latest proposals, the president has shown that he is
convinced that Gorbachev is ready to change the military balance in
Europe, and that he is willing to commit the U.S. to be an active
partner in this process,'' Levin said.
   Sen. Joseph R. Biden Jr., D-Del., chairman of the Foreign
Relations subcommittee on European affairs, said Bush put ``a very
substantive'' conventional arms proposal on the table, along with
``a politically necessary'' nuclear proposal.
   ``He has demonstrated an understanding of the dynamic at work in
NATO in terms of responding to Gorbachev,'' Biden said.
   Moreover, the president has silenced, at least for the moment,
those who criticized his allegedly dilatory start in coming to
grips with the challenge poised by the Gorbachev inititives, Biden
said.
   ``The time had nearly run out and I think he took it right up to
the wire,'' Biden said. ``But I think it's sort of a vindication
for him.''
</TEXT>
