<FIRST>r w PM-UPIAuthor     05-31 0338</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UPI Author,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>UPI Reporter Says He Was Fired For Turning Over Book</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A reporter for United Press International says
he was fired for refusing to let his bosses look at a book he is
writing about the news service.
   ``I'm outraged, but not surprised,'' said Gregory Gordon, who
had been a UPI reporter for nearly 18 years, much of it as the
service's chief investigative reporter.
   ``We asked to see the manuscript, not to censor it,'' said Al
Rossiter Jr., executive editor of UPI. ``He was dismissed because
he refused to assure UPI that the book he is writing about UPI is
beneficial to the company and that it was not a conflict of
interest between him and UPI.''
   Rossiter said a conflict of interest would be if Gordon ``were
writing something derogatory about UPI.''
   Gordon is co-author of the book, ``Down to the Wire,'' with Ron
Cohen, who was fired three years ago as UPI's managing editor. The
book, to be published next January, describes ``the last decade of
UPI's fight for survival,'' Cohen said.
   Gordon said that on his return from his honeymoon in early May,
he was asked the status of the book by Rossiter. A week later, he
said, he received a letter asking either for a review of the
manuscript or ``a written declaration that it contains nothing
derogatory about UPI, its managment or its ownership.''
   Gordon said the news service's managment knew he and Cohen were
writing the book, for which 200 people _ mostly present and former
employees of UPI _ were interviewed.
   ``I told him the book was written by two people who had a
combined 43 years with UPI and we were very sympathetic to the
institution,'' Gordon said. ``He said they needed to see the
manuscript. I told Jim Arnold, senior vice president of UPI, that I
was shocked that a wire service that for years fought for the First
Amendment, would follow such a course.''
</TEXT>
