<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     05-31 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0422</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Now for something completely different: the
pet cockroach.
   Don't reach for the insectide, said Gene Alford, a salesman at
Critter Shop. This isn't the kind of roach you want to stomp.
   The Madagascar Hissing Roach, 2{ to 3 inches long, hisses like
an aerosol can and will frolic on an owner's arm or shoulder, said
Alford, who's asking for $6 a bug.
   ``Most people that have exotic tastes want something clean, not
too much cleanup, easy maintenance, and it is a conversation
piece,'' Alford said. The homely pets have sold well since going on
the market in January, he said. Some people think of them as trendy.
   ``It depends on the individual's taste,'' Alford said.
   One customer watching Alford stroke one of the little arthropods
was unwilling to join the trend.
   ``I've had enough of roaches,'' she said.
   The exotic pet shop has sold six of the 12 roaches it bought
from the Southeast Reptile Exchange Inc., a local wholesaler,
Alford said.
   The roaches are bred in zoos and generally used as food for
reptiles.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A model of the multimillion-dollar monument
designed to symbolize Los Angeles was ridiculed when it was
unveiled six months ago, but it got a warmer reception up north.
   The ``Steel Cloud'' model has been on display in San Francisco.
   ``I really hope it gets built,'' said San Francisco architect
Michael Harris.
   The model is a replica of the $33 million project backers hope
will span over the Hollywood Freeway as Los Angeles' answer to the
Statue of Liberty.
   The conglomeration of structures would house museums, gigantic
aquariums, theaters and eateries. It would be propped up on a grid
of exposed steel beams.
   Some critics of the project say it looks like the ruins left by
an earthquake, but supporters say the design is gaining acclaim.
   ``To me it symbolizes the openness of L.A.,'' said architect
Mark Horton, a director of the Art &amp; Architecture Exhibition Space,
where the model is on display.
   ``We've been moving very fast,'' said Nick Patsaouras, chairman
of the privately funded West Coast Gateway Committee, which is
trying to get the project literally off the ground.
   ``People have begun to take the work more seriously,'' said
architect Hani Rashid, the 30-year-old New Yorker who designed the
monument. ``It's not so much a one-liner joke any more.''
</TEXT>
