<DOCNO> AP890531-0033 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 0241EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BoxOffice     05-31 0757</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Box Office,0782</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Indiana Jones' Reaches Pinnacle of Box-Office Success</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Indiana Jones liberated the Holy Grail from the
Nazis and delivered a treasure to box offices across the country: a
record $46.9 million in ticket sales in its first six days.
   ``Indiana Jones and The Last Crusade,'' the third and presumably
final installment in the adventures of Steven Spielberg's
archaeologist, also toppled records for week, weekend and
single-day admissions, according to figures released Tuesday.
   ``It's been fantastic,'' said George Pappas, assistant manager
of downtown Philadelphia's Sameric 4. ``On opening day, we had
people lining up at 8:30 a.m. for the 8 p.m. show. First time I've
ever seen that for a movie.''
   ``I haven't been home since last Wednesday,'' when the
consistently sold-out show opened, said John Pellegrino, manager of
the Loews 34th Street Showplace in New York
   Russell Duncan, regional marketing manager for General Cinema
Theaters in Chicago, said ``The Last Crusade'' was going ``like
gangbusters _ they love it.'' It was being shown in 11 of the
company's area theaters.
   ``The Last Crusade,'' which opened May 24 on 2,327 screens, set
a mark for the largest single-day gate in movie history, selling
$11.2 million in admissions on Saturday alone. For the four-day
Memorial Day weekend, it grossed $37 million.
   By comparison, last year's mega-hit ``Rain Man'' collected $7
million in its opening three-day weekend.
   The previous six-day record-holder, Paramount's ``Indiana Jones
and the Temple of Doom,'' gathered $42.3 million in 1984 and drew
$45.7 million for its first full week, also the previous mark.
   The former single-day mark was held by Paramount's 1987 hit
``Beverly Hills Cop II,'' which sold $9.7 million its first
Saturday and $33 million in its opening four-day weekend.
   ``See No Evil, Hear No Evil'' took second on last weekend's
box-office charts with $6.1 million, followed by ``Field of
Dreams'' in third with $5.7 million and ``Road House'' in fourth
with $5 million, according to Exhibitor Relations Co.
   In fifth place was the most immediate victim of ``The Last
Crusade'' assault, Clint Eastwood's new movie ``Pink Cadillac,''
which opened last weekend with $4.4 million.
   In sixth was ``K-9'' with $3.1 million, ``Pet Sematary'' in
seventh with $2.6 million, ``Major League'' in eighth with $1.4
million.
   The Oscar-favorite ``Rain Man'' finished in ninth with $1.2
million, bringing its box-office receipts to $165.3 million after
24 weeks. ``Scandal'' finished in 10th with $1 million.
   ``The Last Crusade's'' fortunes were boosted by a barrage of
holiday vacationers and higher ticket prices in many of the
country's movie houses. In Los Angeles, for example, some theaters
charged $7, a dollar more than usual.
   No matter how high the price or how long the wait, audiences
were determined to see Harrison Ford's Indy save the Holy Grail _
said to be the chalice used by Jesus at the Last Supper _ from the
Nazis.
   At theaters in Westwood near the University of California-Los
Angeles, lines for ``The Last Crusade'' snaked around the block
throughout the weekend. At the Mann Alex theater in nearby
Glendale, the flood of fans drained the concessions stand of ice,
hot dog buns and change. The wait for late-night screenings in
suburban theaters approached an hour.
   Audiences at some theaters cheered even the movie's opening
credits, greeted Ford's first appearance with whoops of joy and
heartily applauded the introduction of co-star Sean Connery, who
portrayed Indiana's father.
   At the AMC Walnut Mall 3 in Philadelphia, extra midnight shows
were added.
   ``We turned people away from every show,'' said manager Tracey
Scott-Hall. ``It's been sold out since last Wednesday.''
   ``It's just an extraordinary accomplishment for the movie,''
said Barry London, president of Paramount's motion picture group,
which produced ``The Last Crusade.'' ``People were just having a
great time with the movie.''
   The phenomenal opening for ``The Last Crusade'' gives Paramount
early control of this summer's box-office sweepstakes, considered
the most competitive in movie history. To capitalize on the
weekend's packed houses, Paramount attached preview trailers for
its upcoming ``Star Trek V'' and ``Black Rain'' to ``The Last
Crusade'' prints.
   Forty percent of all movie grosses usually come between Memorial
Day and Labor Day. Last summer's season was worth $1.6 billion, and
this summer is seen as potentially even more lucrative.
Expectations are high for ``Ghostbusters II,'' opening June 16;
``Batman,'' opening June 23; and ``The Abyss,'' coming July 19.
   ``The Last Crusade'' is being advertised as the final Indiana
Jones chapter. ``As far as we know, it's still the last movie,''
London said.
</TEXT>
