<HEAD>Cost of New Medical Technologies To Be Considered</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The cost of increasingly expensive new medical
technologies must be balanced by insurers against the potential
health benefits, says a study by a leading health maintenance
organization.
   ``Even when it is established that a new, more expensive therapy
is better than the existing alternatives, one must question whether
the added benefit is worth the added cost,'' concluded the report
released Tuesday by the Harvard Community Health Plan, the oldest
and largest HMO in New England.
   The study said new technologies must be investigated to see if
they improve health care.
