<FIRST>r a PM-MarineCrash-Hawaii     05-31 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Marine Crash-Hawaii,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>News of Helicopter Crash Hits Hard at Hawaii Base</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Marine Crash</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRUCE DUNFORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fellow Marines and relatives waited anxiously
for news of the 14 men missing after a helicopter crash during a
training mission off Okinawa.
   ``There is a great somberness and pain with reports of the
tragedy or possible tragedy. We are fearful and concerned,'' said
Navy Capt. Herbert Bergsma, chaplin at Kaneohe Marine Corps Air
Station.
   A Kaneohe-based CH-46 Sea Knight helicopter with 22 Marines
crashed into the sea Tuesday night after taking off from the USS
Denver off Okinawa, Japan. Eight Marines were rescued, including
four who were injured. A search was continuing for the missing,
whose names have not been released.
   A special hotline number was set up for Marine families to call,
but they are told only if their relative was not involved,
officials said. The families of the missing were being notified
individually.
   Nancy O'Donnell, ombudsman for the 3rd Marine Regiment, was
fielding telephone calls from servicemen's wives.
   ``I hear anxiety in their voices. Some are in tears. They want
to know right now'' if their husband is among the missing, said
Mrs. O'Donnell, whose husband, Sgt. Kevin O'Donnell, is in Okinawa
but was not involved in the accident.
   The helicopter was carrying a crew of four assigned to Kaneohe's
Aircraft Group 24, and 18 passengers from the 3rd Marine Regiment.
The base is located 10 miles from Honolulu on Oahu island.
   The two units were on a six-month deployment to the western
Pacific for training.
   ``It affected two of our major subordinate commands ... so we're
very concerned,'' said Maj. Kerry K. Gershanek, the base public
affairs officer.
   While the search was the priority at the scene of the accident,
``here our first priority is to make sure our families are taken
care of,'' Gershanek said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890531-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 0348EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DukakisAd Bjt   05-31 0704</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dukakis Ad, Bjt,0729</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ad Lampoons the Latest in Dukakis Bashing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONNI EFRON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America hates a loser, and no politician seems
more scorned these days than Michael Dukakis.
   The failed Democratic presidential candidate is the butt of
jokes in his home state. Question: ``What does Dukakis mean in
Greek?'' Answer: ``Mondale.''
   The Massachusetts governor also is facing a huge state budget
deficit, a cranky Legislature, a wife recovering from alcoholism
and the lowest popularity ratings of his career.
   When his car was stopped for an expired registration sticker
recently, his driver was given a warning instead of the usual $50
fine. A radio station sold cardboard cutouts of Dukakis, saying
ordinary people could avoid tickets, too, if only they had a
governor in the back seat.
   Now, a California company has started an advertisement showing a
photo of Dukakis giving a speech. ``There are some people even we
couldn't make more persuasive'' reads the huge caption.
   Fortune magazine declined to run the ad by Precision
Technologies Inc., but the two-page spread appears in the latest
California editions of Newsweek and Inc. magazines.
   The creators insist the ad isn't meant to demean Dukakis.
   In fact, the two people who came up with the idea supported him
in his bid for the White House, and one even campaigned for him,
said Ken Mandelbaum of the Mandelbaum Mooney Ashley advertising
agency in San Francisco.
   But lest the ad be overlooked, the year-old agency that has also
made controversial ads showing nudists and underwear sent a copy of
its Dukakis piece to news organizations.
   A spokesman for the governor said the unauthorized use of
Dukakis' photograph to sell a product ``shows a lack of common
sense and decency.''
   The ad pushes a product that can make a photographic slide from
the image on the screen of a personal computer.
   ``It's something that will allow anyone to make more persuasive
presentations,'' the text reads.
   ``We were sitting around talking about who was a poor presenter,
who couldn't get his points across, and Dukakis was the guy who
leapt into mind,'' Mandelbaum said.
   The only other candidate considered was Neville Chamberlain, the
British prime minister remembered for his appeasement of Adolf
Hitler. But they decided few people would recognize Chamberlain,
Mandelbaum said.
   Dukakis was in Toronto on Tuesday and could not be reached for
comment. But Donald K. Stern, the governor's chief legal counsel,
said Massachusetts law prohibits use of a person's photograph for
advertising or commercial purposes without their consent.
   ``That law reflects common sense and decency,'' Stern said.
``One would hope that any company would show restraint in using
someone's likeness for commercial purposes and that any magazine
would take steps to determine whether consent has been given before
they ran it.''
   Mandelbaum said there had been some debate about the legality of
using the photograph.
   ``I think the company looked at the risks and accepted them,''
he said.
   Fortune spokesman Gary Belis said the magazine would not discuss
its reasons for rejecting the ad.
   Hank Thunhorst, national advertising manager for Inc., said he
didn't think the ad was derogatory, just trying to make a point.
   ``In the past, advertisers have used pictures of presidents that
were derogatory,'' Thunhorst said. ``They flayed Nixon pretty
good.''
   Cambridge pollster Gerry Chervinsky called the ad demeaning.
``That, after all, was the knock on Dukakis, that he was a poor
campaigner who couldn't get the message across,'' he said.
   Chervinsky's polls of Massachusetts voters last month show that
53 percent have an unfavorable view of Dukakis, and 41 percent have
a favorable view. A national survey in early April showed 39
percent rated Dukakis unfavorable and 44 percent favorable, he said.
   ``In Massachusetts there's a tremendous amount of Duke-bashing
going on,'' he said. ``Nationally, there was some lessening of
derision, because it's basically out of sight, out of mind.''
   Chervinsky said the public is used to having political figures
lampooned.
   ``It's sort of a sad commentary,'' Chervinsky said. ``If it's OK
to bash Dan Quayle, the incumbent vice president, nightly, as he is
bashed, then I guess it's OK to bash the loser.
   ``But to me it's like, leave the poor guy alone already.''
</TEXT>
