<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 0354EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Panama     05-31 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Panama,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Claims Regime is Holding 89 Political Prisoners</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD HERZFELDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The opposition says the regime of
Gen. Manuel Antonio Noreiga is holding at least 89 political
prisoners.
   ``The prisoners are nothing more than hostages,'' opposition
presidential candidate Guillermo Endara said in an interview
Tuesday.
   The Panamanian Defense Forces commanded by Noriega ``take people
prisoner for a while and then, if things are quiet, they just let
them go,'' he said. ``They take people off the street, people who
were just watching a parade.''
   The opposition charges were the latest following the May 7
presidential election, which the government nullified three days
later. International observers said the opposition, led by Endara,
won the election by a 3-1 margin.
   The Organization of American States has criticized Noriega, the
vote nullification and the beating of Endara and two other
opposition candidates.
   Opposition first vice presidential candidate Ricardo Arias
Calderon said six people arrested May 24 while marching with
opposition candidates to an OAS delegation meeting ``have not even
been allowed to see their families.''
   At a news conference, Arias Calderon distributed a list of 89
people he said were political prisoners. It included opposition
spokesman Luis Martins; legislative candidate Felipe Escobar;
Antonio Galvez, Arias Calderon's bodyguard; and Jose Guillermo
Lutrel, a Panamanian Human Rights Committee election observer.
   Many prisoners were accused of threatening state security and
sentenced to a year in jail the night of their arrest, Arias
Calderon said.
   He said such sentences often are converted into fines payable at
the rate of $1 a day but inmates' relatives were told nobody is
available to collect fines.
   Messages left for a Defense Forces spokesman for comment on
Arias Calderon's charges were not returned. The Defense Forces have
not commented on the issue despite repeated requests.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
