<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     05-31 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Stocks Rebound, U.S. Dollar Off Against Yen</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The key index on the Tokyo Stock Exchange bounced
back Wednesday, while the U.S. dollar edged down against the
Japanese yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 83.94-point
loser the previous day, regained 189.86 points, or 0.56 percent, to
end trading at 34,266.75 points.
   The dollar finished at 142.70 yen, down 0.40 yen from Tuesday's
close of 143.10 yen. The currency moved between 142.43 yen and
142.90 yen.
   Traders said the dollar eased as market players sold it to buy
European currencies due to speculation that Britain might raise its
discount rate, following a similar move by Japan.
   The Bank of Japan announced Tuesday that it will raise its
official discount rate by 0.75 percentage point to 3.25 percent
effective Wednesday, reversing its easy money policy for the first
time in nine years.
   ``The discount rate hike in Japan has little impact on foreign
exchange dealings because it has been expected for over a month,''
said a trader with a major commercial bank.
   Speculative investors' demands for the U.S. currency remained
strong, he said.
   Analysts say President Bush's pledge for a 20 percent cut in
U.S. military forces stationed in Europe boosted the dollar because
people expected the move would help reduce the U.S. budget deficit.
   On the stock exchange, dealers said the index's recovery was
spurred by the yen's rebound on the currency exchange.
   But trading was directionless, said an analyst with Nomura
Securities, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   ``The energy of the market has been low due to uncertainties
over the political situation and in the currency market, resulting
in thin, directionless trading recently,'' he said.
   ``The strong yen has long been a merit in stock trading, but now
its stability should be considered more than its level,'' the
analyst added.
   Some participants remained on the sidelines due to concerns over
a West German federal bank meeting Thursday, where market players
speculate the West German interest rate might be raised again, he
said.
</TEXT>
