<FIRST>r i PM-Israel-Victim 1stLd-Writethru a0426 05-31 0821</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Victim, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0426,0844</SECOND>
<HEAD>500th Palestinian Victim: Girl of 13 Who Wanted to be a Doctor</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: To UPDATE with report of six suspects detained, SUB three grafs
for 7th, `Twenty seminary ...' Picks up 8th pvs, ``Two students ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALLYN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KIFIL HARITH, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ibtisam Bozieh woke from
a nap and peered through the green shutter when the Jewish settlers
began shooting. The shy 13-year-old had wanted to be a doctor, but
she became a martyr instead.
   Ibtisam was the 500th Palestinian victim in nearly 18 months of
rebellion against Israeli rule in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   There was a single bullet hole in the shutter Tuesday. Members
of her family said Ibtisam, ever inquisitive, looked out at the
settlers shooting wildly in her farming village the day before and
a bullet hit her in the chest.
   Israeli media called it one of the worst vigilante attacks of
the uprising, in which 22 Israelis also have been killed. Defense
Minister Yitzhak Rabin said the raid was ``a shameful act.''
   About two dozen Jewish settlers set a wheat field and part of a
house ablaze in Kifil Harith, smashed windows in a car and a truck,
and shot up several rooftop water tanks.
   Villagers said an elderly man was struck in the face with a gun
and an 18-year-old was shot in the stomach. Police confirmed two
people were wounded.
   Northern police commander Albert Musafi said on army radio today
that six suspects were detained and being questioned. He declined
to elaborate.
   Two Israeli newspapers, Hadashot and Maariv, said the suspects
were students at Joseph's Tomb Yeshiva in Nablus, 12 miles away.
The Haaretz daily said some lived in the Yizhar settlement next to
Nablus and that more arrests were expected.
   Israel radio said 20 of the seminary students were questioned
about the case on Tuesday and that their rifles were taken for
ballistic tests.
   Two students said on the radio they were hiking through the
village to Joshua's tomb and fired their guns in response to a
stoning attack. The Boziehs live about 50 yards from the
white-domed monument at the biblical prophet's burial site.
   Gadi Ben-Zimra, one of the students, said: ``Our intention was
to hike. There was no punishment mission here. Very close to the
village, we were met with a barrage of stones and rocks.
   ``We were surrounded and, from that moment on, our lives were in
real danger. Stones and rocks were flying from the houses. ... What
we did, I mostly talk of myself, was to fire in the air only.''
   Media reports suggested the assault on Kifil Harith was linked
to a stoning attack Monday in which Yitzhak Ginzburg, the yeshiva's
rabbi, was struck in the head during a hike with students to Sinjil
village.
   Haim Malka, a West Bank police commander, said on army radio
that Jewish settlers set fires and began shooting before entering
Kifil Harith.
   A senior military commander told the daily Maariv the raid was
of unprecedented severity and the settlers ``shot like madmen.''
   It was the latest of several reprisal raids on Palestinian
villages and neighborhoods after stoning attacks on settlers.
Israeli civilians have killed 18 Palestinians since the uprising
began Dec. 8, 1987.
   Hussein Ahmed Hassan of Kifil Harith said some raiders wore the
skullcaps of religious Jews.
   ``There were about 30 of them who came through here with guns,
throwing firebombs,'' he said. ``They burned our wheat and shouted
things in Hebrew we couldn't understand.''
   Her village of 3,000 people has transformed Ibtisam Bozieh from
a soft-spoken schoolgirl to a symbol of resistance to Israeli
occupation.
   Palestinian flags of green, black, red and white _ declared
illegal by Israel _ were unfurled Tuesday on the roof of the small
stone house where she lived with her family.
   Children led by two men masked with red-checked Arab headdresses
shouted: ``With blood and fire we will redeem Palestine!''
   Inside, several dozen women in white veils sat in mourning on
the floors. Ibtisam's teacher, Subhia Abdel Salah, showed a
reporter the girl's workbooks from English class and said her
favorite subjects were English and science.
   ``She was very clever, always at the top of her class,'' said
the teacher, sitting in the living room not far from the green
shutter with the single bullet hole.
   ``All she wanted to be was a doctor,'' said Ibtisam's mother,
Samia Jamil Salem Bozieh, 46, who wore a white headscarf and a
faded dress with a floral pattern.
   She said her daughter was awakened by the shots and went to the
window.
   ``Next thing, she stumbled into the corridor and said `Mommy, I
have been shot here,''' Mrs. Bozieh said, holding both hands over
her heart. ``Then she fell dead.''
   The Boziehs have 11 other children. One of them, Ibtisam's
18-year-old sister, Hanan, said, ``It is good to die for your
country.''
</TEXT>
