<FIRST>r i PM-Hungary     05-31 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hungary,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist Leaders Pronounce Uprising Leader's Execution Illegal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALEX BANDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Communist leaders have agreed that Imre
Nagy, leader of the 1956 anti-Soviet uprising, was illegally
executed two years later after being convicted of
counterrevolution, a party spokesman said.
   After Tuesday's announcement, however, Communist Party chief
Karoly Grosz said that while he did not oppose Nagy's legal
rehabilitation he was opposed to blaming the party for the
premier's execution.
   Nagy had called for open, multiparty elections before the
short-lived revolt was crushed by Soviet tanks.
   Reformers within the ruling Communist Party have backed calls
for Nagy's rehabilitation as the country moves toward a multiparty
political system.
   Also during its meeting Monday, the party's policy-setting
Central Committee decided to move up to the fall a party congress
that had been scheduled for 1990.
   The committee agreed that ``there is every indication'' that
Nagy ``was executed in the wake of a show trial and that his
sentence was a violation of the law,'' party spokesman Laszlo Major
told reporters.
   In a later television interview, Grosz claimed no part of the
ruling Communist Party had taken a position on Nagy's guilt or
innocence.
   ``Those returning the verdict were obviously influenced by other
forces'' he did not identify. ``The sentence was not a (party)
decision.''
   Major said there had been ``considerable debate'' during
Monday's session on Nagy, and the Central Committee agreed it
cannot come to a final decision, because documents are still
missing and a judicial review is still in progress.
   Major told reporters, ``Several Central Committee members
pointed out that Nagy died a committed communist.''
   The party's admission came as no surprise in the wake of a
public debate over Nagy's 1958 execution and burial in an unmarked
grave. On June 16, the remains of Nagy and some of his associates
are to be reburied.
   Major said the party would like the day to be one of national
reconciliation but said it plan to be represented at the reburial
since it was not invited. The event is to be televised to the
nation.
   Laszlo Domonkos, a deputy department head of the Central
Committee, said Tuesday that the date of Hungary's first multiparty
elections _ promised by Communist authorities _ depends on talks
with opposition groups,.
   The talks have been delayed by disagreements over the makeup of
negotiating teams and the agenda.
   Also Tuesday, two Central Committee members stepped down, the
party said in a communique. The two _ Mihaly Korom and Sandor
Rajnai, the current ambassador to Moscow, were both involved in the
Nagy case as Interior Ministry officials, say relatives of Nagy and
other victims of the post-revolt crackdown.
</TEXT>
