<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Milanov     05-31 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Milanov,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zinka Milanov, Soprano At Metropolitan Opera, Dies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Zinka Milanov, a leading dramatic soprano for
the Metropolitan Opera for 28 years until her retirement in 1966,
has died. She was 83.
   Ms. Milanov died Tuesday at Lenox Hill Hospital after suffering
a stroke, according to Anne Werner, a hospital spokeswoman. The
Manhattan resident had been admitted to the hospital Saturday, Ms.
Werner said.
   Ms. Milanov was born in Zagreb, Yugoslavia, on May 17, 1906. She
studied in Zagreb, Milan and Berlin, and debuted at the Zagreb
Opera in Verdi's ``Il Trovatore'' in 1927.
   After nine years with that company, she began singing for the
Vienna State Opera, where she appeared in the Italian repertory.
Her reputation spread throughout Europe with guest appearances in
Germany, Czechoslovakia and at the Salzburg Festival, where in 1937
she was chosen by Arturo Toscanini as soloist in Verdi's
``Requiem.''
   That year, she made her U.S. debut at the Metropolitan Opera as
Leonora in ``Il Trovatore.''
   She sang more than 400 performances with the Met until retiring
at age 59. She was one of the few principal singers to inaugurate
two successive seasons for the company _ in 1951 and 1952.
   She enjoyed a successful concert career and recorded widely in
the Italian repertoire, especially works by Verdi and Puccini.
   She was most noted for the roles of Aida in the Verdi opera and
Desdemona in Verdi's ``Otello.''
   Born Zinka Kunc, her first marriage, to Predag Milanov, ended in
divorce. She is survived by her second husband, Ljubomir Ilic.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
