<DOCNO> AP890531-0054 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 0426EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Markets     05-31 0317</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0328</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Off Against Yen, Stocks Up Sharply</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar lost ground today against the
Japanese yen in Tokyo as stock prices rose sharply.
   The 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which fell 83.94 points
Tuesday, gained 189.86 points or 0.56 percent to end trading at
34,266.75, a record high.
   The dollar closed at 142.70 yen, down 0.40 yen from Tuesday's
close of 143.10 yen. The U.S. currency opened lower at 142.50 yen
and ranged from 142.43 to 142.90 yen during the day.
   Traders attributed the dollar's slip to a similar down-swing in
New York Tuesday.
   ``Trading was inactive, with market players only making position
adjustments at around 142.70 yen because of the absence of
market-affecting news,'' said a trader with the Bank of Tokyo, who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The expected meeting of the West German Bundesbank later today
and release of U.S. unemployment figures for May on Friday made
some investors stay on the sidelines, he said.
   Market players and news reports speculated that West German
monetary authorities may decide at the meeting to raise the central
bank's discount rate.
   The trader said the rise in Japan's official discount rate had
no major impact on the market. The Bank of Japan raised its key
rate today by 0.75 percentage points to 3.25 percent.
   On the stock market, high-tech issues attracted participants and
contributed to the sharp rise in the Nikkei index, said Kazuhiro
Nomura of New Japan Securities.
   ``Market players also were reassured by the apparent
stabilization of the yen-dollar exchange rate,'' he said.
   ``People tend to pay too much attention to the rate itself but
the market has come to consider it satisfactory as long as the rate
is stable,'' Nomura said.
   Trading was active, with volume on the market's first section
estimated at 1 billion shares. Technology issues including Sony and
Toshiba attracted buyers, as did automobile issues.
</TEXT>
