<FIRST>r i PM-Argentina-Looting     05-31 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Argentina-Looting,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shopkeepers Defend Their Shops Against Looters</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Argentina, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VICENTE L. PANETTA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROSARIO, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As about 100 looters _ men, women and
children _ descended on Julio Bidalle's store, the five policemen
assigned to guard it were helpless.
   Very soon, it was empty of meat, vegetables and fruit, wine and
cheese. The raiders Tuesday even took the cleaning prducts.
   ``This ruins me,'' Bidalle said.
   Vicente Senes, who owns a neighborhood grocery, said he would
help guard his store. ``I don't have any alternative,''
   Senes said as he and other grocery store and butcher shop owners
tried to protect themselves from looting that began a week ago
because of raging inflation and economic chaos in Argentina.
   A heavy metal shutter protecting the front of one store carried
a warning: ``Danger. Door Electrified.''
   Despite a state of siege declared Monday by President Raul
Alfonsin, sporadic looting continued Tuesday in Rosario, a
meat-packing city of 1 million people about 185 miles north of
Buenos Aires.
   Santa Fe provincial police reinforced by members of the
paramilitary border force guarded shops and patrolled streets.
Little public transport was running and schools, closed Monday, did
not reopen.
   Police reported at least six people killed, 70 injured and about
1,000 arrested.
   Many supermarkets were stripped Monday, particularly those near
slum districts. Most of the looters were women, children and
teen-agers.
   The manager of one supermarket said some people ``fought for a
piece of meat or a bag of mate,'' the herbal tea that is a staple
in Argentina. ``They looked like hungry poor people, but there also
were thieves who took advantage of the situation,'' he said.
   One woman in her 70s, rushing out of a food market with a bag of
groceries, shouted: ``Thank God, today I can eat!''
   Crowds gathered around many neighborhood stores Tuesday, but
guards generally were able to hold them back with shields and
truncheons.
   Daniel Rodriguez said his small market four miles from downtown
Rosario was raided three times Monday. Fifty border guards
surrounded it Tuesday morning.
   If the looting continues, Rodriguez said, ``I have two
alternatives: I can put the little I have left in the street and
give it away or I can just set fire to it all.''
   He said he opened the store two years ago ``with four cans of
preserves.''
   ``I was successful, but now what do I do?'' he said. About 100
people, most of them poorly dressed women and children, milled
around in the street beyond the ring of guards.
   Cmdr. Cesar Valdez, in charge of the guards, said he had orders
to hold off looters with tear gas or rubber bullets, ``but we are
afraid to shoot because many women have children in their arms.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
