<DOCNO> AP890531-0056 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 0532EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CambodiaArms     05-31 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia Arms,0435</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: U.S. Wants to Aid Non-Communist Guerrillas In Cambodia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration wants Congress to
support a covert supply of weapons to non-communist guerrillas
fighting Cambodia's Vietnam-backed government, The New York Times
reported today.
   The aid would be used to strengthen Prince Norodom Sihanouk's
position in negotiations with the Phnom Penh government and with
the communist Khmer Rouge forces. The newspaper attributed the
report to unidentified Bush administration officials.
   Earlier this month, the prince indicated he might be able to
reach an accommodation with the Phnom Penh government under certain
conditions.
   The Times quoted a State Department official as saying, ``We
believe that appropriate assistance will strengthen the political
standing and security of the non-Communist resistance and enhance
its position'' in negotiations for a political settlement of the
war in Cambodia.
   The official said such aid would help the non-communist force
hold its own if the Khmer Rouge tried to seize control.
   Sen. Claiborne Pell, D-R.I., said he had not been notified of
any new administration initiative on Cambodia.
   ``Their policy always was that they wanted to give lethal aid to
the Sihanouk'' forces, the Senate Foreign Relations Committee
chairman said in a telephone interview Tuesday night with The
Associated Press.
   Pell said such aid was included in an administration bill, but
he was not sure of its status and added that the administration has
not pushed for the aid.
   Pell was among three senators who wrote Bush last weekend
opposing lethal aid to Sihanouk's forces on grounds it may fall
into the hands of the Khmer Rouge.
   ``My view is that would be a major error unless there is
specific language that it not go to the Khmer Rouge,'' Pell said
when asked what his reaction would be to such a proposal from the
administration.
   The Khmer Rouge, led by Pol Pot, ruled the Southeast Asian
country from 1975 through 1978, and presided over the period in
which 1 million Cambodians died.
   A State Department official who refused to be identified would
not be specific when asked whether the administration would seek
congressional backing for lethal aid to the non-Communist forces.
   ``It's our policy to do what we can do to strengthen the
non-communist resistance,'' the official told the AP. ``We believe
that by doing so they will be better able to play the essential
political role which will be required if there is to be a
comprehensive political settlement in Cambodia. And such a
settlement is the best way of controlling the Khmer Rouge.''
</TEXT>
