<FIRST>r a PM-Custody-Race     05-31 0393</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Custody-Race,0411</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Rules Black Child Should Remain With White Family</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal appeals court has ruled that a
5-year-old black child should remain with his white foster parents,
ending a three-year custody fight with the boy's black former
guardians.
   The Rev. Willie Williams, who had custody of Raymond Bullard
between 1985 and 1988, said he and his wife, Elaine, will not
appeal Tuesday's decision by the 3rd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals.
   ``Our family has suffered greatly,'' Williams said. ``I don't
want to keep dragging it on and on and on.''
   Williams said he has declined to see the child during the appeal
for fear of confusing him and would continue that to help the
youngster adjust to the home of John and Marilyn McLaughlin. The
boy turns 6 on June 25.
   Michael Churchill, the McLaughlins' attorney, said his clients
are hopeful ``that a long nightmare is over.''
   ``I'm very happy,'' said Mrs. McLaughlin. ``Hopefully it's
over.''
   When he was a few months old in October 1983, Raymond was placed
with the McLaughlins for what was supposed to be six months. But
his mother, who had emotional problems, was deemed not ready to
resume caring for the child at the end of the period, and Raymond
remained with the McLaughlin family.
   At age 2, he was moved to the Williams' home under a city policy
that tries to match children with culturally similar foster parents.
   The McLaughlins challenged the policy. In August, a federal
court ordered the child returned to their custody, ruling the
Constitution prevented agencies from using race as the sole reason
to remove a child from a foster home.
   The Williamses appealed the case.
   A three-judge panel ruled Tuesday that while the Williamses have
been ``superb foster parents,'' a return to the McLaughlins offered
Raymond ``the best hope of realizing his full potential.''
   A report from Dr. Eileen A. Bazelon, a psychiatrist chosen by
the city to examine Raymond while he lived with each family, said
Raymond had suffered depression and developmental problems after
leaving the McLaughlins.
   Churchill said the decision set an important precedent.
   ``This confirms that the city was wrong to remove the child on
the basis of race _ that what's most important is the child's
needs,'' Churchill said. ``We believe that it's the right decision
and should have nationwide impact.''
</TEXT>
