<FIRST>r i PM-China-Nightlife     05-31 0650</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Nightlife,0675</SECOND>
<HEAD>Students Sing, Dance the Nights Away at Tiananmen</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRIL JONES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tiananmen Square, a raucous rallying point for
students demanding democratic rights by day, at night becomes a
carnival ground of concerts, dancing and exotic food.
   While thousands of students camped out on the square doze in
rickety huts, night owls sing folk songs and dance to tinny sounds
from portable cassette players.
   Some sing Chinese ballads or hearty renditions of Lionel Richie
and John Denver. Others croon Peter, Paul and Mary, sometimes in
English, sometimes in Chinese.
   One night last week students held a talent show, including
serenaders and an amateur stand-up comic. Another night there was a
huge rock concert, with 10,000 fans clustered around the base of
the Monument to the People's Heroes as popular Chinese singers took
turns at the mike.
   ``I've been coming out here since the protests began,'' said
guitar strummer Cai Wei, a 22-year-old student at the Central
Academy of Fine Arts. ``The students on the square are exhausted,
so I try to provide some atmosphere for them.''
   Cai, clad only in a loose green shirt and smudged red shorts,
sings folk songs from the provinces, such as the tragicomic tale of
a man with a bad leg:
   ``For the revolution, for the party
   ``The cripple joined the army,
   ``For the revolution, for the party
   ``The cripple died for the army.''
   Traditional and romantic numbers are in. Jabs at unpopular
leaders are not.
   Unlike the strident chants of millions of protesters in the last
two weeks taunting Premier Li Peng and questioning the mental
competence of aging senior leader Deng Xiaoping, the balladeers
don't poke fun at their enemies.
   ``We're not here to insult anybody, we're seeking political
reforms,'' said a student from Beijing Normal University who gave
her name only as Liu.
   She was singing with about 20 other colleagues outside a
clumsily built tent at 4:00 a.m.
   A few couples stroll arm-in-arm under a crescent moon in the
vast expanse sweeping southward from the Forbidden City, where
China's emperors once lived, though Tiananmen has hardly become a
lover's lane.
   Some slow dance at the mini-dances that spring up spontaneously,
swaying to drippy instrumental tunes from cassette players set on
the ground.
   With sundown, the avenues bordering the square fill with vendors
of barbecued mutton, onion pancakes, dumpling soup and noodles
stretched from dough as you watch.
   But most of the food goes to curious residents of the capital
who come to Tiananmen at night for a moonlit glimpse at the
revolution, which began May 13 with a hunger strike by some 3,000
students and swelled to more than 200,000 before tapering off.
   The students, many from outlying provinces and most of them
broke, rely on donations for their meals, usually a couple of buns
twice a day, sometimes with rice porridge and a bottle of chalky
soda pop.
   ``Look how cracked my lips are,'' said a rower from Beijing
Physical Education University. ``I collapsed once during the hunger
strike. What's hardest is keeping up our strength.''
   It's easier to stay up all night because of the cold, the rower
said. ``If I sleep at night I get the chills,'' he said, squatting
on a thick cotton jacket on Tiananmen's concrete pavement.
   Overnight temperatures drop to 52 degrees.
   The food situation has improved lately, said Chen Shounan of
Anhui Industry Institute: ``The last couple of days we each got an
egg with our meals.''
   The lamps glowing in the square go out around 5:15 a.m. and the
nights wind down with the raising of the national flag by a
People's Liberation Army honor guard at sunrise.
   ``You see, we are a patriotic movement, nothing more,'' said a
Beijing Agricultural Institute coed who stayed up to join about 100
others and applaud the flag-raising. ``I may lose sleep, but it's
worth it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890531-0059 </DOCNO>
