<FIRST>r a PM-Mutilation     05-31 0626</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mutilation,0646</SECOND>
<HEAD>Calls for Death Penalty Punctuate Community Meeting on Mutilation
Case</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents in 4th graf.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM KLASS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of people cheered at calls for
swift, sure and lengthy imprisonment for sex offenders at a meeting
prompted by the rape and mutilation of a young boy.
   ``The case that has drawn us here tonight is everybody's worst
nightmare ... the sadistic abuse of a child,'' Karen Sundquist of
the Child Guidance Clinic, said Tuesday night.
   More than 400 people filled the Tacoma City Light auditorium for
the meeting, which was punctuated by cheers, applause and calls
from the crowd for the death penalty. At least another 50 people
watched on closed-circuit television from down the hall and dozens
were unable to get inside.
   The meeting was organized by sexual assault counselors and
community leaders to deal with the uproar after a 7-year-old boy
was raped and his penis cut off on May 20. More than $100,000 has
been raised or pledged from around the country for the youngster,
who is recovering.
   Charges of attempted murder, rape and assault have been filed
against Earl Kenneth Shriner, 39, diagnosed as retarded and
confined in prison and mental health institutions five times since
1965.
   A legislative hearing on the case is scheduled Friday in Olympia.
   ``I am angry. I'm appalled. I'm frustrated,'' said Pierce County
Executive Joe Stortini. ``We must eliminate the gap between the
mental health system and the criminal justice system.''
   County Prosecutor John Ladenburg drew one of the biggest cheers
when he called for building a mental health prison.
   He dismissed the notion that treatment could cure habitual child
sex abusers as ``a '60s mentality ... that's not the reality.''
   Mike Comte of Comte Associates, which provides therapy for sex
offenders, said the 200 people being treated in his program
``probably represent 2,000 to 3,000 victims.''
   But Comte warned that incarcerating every sex offender
indefinitely would mean 10 or 15 new prisons.
   There was an uncomfortable stirring when Comte said he
recognized men in the audience who had been through treatment
successfully ``and are now law-abiding, taxpaying citizens.''
   Loud applause also followed calls for more widespread and
explicit warnings about sex offenders, including publicizing their
names once they have completed prison terms. Also popular were
calls for laws to ensure that more sex offenders are locked up and
fewer are released.
   Most audience members were orderly during the two-hour session,
but a few interrupted speakers with shouts like ``Castrate him!''
from one man and ``What about the death penalty for the
untreatable?'' from one woman.
   Others complained bitterly of being unable to get charges filed
against ex-husbands they claimed had abused their children, and
some said they now were afraid to let their children play outside.
   ``Do I tell my hyperactive child, after they told me to let her
run around outdoors as much as possible, she has to stay in the
house and drive all of us crazy?'' one woman shouted.
   No one who spoke from the audience gave his or her name.
   State Rep. Art Wang, D-Tacoma, got a vocal response when he
urged voter approval of a state constitutional amendment to bolster
victims' rights, including a right to be heard at sentencing.
   ``Why wait till November?'' one man shouted. The Legislature has
already passed the amendment.
   State Attorney General Ken Eikenberry was among the crowd unable
to get in the building. He said he was ready to help draft
legislation to keep dangerous sex offenders and those likely to
commit sex offenses locked up.
   Petitions circulated inside and outside the building calling for
a special session of the Legislature for tougher laws against
sexual crimes that cause severe bodily harm or death.
</TEXT>
