<FIRST>r a PM-KidnapDismissal     05-31 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kidnap Dismissal,0292</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Dismisses Kidnapping Charges Against Man</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRIGHAM CITY, Utah (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prosecutors have dropped charges in a
1987 child kidnapping case that had yielded a conviction of the
wrong man and a mistrial for a second suspect.
   Box Elder County Attorney Jon Bunderson on Tuesday filed a
motion to dismiss charges of child kidnapping, aggravated sexual
abuse of a child and aggravated kidnapping against Thomas C.
Headley, 32.
   Bunderson said he had consulted with the parents of the victim,
a 9-year-old girl who was abducted from a schoolyard on March 24,
1987, sexually abused and abandoned the next day across the border
in Idaho.
   ``I think this was a mutual decision we all reached,'' Bunderson
said.
   Frank Harvey, 47, of Elma, Wash., was convicted in August 1987
but released from prison four months later after authorities said
they had evidence implicating Headley.
   A mistrial was declared in Headley's trial May 19 after the
eight-member jury became deadlocked and said it could not reach a
decision because of a ``lack of facts.''
   Bunderson said those difficulties were weighed in his decision
to file the motion.
   ``I don't see that another jury would do anything differently,
to tell the truth,'' he said.
   Prosecutors also did not want to subject the girl to a third
appearance on the witness stand.
   The girl, who was 6 at the time of her abduction, had not
identified Harvey as her assailant but was able to pick Headley, of
Snowville, out of a photo collage and a police lineup.
   The case was further complicated when it was learned both
suspects drove blue cars, smoked cigarettes with brown tips, and
owned the same breed of dog.
</TEXT>
