<FIRST>r i PM-Korea-Dissident     05-31 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea-Dissident,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Top Dissident Indicted for Unauthorized Trip to North Korea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leading dissident was indicted today
on charges his controversial and unauthorized trip to communist
North Korea violated his country's national security law.
   Prosecutors said the Rev. Moon Ik-hwan, 71, and a traveling
companion, Yoo Won-ho, 59, were charged with ignoring the country's
ban on unauthorized travel to a hostile government and praising
``anti-state elements'' during a nine-day trip to North Korea.
   The two were arrested April 13 on their return to Seoul and have
been held in detention since.
   If convicted, Moon could be sentenced to anywhere from five
years in prison to death, although there is little chance he would
be executed.
   Moon's trip triggered a major controversy, with South Korean
officials saying the dissident clergyman's visit to the communist
capital of Pyongyang aided North Korean attempts to cause unrest
and discredit the Seoul government.
   While in the north, Moon met with North Korean leader Kim Il
Sung to discuss territorial reunification and other issues. Seoul
holds that talks with the north should be conducted through
official channels only and that Moon did not represent the south.
   The charges accuse Moon of asking Chung Kyong-mo, a Korean
resident in Japan, to arrange the trip.
   Yoo is charged with receiving money from leaders of Hanmintong,
a pro-North Korean organization in Japan, to buy a parliamentary
nomination from an opposition party last year. Yoo was also charged
with receiving $120,000 dollars from Hanmintong to set up an
engineering company and act as agent for the group in South Korea.
   Lee Young-hee, an editorial advisor to the liberal newspaper
Hankyoreh Shinmum, was indicted last week for attempting to arrange
an unauthorized trip to North Korea for reporters on the newspaper.
   The two Koreas have been bitter rivals since the division of the
peninsula into the communist north and capitalist south at the end
of World War II. North Korea invaded the south in 1950, touching
off the bloody three-year Korean War.
</TEXT>
