<DOCNO> AP890531-0063 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 0559EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Bush-China-Hungary     05-31 0118</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush-China-Hungary,100</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Grants Trade Benefits Extension to China, Hungary</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MAINZ, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush today granted a
one-year extension of trade benefits to China and Hungary, based on
their peformance on human rights.
   In a notice to Congress, Bush said he was keeping the two
countries on the list of nations that enjoy the ``most favored
nation'' trading status.
   The designation protects these nations from higher tariffs that
the United States imposes on countries it deems to have poor
records on human rights and emigration.
   The Soviet Union, for example, does not have preferred trade
status, but Bush has offered to grant that designation if Moscow
formalizes its relaxed emigration policy.
