<FIRST>r a PM-CottonClub     05-31 0566</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cotton Club,0584</SECOND>
<HEAD>Witness Tells of Threats Against Slain Producer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A threat from entertainer Joey Bishop and two
anonymous telephone calls prompted ``Cotton Club'' producer Roy
Radin to hire a bodyguard about six months before he was killed,
Radin's former assistant testified.
   At a preliminary hearing for three defendants Tuesday, Jonathan
Lawson said Radin sought protection after Bishop threatened to
``call out the Philadelphia Mafia on him.''
   Bishop has not been named in the case. A telephone call to a
number listed as his residence yielded no answer Tuesday evening.
   Attorneys for the defendants were trying to show that many other
people had motives to kill Radin, an obese, cocaine-sniffing
producer whose first attempt at Hollywood movie-making was aborted
by his slaying.
   The prosecution contends that reputed drug dealer Karen DeLayne
Greenberger arranged Radin's murder after they fought about her
share of profits from the movie, ``The Cotton Club.''
   Mrs. Greenberger is charged along with Alex Lamota Marti,
William Molony Mentzer and Robert Ulmer Lowe, former bodyguards for
Hustler magazine publisher Larry Flynt. Lowe is fighting
extradition in Maryland. The current hearing will determine whether
Mrs. Greenberger, Mentzer and Marti stand trial.
   Six months before his disappearance, Lawson recalled that Radin
hired a former wrestler named Sal to guard him. He was asked to
explain.
   ``We had a very bad experience in Atlantic City,'' N.J., said
Lawson.
   Asked to explain, Lawson replied, ``Joey Bishop made threats to
him and threatened to call out the Philadelphia Mafia on him ....
This took place in Atlantic City.''
   He indicated Bishop was part of a show Radin had staged at
Bally's casino in the gambling resort.
   ``Were you present when the threats were made?'' asked attorney
Richard Hirsch.
   ``I was present in the office at Bally's when Joey Bishop
pointed a finger at Roy and said, `I'll see that you're
straightened out because you're in my territory now,''' Radin said.
He did not explain what triggered the remarks, and further
questioning was cut off by Municipal Court Judge Patti Jo McKay,
who ruled it was irrelevant.
   Lawson said that in the months leading up to Radin's May 1983,
disappearance, at least two anonymous phone callers threatened
Radin's life.
   He quoted one of the callers as saying, ``Radin has been
shooting off his mouth too much. He should take the deal the way it
is and shut his mouth.''
   The second caller, he said, warned that if Radin didn't heed
warnings, ``he'll find himself dead.''
   Radin's show business connections have added glitter to the
case. Actor Demond Wilson of TV's ``Sanford and Son'' was scheduled
to take the stand sometime today.
   Former Paramount Pictures chief Robert Evans, who initially was
implicated in the case, invoked Fifth Amendment protection against
self incrimination and refused to testify. He and Radin
collaborated on raising money for ``The Cotton Club'' production
after they were introduced by Mrs. Greenberger.
   Radin disappeared after leaving for dinner with Mrs. Greenberger
on May 13, 1983. His body was found a month later in a dry riverbed
65 miles north of Los Angeles. He had been shot repeatedly in the
head.
   The defense stepped up its attack on the dead man's character
Tuesday, eliciting testimony that he physically abused his former
wife, used cocaine in excessive amounts and substituted the
tranquilizer Thorazine when he was withdrawing from cocaine.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
