<FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     05-31 0604</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0621</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thunderstorms From Colorado to Michigan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Scattered thunderstorms rumbled from Colorado to Michigan early
today, dumping heavy rain in the Midwest and causing some flooding,
while warm weather lingered over parts of the East.
   The heavy rains followed tornadoes late Tuesday in Michigan and
Iowa. In central Iowa, tornadoes injured three people and damaged
eight farms, according to the National Weather Service. No injuries
or property damage were reported in Michigan, authorities said.
   In central Wisconsin, flooding in North Fond du Lac near the
south shore of Lake Winnebago forced the evacuation of about a half
dozen dwellings, officials said.
   But a flash flood watch for the area was cancelled by the
Weather Service early today. ``It has calmed down pretty much,''
Renee Kissinger, a dispatcher for the Fond du Lac County Sheriff's
Department.
   In southwestern Michigan, flooding was reported in Jackson and
Lansing areas. Flood watches were in effect this morning for lower
Michigan and northwest Ohio.
   Heavy rain during the six hours ending at 2 a.m. EDT included
more than an inch in Muskegon, Mich., and about three-quarters of
an inch in Lander, Wyo., and in Detroit.
   In the 24 hours ending at 9 p.m. EDT, Hopkins, Mich., had 4
inches of rain and Hamilton, Mich., received 3.75 inches.
   Other severe thunderstorms occurred over western portions of the
central and southern Plains. Farther west, snow fell early today in
Rock Springs, Wyo., and in portions of Yellowstone National Park.
   Elsewhere, late Tuesday thunderstorm winds gusted to 59 mph at
Midland, Texas, downing trees and power lines, and thunderstorms in
Florida spawned a tornado Tuesday afternoon in Pasco County, but no
major damage was reported.
   Tampa, Fla., recorded a temperature of 96 degrees on Tuesday, a
record for the date; Laredo, Texas, had the nation's high, though,
with 103 degrees.
   Today's forecast called for showers and thunderstorms extending
from the Great Basin across the central Rockies, the northern and
central Plains, the upper half of the Mississippi Valley and the
Great Lakes region to the north Atlantic coastal states; and widely
scattered thunderstorms over central and southern Florida.
   High temperatures were to be in the 50s and 60s from the Great
Basin across the northern half of the Rockies, most of Nebraska,
the Dakotas and Minnesota to Upper Michigan; in the 60s over
eastern Maine; in the 90s from the middle and south Atlantic
coastal states across the Ohio and Tennessee valleys, the Gulf
Coast states, the lower half of the Mississippi Valley and the
southern Great Plains to the desert Southwest; and a few 100 degree
readings along the Rio Grande Valley of Texas. Elsewhere, highs
were mostly to be in the 70s and 80s.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 31
degrees at Yellowstone, Wyo., to 82 degrees at Key West, Fla.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 72 fair; Boston 67 cloudy; Buffalo 67 cloudy;
Charleston, S.C., 69 fair; Cincinnati 73 partly cloudy; Cleveland
67 showers; Detroit 65 thunderstorms; Miami 76 showers; New York 61
fair; Philadelphia 70 hazy; Pittsburgh 73 fair; Portland, Maine, 58
foggy; Washington 72 fair.
   _Central: Bismarck 47 cloudy; Chicago 74 foggy; Dallas-Fort
Worth 76 windy; Denver 48 rain; Des Moines 63 cloudy; Indianapolis
75 fair; Kansas City 75 partly cloudy; Minneapolis-St. Paul 54
cloudy; Nashville 71 fair; New Orleans 77 fair; St. Louis 78 fair.
   _West: Albuquerque 64 fair; Anchorage 48 cloudy; Las Vegas 64
fair; Los Angeles 57 fair; Phoenix 73 fair; Salt Lake City 45
cloudy; San Diego 61 fair; San Francisco 52 fair; Seattle 54 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 59 foggy; Toronto 61 foggy.
</TEXT>
