<FIRST>u i PM-BarbaraBush     05-31 0389</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Barbara Bush,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Lady Donates Redwood Slab as Symbol of U.S.-West German Ties</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Bush Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First Lady Barbara Bush dedicated a
cross-cut slab from a 750-year-old California redwood tree today as
a symbol of lasting friendship between the United States and West
Germany.
   Mrs. Bush noted that the piece of redwood had lived long and
traveled far to reach its new resting spot on a windswept knoll in
Bonn's Rheinaue Park.
   ``I hope passersby will enjoy this redwood slab and I also hope
they will be reminded of the close ties and friendship between our
peoples,'' she told about 200 West German well wishers who gathered
at the park for a brief dedication ceremony.
   Mrs. Bush, dressed in a royal blue and white silk dress with
matching jacket, said the redwood monument had been fashioned from
a tree felled in northern California's Six Rivers National Forest.
It was transported by ship from Oakland to the Dutch port of
Rotterdam, then by train to West Germany's capital.
   The 8-foot-wide slab was mounted on its side atop an oak
platform to display its rings. Small brass plaques embedded in the
wood note important dates in Bonn's history.
   The redwood gift is intended to mark Bonn's 2,000th anniversary,
which is being celebrated this year in tandem with the 40th
anniversary of the founding of the West German state.
   A White House statement said the giant redwood from which the
slab was cut had been ``harvested for environmentally sound
reasons.''
   Bonn Mayor Hans Daniels thanked Mrs. Bush for the redwood gift
and ``for the great help of the American people with the rebuilding
of the Federal Republic of Germany after the war.''
   Hannelore Kohl, wife of West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl, said
the redwood display would remind visitors of ``the continuity of
the world.''
   To applause from the mostly elderly crowd, Mrs. Kohl praised
President Bush's announcement that West Germans no longer would
need visas to visit the United States.
   After the two first ladies posed for pictures with Daniels in
front of the redwood display, Mrs. Bush moved briskly through the
crowd shaking hands.
   Rheinaue Park overlooks the Rhine River between the federal
government offices and Bad Godesberg, where many foreign embassies
and guest houses are situated.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
