<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     05-31 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0258</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Gold Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar eased in early European trading today
following Tuesday's central bank intervention. Gold prices fell.
   Currency dealers said the dollar's decline began in New York on
Tuesday afternoon and carried over into East Asian trading
overnight.
   In Frankfurt, where the dollar slipped back below 2.00 marks,
dealers said uncertainty about U.S. and West German interest rates
also put pressure on the dollar.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day
begins, the dollar fell 0.40 yen to a closing 142.70 yen. Later, in
London, it was quoted at 142.73 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning compared with late Tuesday:
   _1.9883 West German marks, down from 2.0100
   _1.7248 Swiss francs, down from 1.7545
   _6.7391 French francs, down from 6.8085
   _2.2380 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2630
   _1,442.50 Italian lire, down from 1,452.50
   _1.2068 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2055
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.5740 to buy one pound, compared with $1.5570 late Tuesday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $364.25 a troy ounce, up
from $362.25 late Tuesday. At midmorning, the city's five major
bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $363.50.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $363.85, up from $362.10 late
Tuesday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $1.95 to close at a bid $364.68.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.26 a troy
ounce, up from Tuesday's $5.20.
</TEXT>
