<FIRST>r a PM-DomesticPartners     05-31 0204</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Domestic Partners,0210</SECOND>
<HEAD>Domestic Partners Law Goes To Mayor After Second OK By Supervisors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A law allowing unmarried couples, including
homosexuals, to register their unions and receive a document like a
marriage license was sent for signing to Mayor Art Agnos.
   The mayor has pledged to sign the legislation, which won its
second passage Tuesday by the city Board of Supervisors.
   ``This will let people love as they will,'' said Board President
Harry Britt, who sponsored the measure.
   The supervisors voted 9-0, with two absent, to support the
``domestic partners'' law allowing unmarried couples to register
their relationships publicly for a $35 fee.
   The supervisors also voted unanimously for the second time to
form a task force to examine the possibility of extending city
health benefits to the live-in lovers of city employees.
   The board passed both measures unanimously last week.
   Some religious leaders, including Roman Catholic Archbishop of
San Francisco John Quinn, have called the legislation an attack on
the family.
   A few other cities have extended health benefits to live-in
lovers of municipal employees. But San Francisco would be the first
to allow any unmarried couples to register their relationships the
way traditional couples obtain marriage licenses.
</TEXT>
