<FIRST>r a PM-People-Orbison     05-31 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Orbison,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>Publisher Sues Singer's Widow Over Royalties</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A song publishing firm has sued the
widow of rock 'n' roll star Roy Orbison for $1 million over royalty
rights from at least 15 songs he recorded late in life.
   Acuff-Rose Music Inc. claims Barbara Orbison induced her husband
to breach a $70,000-a-year songwriting contract allegedly signed in
July 1985.
   The publisher also seeks triple the profit collected by
Orbisongs, Orbison's California music publishing house, from songs
written or co-written by Orbison between July 1985 and his death in
December at age 52.
   The federal lawsuit filed Friday also claimed Mrs. Orbison and
Orbisongs have interfered with Acuff-Rose's negotiations for a
movie based on the singer's life.
   Mrs. Orbison did not immediately respond to a request for
comment relayed Tuesday through Orbison's Los Angeles-based
publicist.
   Acuff-Rose claims it should have had rights to songs including
``Handle With Care,'' ``Last Night,'' ``End of the Line,'' ``You
Got It,'' ``Dirty World,'' ``Rattled,'' ``Not Alone Anymore,''
``Congratulations,'' ``Heading for the Light,'' ``Margarita'' and
``Tweeter and the Monkey Man.''
   The lawsuit does not estimate the profit from the songs, many of
which appear on ``The Traveling Wilburys,'' an album Orbison made
last year with Bob Dylan, George Harrison, Tom Petty and Jeff Lynne.
</TEXT>
