<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 0728EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DatingGorillas     05-31 0462</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dating Gorillas,0477</SECOND>
<HEAD>Zoo Atlanta's Lowland Gorilla Willie B. Meets Girls for First Time</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Everything was set for the first date: a nicely
decorated room, a convenient hammock, various playthings. And some
water hoses and tranquilizer darts, just so things wouldn't get out
of hand.
   After all, Willie B. hadn't been with a female for 28 years, and
it wasn't clear how the silverback lowland gorilla would react.
   ``I hope the gorilla's not as nervous as I am,'' Atlanta Zoo
Director Terry Maple said before Tuesday's meeting.
   The 30-year-old male gorilla was introduced to a pair of female
gorillas in a specially designed room. He had been isolated from
others of his kind for 28 years, allowed to observe other gorillas
only from a distance and through heavy mesh.
   But neither Willie B. nor the two females _ 6-year-old Kinyani
and 26-year-old Katoomba _ showed any shyness. Both females are
from the Yerkes Regional Primate Research Center at Emory
University.
   Kinyani and Katoomba were free to decide whether to join Willie
B. by using an overhead door large enough for them but too small
for Willie B. They waltzed right in, Maple said.
   Two other doors just big enough for Kinyani and Katoomba to
escape were available. Both used the doors several times but always
returned to the room, Maple said.
   After Willie made a few rushes, Katoomba responded with charges
of her own, and soon Willie gave way, letting the female chase him
around the room.
   ``This may be her social experience showing through,'' said
Kenneth Gould, chief of reproductive biology at Yerkes. ``She's
been through introductions before and has a history of being able
to look after herself.''
   A staring match followed, but after it broke up the gorillas sat
in relative quiet.
   ``It couldn't be going any better,'' Maple said. ``So far,
Willie has proved to be very normal in the behaviors he has shown
during the socialization process.''
   Erika Archibald, a spokeswoman for the zoo, said the norm among
gorillas is for each male to ``hang out'' with a group of females;
male gorillas tend to be antagonistic toward one another and could
fight.
   ``This is just a period of socialization for Willie B.,'' she
said.
   Dates will continue each day in the 37- by 20-foot room, Maple
said. Zoo officials hope the gorillas will mold themselves into a
family, with Katoomba eventually bearing Willie's child.
   Next week, officials plan to let the gorillas continue their
courtship outdoors. There are three other gorilla troops in the
$4.5 million Ford African Rain Forest habitat. The troops are
separated by moats.
   ``If all goes well with Willie B.'s introduction, we will be the
only zoo to have four gorilla troops on exhibit every day,'' Maple
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
