<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 0829EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-TroubledTown 1stLd-Writethru a0477 05-31 0761</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Troubled Town, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0477,0778</SECOND>
<HEAD>Residents Worried About PCB Contamination</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 5th graf, `Frequent floods ...,' to CORRECT subject-verb
agreement.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CN1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK PAXTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINDEN, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This looks like any former company town in
West Virginia, with parallel rows of virtually identical houses, a
small, soapsud-filled creek flowing past back yards and a
played-out mine.
   But residents are worried about something unseen that sets
Minden apart _ it may be contaminated with cancer-causing chemicals.
   For years, Shafer Equipment Co. removed oil from old electrical
transformers they were rebuilding, burning some oil for heat,
giving some to residents to use in furnaces and dumping the rest in
a pit at the mouth of the former Minden mine, residents say.
   The oil is laced with polychlorinated biphenyls, known to cause
cancer in laboratory animals. PCBs bond to soil and are not
water-soluble, so any contaminated oil dumped 15 years ago could
still present a health risk.
   Frequent floods along Arbuckle Creek, which flows through town,
have dumped tons of mud from the plant into yards and basements.
Oak Hill, a city of 9,200 a few miles to the west, also gets much
of its water from the area.
   ``When you sit and think that we've been exposed to this
contamination for 15 years,'' said resident Sue Workman, ``I'm of
the opinion there is no way they could ever clean it up.''
   The federal Environmental Protection Agency has spent $3 million
cleaning up the plant, hauling away 4,735 tons of contaminated
dirt, 110 drums of contaminated liquids and solids, 23 drums of
electric capacitors and 21 transformers, said agency spokeswoman
Theresa Bickel in Philadelphia. Last month, the agency agreed to
test the soil within three miles of the site.
   But some residents, who have formed a group called Concerned
Citizens to Save Fayette County, think no amount of work will make
the town safe. They want a state or federal buyout of their town
and creation of a New Minden somewhere else _ at an estimated cost
at $20 million.
   ``Money _ should that be a consideration when people's lives are
at stake?'' asked Workman, 30, the mother of two.
   Simply moving is out of the question for most of the town's 300
families because no one wants to buy a house here, she said. ``You
can't give a piece of property away,'' she said.
   The EPA soil study will begin in September and take at least six
months, said Loretta Haddy, an epidemiologist with the state Health
Department. If high levels of PCBs are found, the Centers for
Disease Control will investigate whether they have caused any
health problems.
   A state Health Department study of the town's mortality figures
from 1979 to 1985 found nothing unusual.
   But a study by Vanderbilt University students last year came up
with vastly different results.
   The students found traces of PCBs in soil taken from 17 of 19
sites. They also surveyed 173 residents and found 62 percent of the
women surveyed had suffered miscarriages or stillbirths, or had
children with birth defects.
   Sixteen percent said they had cancer, 18 percent suffered from
liver disorders, 34 percent had skin problems ranging from dryness
to hair loss, and 31 percent reported a persistent cough _ all
apparent symptoms of PCB contact.
   ``We don't know anything about the protocol for the study, the
methods they used, anything about the study,'' Haddy said, but
added, ``We're interested in what they came up with.''
   But Workman and other residents complain bitterly about the
department.
   ``They've ignored our pleas, and finally we had to go elsewhere
to get help,'' Workman said.
   Lucian Randall, a laid-off miner, says he has evidence of PCB
contamination in the palm of his hand _ a recurring scaly patch. He
worked for about two years as a security guard during the first
cleanup of the site. He says tests have shown his blood contains
PCBs.
   ``Sure, I'm worried. But I'm 62,'' said Randall, who lives 100
yards from the plant. ``I'm worried about the kids around here.''
   The Fayette County Board of Education plans to shut Minden
Elementary School at the end of this school year, saying there
aren't enough students to keep it open. But some are sure the board
doesn't think it's safe to keep children in Minden.
   ``I don't think anybody in our group would say every health
problem in Minden is caused by PCBs,'' Workman said. ``But the
health problems are incredible, and the stress of not knowing what
to expect _ it's incredible.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
