<DOCNO> AP890531-0077 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 0832EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-JohnstownCentennial     05-31 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Johnstown Centennial,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parade, Pagaent Mark Johnstown's Killer Flood Centennial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHNSTOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The centennial of the giant flood that
swept 2,209 people to their deaths under a 70-foot wall of water is
being marked today with a torchlight pageant and memorials.
   ``The flood, they say, is an old story. But it isn't. It's as
new as Three Mile Island, it's as new as Chernobyl, it's as new as
the Alaskan oil spill,'' said David McCullough, who wrote a book
about the flood.
   The Johnstown flood was the nation's second-worst natural
disaster. A tidal wave killed about 5,000 people at Galveston,
Texas, in 1900.
   Floodwaters from Lake Conemaugh, a private resort created by
wealthy industrialists, broke through a poorly constructed earthen
dam on May 31, 1889, after several days of rain.
   The waters swept 14 miles down the Little Conemaugh River Valley
and slammed into the town of 10,000 people, virtually washing it
away in about 10 minutes.
   A huge pile of debris containing scores of survivors of the
flood piled up against the Pennsylvania Railroad's stone bridge,
which still stands across the Conemaugh River just below downtown,
and caught fire, causing more deaths.
   As part of today's observance, officials are opening a new
National Park Service visitors center and the renovated Johnstown
Flood Museum.
   A memorial is scheduled at Point Stadium near the stone bridge
and will include the lighting of a torch, the ringing of church
bells, sirens, brief fireworks and a citywide moment of silence.
   The two living survivors of the flood, Elsie Frum, 106, and
Frank Shomo, 100, will be the guests of honor at the annual
Survivors' Banquet at Christ the Saviour Cathedral in downtown
Johnstown.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
