<FIRST>u i PM-Japan-Politics 1stLd-Writethru   05-31 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Politics, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0513,0593</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sousuke Uno to be Next Prime Minister, Despite Resistance</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with former prime minister's reaction,
details. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Foreign Minister Sousuke Uno today agreed to become
the next prime minister after leaders of the scandal-ridden
governing party, bucking stubborn resistance, decided he was the
best person for the job, a party official said.
   Uno, in Paris on official business, agreed in a telephone call
to take the jobs of party head and government leader after
expressing some reluctance, Ryutaro Hashimoto, deputy party
secretary-general, told a news conference.
   ``I am not confident I can handle the job when the party is
facing such a difficult time,'' Hashimoto quoted Uno as telling
him. ``But now that the party is in an unprecedented crisis, I will
commit myself for the party.''
   Hashimoto said leaders of the governing Liberal Democratic Party
decided that Uno, 66, is ``the most suited candidate as successor''
to Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita, who is resigning to take
responsibility for an influence-peddling scandal involving the
Recruit Co.
   Recruit, an information and publishing conglomerate, is accused
of seeking favors and influence through political donations and
bargain-priced share transactions that benefited leading
politicians.
   Those linked to the scandal include Yasuhiro Nakasone,
Takeshita's predecessor; Takeshita; and party Secretary-General
Shintaro Abe.
   Uno is not known to have received Recruit money. That and his
expertise in foreign affairs were said to be his main selling
points.
   But some opposed Uno because he is a senior member of the party
faction of Nakasone, during whose 1982-87 tenure most of the
Recruit scandal took place.
   ``I am outraged by this nonsense of giving the country's highest
office, which only one person can assume, to a sort of managing
director of the Nakasone company,'' former Prime Minister Takeo
Fukuda told reporters after Hashimoto's announcement.
   Fukuda's name was one of many that surfaced during the long
search for a successor to Takeshita.
   Hashimoto said the decision to pick Uno was worked out in
day-long meetings involving himself; Takeshita; Masayoshi Ito,
chairman of the party Executive Council; Michio Watanabe, chairman
of the Policy Board; and Ichiro Yamanouchi, party leader in the
upper house of the Diet, Japan's parliament.
   He said party legislators would probably confirm Uno as party
leader Friday. The Parliament, where the governing party has a big
majority, then will vote on Uno for prime minister.
   Before Hashimoto's announcement, a group of 48 younger
legislators said party leaders should halt their search for a new
prime minister and ``take responsibility'' for the Recruit scandal
first _ in effect resign their party posts.
   ``Now that the party had adopted measures to take responsiblity
for the scandal, we demand the party to implement them first,''
said Shizuka Kamei, head of the Liberal Progressive Alliance. ``If
party leaders are going to neglect responsibility measures and
appoint a new prime minister, we are prepared to support our own
candidate.''
   Party elders such as former prime ministers Fukuda and Zenko
Suzuki suggested a separation of the jobs of party head and prime
minister.
   The party elders had argued it would be too much a burden for a
prime minister to also handle party reform.
   ``The prime minister has to be one person, but difficulties in
the party will not allow one person to handle both the party and
the government,'' Fukuda told reporters. ``I suggested something
like a collective leadership in the party.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
