<FIRST>r a PM-BlacksOusted     05-31 0366</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Blacks Ousted,0380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Woman Says She Was Forced Out Of House Days After Moving In</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black woman says racial harassment forced
her and her two young children to abandon the first house she ever
owned just eight days after they moved in.
   ``Those people just don't want me to live there,'' said Rosa
Toussaint, 29.
   Ms. Toussaint's assessment was confirmed by some residents of
the neighborhood, The Philadelphia Inquirer reported in today's
editions. Several said the real estate company never should have
shown her a house in an all-white neighborhood and should have
warned her that she would not be welcomed there, the newspaper said.
   ``Blacks start moving in and property values go down and white
people start running,'' Frank Sintic said Tuesday. ``They shouldn't
run, in my opinion, but they do and Realtors end up making
fortunes.''
   Ms. Toussaint said she moved to Philadelphia after being
honorably discharged from the Army. She works for a nonprofit
agency that monitors abused and neglected children.
   She said the problems began May 13, the day she moved into the
rowhouse.
   She said she heard someone make a racist comment when she was
moving in, but ignored it. Two days later, she found her garbage
can overturned and a fish skeleton on her doorstep.
   Several days later, she said, rocks were thrown through two
windows.
   ``At that moment, I knew I wasn't staying there and I would not
be going back,'' Toussaint said. ``It could be fire next time.''
   Neighborhood pizza shop owner Sandy Borschell blamed Brunner
Real Estate Inc., which handled the sale of the $27,250 rowhouse.
   ``They made that woman a victim of society,'' he said.
   Bob Coyle of Brunner said the company did exactly what laws
dictate.
   ``The woman came in here and wanted to buy a house and we sold
her a house. We did not discriminate,'' he said.
   ``I don't care what the neighbors say,'' he added. ``They're a
bunch of bigots, anyhow.''
   Ms. Toussaint reported the events to the Police Department's
Conflict Prevention and Resolution Unit and to the city's
Commission on Human Relations.
   Toussaint, who is staying with friends, said she plans to stay
in Philadelphia.
</TEXT>
