<FIRST>r a PM-SecretPlates     05-31 0268</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Secret Plates,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawmakers Seek to Limit Use of Secret License Tags</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DUNCAN MANSFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bill to restrict the use of untraceable license
plates, originally intended for undercover police officers, has
been introduced after status-conscious politicians began using the
ever-so-secret tags.
   The issue came to light when state literacy chief Gerard D'Amico
acknowledged and apologized in early May for running up $900 in
parking tickets on his state car, which was outfitted with
confidential plates that even the Registry of Motor Vehicles
couldn't track.
   D'Amico chalked up the tickets to ``carelessness and
stupidity,'' paid the tickets, turned in his state car and said he
hoped the incident wouldn't hurt his bid for lieutenant governor in
1990.
   The confidential plates look just like those issued to any other
Massachusetts driver. The bill to restrict their use to law
enforcement officers was introduced Tuesday by state Rep. Peter
Torkildsen.
   Since Administration and Finance Secretary Edward Lashman issued
an internal memorandum April 5 asking all agencies to detail and
justify their confidential plates, three cabinet secretaries have
turned in their secret tags.
   Lashman's agency has given 35 administrative officials
permission to retain the plates; 769 plates have been issued to law
enforcement officials or other investigatory officers.
   The administration believes Torkildsen's legislation should
allow exceptions for officials who receive death threats and for
investigatory units that are not strictly law enforcement, such as
Alcohol Beverage Control Commission investigators.
   For example, Revenue Commissioner Stephen Kidder has one of the
confidential plates because of the frequent threats he gets as the
state's chief tax collector.
</TEXT>
