<HEAD>Mental Patient Says He Wants to Return to Cuba</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Cuban immigrant who allegedly tried to hijack
an American Airlines jet to Cuba has offered to plead guilty to all
charges in exchange for deportation to his homeland.
   Pedro Rene Comas Banos, 38, went before U.S. Magistrate Linnea
Johnson to face air piracy charges Tuesday and, speaking through an
interpreter, surprised the court with an impromptu plea bargaining
gambit.
   ``If I plead guilty to all the charges, will you do me the favor
of deporting me to Cuba?'' he asked.
   A psychiatric examination of Comas was ordered on the motion of
a public defender appointed to represent him.
   Comas, who boarded American Flight 1098 in Los Angeles,
allegedly handed a threatening note to a flight attendant Saturday
saying he wanted to go to Cuba. The pilot of the flight, which was
on its Dallas to Miami leg, landed at Miami after telling Comas the
plane didn't have enough fuel to reach Havana.
