<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 0936EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BabyDeath-Panel     05-31 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Baby Death-Panel,0470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Seeks Legal Reform in Light of Linares Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BERNARD SCHOENBURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State law needs to catch up with life-support
technology and help avoid another case like that of Rudy Linares, a
distraught father who disconnected his comatose son's respirator at
gunpoint, a prosecutor says.
   ``The Linares case is now closed. But the issues raised by that
affair are very much alive,'' Cook County State's Attorney Cecil
Partee said Tuesday as he announced formation of a 43-member task
force to recommend legal changes to the Illinois Legislature.
   Legal, medical and religious experts are all represented on the
panel, which should help produce a law that more clearly defines
roles of patients, family members and doctors in life-and-death
decisions, Partee said.
   Linares, 23, disconnected the life support system for his
15-month-old son, Samuel, at a Chicago hospital on April 26. He
held the baby in his arms until Samuel was dead while holding
hospital personnel at bay at gunpoint.
   The boy had been in a coma, considered irreversible by doctors,
since choking on a balloon nine months earlier. The hospital had
refused family requests to withdraw life support, saying the child
was not brain dead.
   Partee's office charged Linares with murder, but a grand jury
refused to indict him.
   Partee said the task force will seek legal answers to such
questions as when death occurs, under what circumstances
life-support equipment can be removed, who decides on such removal,
and what procedures to follow before life support is withdrawn.
   Two members of the panel who appeared at a news conference with
Partee, former U.S. District Judge George Leighton and Chicago
lawyer James Serritella, whose firm represents the Roman Catholic
Archdiocese of Chicago, said they do not believe a new law should
require involving a judge in every case.
   ``These things are fast-moving,'' Leighton said. ``Imagine the
case of a parent of a child in a life-support system and some
hysterical situation arises. You mean you have to wait until Monday
when the court convenes to do something about it?
   ``These are the practical and sometimes philosophical questions
involved.''
   Partee said while some laws concerning life-support do exist,
interpretations in Illinois and throughout the country vary widely.
   The Linares case ended two weeks ago when the young father
pleaded guilty to a misdemeanor weapons charge and was sentenced to
conditional discharge and counseling, if needed. No jail time was
ordered.
   The Cook County medical examiner, who had said he could not
determine the cause of death, ruled Samuel's death accidental after
the grand jury decision.
   Linares, a house painter, has since said he saw no alternative
to his action because his son's continuing ordeal was ``just
tearing apart the whole family.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
