<HEAD>Woman Admits To Letterman Break-ins And Is Freed From Mental Hospital</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORWALK, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who has claimed to be the wife of
NBC talk show host David Letterman and repeatedly has broken into
his house has pleaded guilty and agreed to stay away from him.
   Margaret Ray, 37, pleaded guilty Tuesday to using Letterman's
car without his permission and to two counts of first-degree
criminal trespass.
   A judge then ordered Ray released from a state mental hospital,
where she had been confined since a judge found her not competent
to stand trial in April.
   As part of a plea bargain arrangement, Norwalk Superior Court
Judge William F. Hickey Jr. sentenced Ray to a one-year suspended
sentence and three years probation.
   As a condition of probation, Ray must stay away from Letterman
and continue to undergo psychiatric treatment, Assistant State's
Attorney Robert G. Hall Jr. said. He said he believes Ray is
returning home to Crawford, Colo.
   The other charges against Ray were dropped, Hall said. She had
been charged with two counts of third-degree burglary, two counts
of sixth-degree larceny, two counts of first-degree criminal
trespass, possession of marijuana and possession of drug
paraphernalia in connection with break-ins at Letterman's New
Canaan home on Feb. 24 and 28.
   Last June, Ray was arrested when she tried to pass herself off
as Letterman's wife after she was stopped while driving Letterman's
1988 Porsche.
   Police said they later discovered that someone had broken into
Letterman's home in the exclusive suburb 40 miles north of New York
City. Police said it appeared someone had been living there for
several days while Letterman was out of town.
