<HEAD>Military Plane Crashes, All Four Aboard Die</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A military plane taking food to a village
crashed and burned in northern Mexico, killing all four people
aboard, military officials said.
   The government news agency Notimex late Tuesday quoted officials
as saying the plane went down Tuesday morning near the border of
the states of Chihuahua and Sinaloa.
   The plane, an Arva 2002, belonged to the Mexican Air Force's
Search, Rescue and Evacuation Unit 208 and was taking food to a
village in Chihuahua when it crashed, Notimex said.
   It said the crew had completed the same trip earlier in the day,
from the town of Baridajuato, Sinaloa, to the town of Cienega
Pineda.
   The cause of the accident was under investigation.
   The dead were identified as the pilot, Mexican Air Force Capt.
Oscar Jose Bernabe Cruz and crew members Lt. Jose de Jesus Martin
Perez, 2nd Sgt. Alejandro Sanches Flores and Cpl. Mario Alvarez
Hernandez.
