<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Waite     05-31 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Waite,0271</SECOND>
<HEAD>Terry Waite's Family Marks His 50th Birthday Quietly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The family of hostage Terry Waite, who turned 50
today, said it was marking his birthday in quiet prayer for the
Church of England envoy.
   ``Terry will obviously be even more in our thoughts today,''
said his cousin, John Waite. ``I know hundreds of cards will be
arriving, as they always do at times like these, from all over the
world.''
   Waite, the archbishop of Canterbury's personal envoy,
disappeared on Jan. 20, 1987, in Beirut, where he had been trying
to secure the release of foreign hostages. No group has claimed to
hold him, but he is widely believed to be in Shiite Moslem hands.
   ``As we go through our daily routines today, we will all be
saying a prayer for Terry wherever he happens to be,'' John Waite
said.
   A spokesman for Archbishop Robert Runcie said: ``The archbishop
will be talking during the day with his (Waite's) brother and wife,
but he is remembered every day in our prayers.'' The spokesman was
not named according to British custom.
   Waite's other brother, David, said the family believes Waite
still is alive.
   ``Our faith takes the pressure out and we can relax in the
knowledge that at the right time, Terry will be released,'' he said.
   Terry Waite and his wife, Frances, have three daughters and one
son.
   Fifteen foreigners, including nine Americans, are held by
kidnappers in Lebanon. The longest held is Terry Anderson, chief
Middle East correspondent of The Associated Press, who was taken
captive March 16, 1985.
</TEXT>
