<SECOND>PM-Bank Shooting,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dramatic Bank Shootout Injures Seven</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 17-year-old boy opened fire inside a
crowded bank and was shot down by the money courier he was trying
to rob, police said.
   Five customers were struck by flying debris or shattered glass
during the shoot-out Tuesday morning at a Wells Fargo Bank branch,
police said, but none of their injuries was life-threatening.
   The critically wounded teen-ager and Miguel Sumano, 30, a
Federal Armored Express Inc. guard, were hospitalized, said police
officer Roger Mora.
   The shoot-out was the latest in a rash of armored car holdups in
which three couriers have been killed in the last year in Southern
California.
   When Sumano arrived at the bank to make a delivery, Mora said,
he was shot twice. Sumano and the teen-ager then fired additional
shots at each other; the teen-ager crashed against a glass door and
fell through it, Mora said.
   Sumano ``sat on him until help arrived,'' said Lt. Bob Ruchhoft.
   The teen-ager underwent surgery and was in critical condition at
Cedars-Sinai Medical Center, said hospital spokesman Ron Wise. He
sustained heart and liver damage from a bullet that entered his
right side, Wise said.
   The teen-ager was not booked because of his wounds, Mora said.
   Two alleged accomplices were seen leaving the area in a gray or
blue car, Mora added.
   Sumano said his bullet-proof vest saved him; he was in good
condition at Midway Hospital Medical Center, said spokeswoman Mary
Miller.
