<FIRST>r a PM-LibelDecision     05-31 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Libel Decision,0272</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ruling Extends First Amendment Protection in International Libel
Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge says the First Amendment's
protection of free speech for U.S. citizens extends to
international libel cases, a ruling that could have broad
implications for American speakers and authors.
   Ruling in a $100 million lawsuit brought by former Indian Prime
Minister Morarji Desai, U.S. District Judge Charles Norgle said
Tuesday that it must be proven that journalist and author Seymour
Hersh intentionally distributed a libelous book in India.
   Desai's lawsuit contends the former prime minister was defamed
in Hersh's book, ``The Price of Power; Kissinger in the Nixon White
House,'' which said Desai sold state secrets to the Central
Intelligence Agency.
   Attorneys for 94-year-old Desai sought to recover damages based
on the lesser standard of negligence, rather than the ``actual
malice'' standard required under U.S. law in libel cases that
involve public figures.
   But Norgle said U.S. legal standards will be applied to the case
since Desai has acknowledged being a ``public figure.'' The judge
added in a written opinion that to apply ``Indian defamation law or
any other foreign defamation law at odds with the First Amendment
could have a tremendous chilling effect.''
   Legal experts say Norgle's ruling is the first of its kind and
signals protections for U.S. authors, speechmakers and publishers
whose domestically produced works are later published or
distributed abroad.
   Trial is set for Sept. 13. The 6-year-old lawsuit was filed in
Chicago under the principle of filing defamation actions in the
hometown of the defendant. Hersh, a Pulitzer Prize-winning
journalist, was born in Chicago.
</TEXT>
