<FIRST>r i PM-SouthKorea 1stLd-Writethru   05-31 0578</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Korea, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0542,0592</SECOND>
<HEAD>Riot Police Break Up Student Protests, Hundreds Arrested</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with report police buying tear
gas guns, water cannons. No Pickup. ^By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riot police swinging truncheons today
arrested hundreds of students who tried to march to Seoul's
Catholic cathedral in support of anti-government hunger strikers.
   About 5,000 riot troopers in helmets and combat fatigues stopped
about 1,000 students a few blocks from Myongdong Cathedral in the
city center. Police charged into the students several times and
dragged away struggling protesters in a confrontation that lasted
about four hours.
   Some students tried to ram through police lines to reach the
cathedral, but most demonstrated peacefully.
   Police said at least 500 students were arrested. Riot troopers
kicked and beat some protesters who were hauled away and police
said there were injuries among both troopers and students, but said
they had no figures.
   The students marched to the cathedral after 4,000 others took
part earlier in rallies at 13 Seoul colleges. They called for the
resignation of President Roh Tae-woo and protested the death of
dissident student Lee Chol-kyu, whom they claim was killed and
tortured by police.
   ``Down with Roh Tae-woo!'' and ``Bring back Lee Chol-kyu!''
students shouted.
   The campus protests were peaceful except at Sogang University,
where about 300 students battled police with firebombs and rocks.
At least six people were hurt, police said.
   Hundreds of students hurling rocks also clashed with police in
the southern city of Kwangju. Lee's body was found in a reservoir
near that city May 10.
   A government report concluded Lee slipped and fell into the
reservoir after fleeing a police roadblock. The report said there
was no evidence Lee was tortured or that police were involved in
his death.
   Student leaders said hundreds of students today joined the
hunger protest at the cathedral demanding the government admit
police killed Lee. About 300 students began the hunger strike last
Thursday, but their number dwindled to 60 by Tuesday. Student
leaders said about 500 students were now taking part in the hunger
strike, but there was no way to confirm the figure.
   Doctors aiding the students said eight hunger strikers were
hospitalized after collapsing and that scores gave up fasting
because of weakness.
   Riot police blocked the hunger strikers and about 300 protesters
when they tried to march from the cathedral in a candlelight
parade. Lines of police stopped the march, but there was no
violence.
   Some radical student groups have called for peaceful protests
after six riot troopers were killed May 3 in a campus
demonstration. The deaths outraged public opinion in South Korea.
The South Korean radicals lack broad public support because of
their violent tactics and extreme views.
   Students said the cathedral protest is based on the same tactics
as those used by pro-democracy Chinese students in Beijing.
   In a related development, news reports today said South Korea
will import spray guns that shoot tear gas mixed with water to
replace controversial rifles that shoot tear gas canisters. About
230 guns will be imported from Israel to combat the violent
protests, according to the daily Chosun Ilbo.
   Police will also import water cannons from Austria, the
newspaper said. Police refused comment on the reports.
   There has been public outcry against police for using the rifles
and armored vans carrying multiple tear gas launchers. The straight
tear gas has caused injuries and some deaths.
</TEXT>
