<FIRST>r i PM-Taiwan-China     05-31 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Taiwan-China,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>An Estimated Million People Link Hands to Support Chinese Democracy</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An estimated 1 million people linked hands
in the rain today to support the student-led democracy movement in
China, organizers said.
   They said the human chain, from Keelung in the north to
Kaohsiung in the south, stretched about 240 miles over highways and
city streets and was broken only at intersections to allow traffic
to pass.
   Participants, most of them students on their lunch break, sang
patriotic songs. In some cities they heard speeches during the
30-minute demonstration.
   ``Students on mainland China are facing a turning point in
history, but they are not alone in shouldering their duties because
we are firmly behind them,'' Ko Chien-wei, a student leader at
National Chengchi University, told a rally at Taipei's Chiang
Kai-shek Memorial Park.
   Chiang, who died in 1975, was the Nationalist president who led
the Nationalists to Taiwan in 1949 after they were defeated in a
civil war on the mainland by communist troops.
   About 3,000 officials and students attended the rally in Taipei.
   Before today's demonstration, only several small rallies had
been held in Taiwan to support the Chinese democracy movement. The
lukewarm public response embarrassed the Taiwanese government,
which continues to claim it is the legitimate ruler of all China.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
