<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 1120EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BRF--AbortionLawsuit     05-31 0159</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Abortion Lawsuit,0162</SECOND>
<HEAD>Michigan Supreme Court Refuses to Rule on Abortion Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michigan's Supreme Court today refused a
speeded-up ruling on the constitutionality of a voter-approved ban
on state-funded abortions for the poor.
   The high court declined to bypass the Michigan Court of Appeals
and take up the issue first, saying it was unconvinced the question
needed to be handled so quickly.
   The Michigan chapter of the American Civil Liberties Union had
appealed directly to the Supreme Court a decision by Wayne County
Circuit Judge John H. Hausner upholding the ban, which was approved
by the voters in November.
   The ACLU acted on behalf of a 15-year-old girl from Detroit who
became pregnant as a result of a gang rape. The girl's family had
challenged the cutoff of about $6 million a year for some 18,000
Medicaid abortions.
   The girl obtained an abortion privately after Hausner upheld the
ban on use of state money.
</TEXT>
