<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 1stAdd   05-31 0950</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 1st Add,0992</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNDATED: the question.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   May 29
   The Fresno (Calif.) Bee on Rep. Tony Coelho's surprise
resignation:
   Once the shock wore off, the decision of Rep. Tony Coelho
(D-Calif.), to resign from Congress six months into his sixth term
made sense.
   There are still unanswered questions as to timing and motives,
but we have his statement that he would not put his party, his
colleagues and his family through a continuing barrage of questions
about his ethics. ...
   As the third-ranking Democrat in the House, he was certain to be
Republican target No. 1 after the expected resignation of Speaker
Jim Wright.
   But what Coelho called the predictable ``turmoil'' was only part
of it. For all of his fierce attachment to the political life, he
is not a time server.
   He is both ambitious and fatalistic; when he saw a lid possibly
coming down on his chances to move up in the House hierarchy _ and
even a prospect that he might have to fight for his present
position as Democratic ``whip'' _ he had no yen to hang on. ...
   We do not share Coelho's apparent conviction that he's being
besieged simply because of an overheated climate of ethical
scrutiny. His problem with an investment in high-yield, high-risk
bonds, in which he received financial help from a savings and loan
executive, can't just be ascribed to a ``mistake'' or a simple
failure to accurately report details of the transaction.
   A reporting glitch aside, the deal itself was unsettling. ...
   Putting aside the circumstances of his leave-taking, his
effectiveness as a representative is beyond challenge.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 26
   The Plain Dealer, Cleveland, on House Speaker Jim Wright:
   With his power as speaker of the House of Representatives fast
eroding, Jim Wright is sensibly weighing resignation from his
leadership role. ...
   Although the House Ethics Committee has not yet rendered a
verdict on the 69 allegations of ethical misconduct against Wright,
the speaker belatedly has recognized his futile position.
   Holding any of the top offices within the hierarchy of Congress
requires not just electoral longevity (awarded by the voters back
home) but institutional fealty (awarded by the membership on
Capitol Hill).
   Now that Wright's years-long pattern of shady scheming has been
revealed, the reputation of the entire House has been sullied by
implication. Wright has sacrificed the political prerequisite of
leadership in Congress: its majority's allegiance. ...
   Painful as it has been, the Wright episode will have served a
useful purpose if it prompts Congress _ out of fear if not out of
self-discipline _ to uphold higher standards of conduct.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 30
   The Evening Sun, Baltimore, on health care for the aging:
   A new report from the U.S. House Committee on Aging offers a
sobering view of the nation's already embattled health-care system.
   According to the report, two trends are currently at work in
America today that will collide early in the 21st century: The
population is aging, and the percentage of care-givers is dropping.
   If doesn't take a demographer to realize that if these trends
continue unabated, there simply will not be enough nurses and home
health care workers. One piece of the equation is unchangeable _
the elderly will make up a larger and larger share of the
population.
   Thanks, in large part, to the demographic glitch caused by the
baby-boom generation, the number of senior citizens will swell from
the current 29.1 million (11.8 percent of the population) to 54.5
million (17.7 percent of the population) by 2020.
   And the elderly typically suffer from more chronic illness, need
more at-home care and spend more days in the hospital than the
overall population.
   Meanwhile, nursing shortages in hospitals nationwide have more
than doubled in the last five years. More than half of all home
health-care agencies report difficulties in finding and recruiting
health-care professionals. And the shortfall is predicted to
continue.
   The statistics warn of a health-care crisis. Fortunately,
though, it can be averted _ through proper planning.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 24
   The Sun Herald, Biloxi, Miss., on pollution:
   A survey .. shows that Americans are aware of the rapid increase
in the pollution of our environment and they want goverment to take
urgent action to halt it.
   The message hasn't yet been understood by the politicians and
the bureaucrats who have been charged with protecting the
environment. Public support for cleanups has been greatly
underestimated.
   The survey, undertaken by Media General and The Associated
Press, clearly demonstrated that the public is not blind to what's
happening and not unconcerned. ...
   It is no suprise that the people polled were aware of what's
happening. The media have been documenting the problems.
   What is encouraging is that the survey shows just how willing
people are to support efforts to halt the pollution, even with
measures that would be inconvenient and costly to them.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 30
   The Tulsa (Okla.) Tribune on Soviet-Chinese relations:
   Temporarily, at least, the air has gone out of the balloons in
Beijing and Moscow. China's leaders outwaited student demonstrators
and Soviet conservatives outvoted reformers.
   Disappointment runs deep in both capitals, but last week the
world got a glimpse of the future and it looked encouraging.
   Young Chinese, well-educated and more worldly wise than their
parents, are demanding that their lives have meaning. In a nation
which has place almost no value on the individual, this is radical
behavior. ...
   It appears that the entrenched party members in both China and
the Soviet Union are safe for now. Still, the power of 1 million
demonstrators in Beijing and the outspoken opposition in Moscow to
the status quo had its effect.
   Fear remains, but now it is mostly in high places.
</TEXT>
