<FIRST>r k BC-EditorialRdp 2ndAdd   05-31 0946</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Editorial Rdp, 2nd Add,0990</SECOND>
<HEAD>UNDATED: high places.</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   May 30
   Deseret News, Salt Lake City, on Energy Secretary James Watkins:
   Someone needs to take Energy Secretary James Watkins aside and
explain the problems that arise when the fox guards the hen house.
   Billed by a DOE spokesman as a move to improve ``line management
efficiency,'' Watkins has ordered that the same assistant who is
responsible for nuclear weapons production should now assume
responsibility for safety at the nation's 16 weapons plants.
   He has also eliminated any safety oversight and monitoring at
the plants by another office within his department.
   Production schedules and proper safety procedures are both
important components in the weapons production program, but the two
functions are diametrically opposed, and each should be overseen by
someone without a built-in conflict of interest.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 30
   The Atlanta Journal on air pollution:
   During the past two decades of environmental cleanup, industry
has been viewed as part of the problem rather than part of the
cure. Legislation proposed by the Bush administration would change
that, offering the business sector reason to become an ally instead
of an adversary.
   The Bush plan focuses on setting sulfur emissions limits and
then allowing polluters to choose the most cost-effective way to
comply.
   The strategy offers welcome innovation to resolving an enduring
problem whose most accessible solutions have been undertaken
already.
   The nation has made remarkable progress in reducing air
pollution using regulation as a stick to coerce compliance, but
we've gone about as far as we can go by traditional methods. Now,
it's time to offer a carrot to stimulate efforts toward going the
rest of the distance.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 30
   The Wichita (Kan.) Eagle-Beacon on gas guzzling cars:
   Sometime within the past decade, America's idea of auto fuel
conservation took a wide detour.
   Automobile dealerships in the late 1970s and early 1980s pushed
small, economy-sized vehicles that offered high gasoline mileage.
As gas prices decreased, however, Americans traded their economy
cars for new models that offered greater comfort and increased
performance, yet demanded more fuel.
   Already, there's pressure aplenty to increase auto fuel
efficiency. ...
   These suggestions play into concerns of U.S. foreign
policymakers who fear the growing U.S. dependence on cheap foreign
oil leaves Americans vulnerable to another energy crisis. ...
   If the United States is to take a leadership role in efforts to
slow the greenhouse effect, strengthening U.S. auto efficiency
standards would demonstrate that commitment.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 30
   The Albuquerque (N.M.) Tribune on ending unfair trade:
   No one who understands the benefits of an open world trading
system can be pleased by President Bush's designation last week of
Japan, India and Brazil as unfair trading nations, but he had no
good alternative to that risky action.
   Bush acted under a stiff provision of the 1988 trade law, which
requires him to name nations that maintain barriers to U.S.
exports. If negotiations do not remove the barriers, the president
is authorized to retaliate.
   If Bush had not moved against Japan, which richly deserves to be
called an unfair trader, Congress would have exploded with fury and
might well have passed protectionist legislation that would have
done even more harm.
   Japan, which ran a $55 billion trade surplus with the United
States last year, was the main target. But Bush did not want to
cite it alone, fearing an irrational reaction by Tokyo, so Brazil
and India, less flagrant offenders, were added as cover.
   Japan has to change. It cannot expect to sell cars and consumer
electronics to Americans and refuse to buy what they make best.
   One hopes Americans will have the patience and Japanese will
develop the maturity to prevent a tit-for-tat trade war that will
harm everybody.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 30
   St. Louis Post-Dispatch on Bush and Congress:
   In his persistent threat to veto a higher increase in the
minimum wage than he would like, President Bush has chosen a
strangely cruel test for his first legislative showdown with
Congress.
   The issue appears to boil down to a president who, having been
rebuffed in his attempt to make John Tower secretary of defense,
wants to look tough in his relationship with Congress.
   Such a pitched battle may have enhanced his public image when he
sparred with Dan Rather on nationwide television, but this time the
loser will be those who can least afford it _ those who work at a
minimum wage that has not risen beyond $3.35 an hour since 1981.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   May 26
   The Indianapolis News on incentives to get the Super Bowl:
   The Super Bowl isn't coming to Indianapolis in 1992. It will go
instead to Minneapolis. Maybe that's a shame, but all the same it's
hard not to breathe a sigh of relief.
   Indianapolis, after all, had offered to fork over about $3.5
million worth of incentives to the NFL. More than $1 million of
that would have come directly from the pockets of taxpayers.
   Yes, the Super Bowl is a prestigious event, and yes, bringing it
to Indianapolis would probably have enhanced the reputation of the
city.
   But you've got to wonder where they come up with these
``economic impact'' statements. Word from city officials was that
the Super Bowl would have an ``economic impact'' of $100 million on
whatever city was chosen.
   What does that mean? Where do such figures come from? ...
   Indianapolis would do well in the future to avoid such giant
offers of tax money to lure events like the Super Bowl here.
   This proud city may be eager for the action that major sports
events bring, but it also has other, more important priorities for
the people's precious tax money.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Editorial Rdp</NOTE>
