<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 1138EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-CollegeDesegregation     05-31 0464</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-College Desegregation,0483</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Appointee Recommends Curbing Open Admissions in Louisiana</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN SAYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An official appointed to draft an
integration plan for Louisiana's public colleges recommended
eliminating most open-admissions policies and putting all 17
schools under a single governing board.
   No universities would be closed or merged under the proposal
issued Tuesday by Paul Verkuil.
   Verkuil, appointed by a federal panel to come up with a
desegregation plan for the 145,000-student system, changed few
details from a preliminary proposal issued April 18, said John
Kennedy, legal aide to Gov. Buddy Roemer.
   The court will have the final say on the plan.
   The 17-member board would be appointed by the governor and
approved by the Senate and would govern all public higher education
in Louisiana, replacing four boards that run the 13 four-year
institutions and four two-year schools.
   Verkuil said the board would be responsible for ``insuring that
progress toward eliminating Louisiana's racially dual education
system is achieved.''
   Verkuil was appointed after the court ruled last year that a
1981 desegregation agreement between the state and the U.S. Justice
Department had failed. The plan had called for spending millions of
dollars to improve predominantly black Southern and Grambling State
universities.
   The dispute began 15 years ago when the Justice Department
accused the state of running a dual system of higher education for
blacks and whites.
   Under the plan recommended by Verkuil, president of William and
Mary College in Virginia, Louisiana State University would become
the state's flagship institution with the toughest admission
standards.
   A second and third tier of four-year schools with less stringent
standards would be set up, while two-year community colleges would
continue to offer open admissions and would be responsible for most
remedial courses.
   The more stringent admissions policies are part of the plan's
larger goal of improving the quality of higher education in
Louisiana.
   Currently, all Louisiana colleges admit all graduates of
Louisiana high schools. Fifty-four percent of entering freshmen
must take remedial courses.
   Kennedy said he did not know if the judges would hear further
comment from the parties in the case _ including Southern
University, the U.S. Justice Department and the Grmbling alumni _
before deciding whether to approve the plan.
   Kennedy said Roemer, who had pushed for a single board, was
pleased by Verkuil's recommendation. ``The single board is the
linchpin of this whole thing,'' he said.
   State Sen. William Jefferson, an attorney for Southern, said he
had not seen the recommendation and declined to comment.
   Other parties were not available for immediate comment. Black
leaders had said a unified board would be insensitive to the needs
of Southern University and Grambling.
   Some proposals for eliminating racial disparities in the state
system included closing some predominantly black institutions.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890531-0103 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 1138EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Mexico-Journalist     05-31 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mexico-Journalist,0244</SECOND>
<HEAD>Journalists Remember Slaying of Colleague, Statue of Limitations
Ends</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Journalists marched in protest in four cities
and opposition parties demanded a new investigation on the fifth
anniversary of the assassination of a nationally acclaimed
reporter, Manuel Buendia.
   The anniversary Tuesday also marked the end of the statute of
limitations in the case, meaning his killers probably never will be
prosecuted.
   As the anniversary neared, there was pressure to find and judge
those who killed the tough investigative reporter. But it passed
without arrests.
   Buendia, who wrote a column called ``Private Network'' for the
Mexico City daily Excelsior, was gunned down on a street in the
capital's Zona Rosa section on May 30, 1984.
   Buendia's subjects ranged from senior politicians and corrupt
cops and union bosses to the CIA.
   The government news agency Notimex on Tuesday reported
journalists in the central city of Tepic, Nayarit and the southern
port city of Veracruz, marched to demand justice for their slain
colleague.
   In Mexico City, the Democratic Journalists' Union held a similar
demonstration, the agency reported.
   It quoted members of the Mexico City group as saying some 30
Mexican journalists have been killed in the five years since
Buendia's death.
   Special Prosecutor Miguel Angel Garcia Dominguez last week was
quoting as saying investigators have narrowed down their list of
suspects in Buendia's killing to 31 after taking statements from
more than 250 people.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
