<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 1155EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-LicenseRevoked     05-31 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-License Revoked,0345</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dropout's Father Promises First Test of Anti-Dropout Law </HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID WILKISON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The father of a 17-year-old school
dropout whose driver's license was revoked under a new law aimed at
curbing dropouts and truancy says he plans to give the law its
first court test.
   The 1988 law, the only such statute in the nation, has drawn
both criticism and praise from educators, parents and politicians.
   Michael Means, of Charleston, lost his license Tuesday under the
law that requires school-age young people who want to drive to stay
in school.
   Means, who dropped out of Roosevelt Junior High School a year
ago when he was in ninth grade, is married. He was an attendant at
a gas station but had to quit when he lost his driver's license.
   ``There were supposed to be exceptions to this law,'' Means'
father, William, said today. ``My son is married, he's an expectant
father with the baby due in September. They have a house ...,
trying to make it on their own.
   ``With the decision, I see no way for him to gain employment and
support his family. If this isn't an exception, I don't know what
is.''
   Under the law passed in the summer of 1988, students under age
18 who miss more than 10 consecutive days or have 15 unexcused
absences must give up their driving privileges. County school
systems notify the Department of Motor Vehicles of students who
have dropped out.
   A school superintendent can waive the law if a student's
withdrawal from school is beyond the student's control.
   DMV lawyer Tom Madden said if Means follows through with the
suit, it will be the law's first court test.
   Means misplaced his license and requested a new one. But the DMV
refused to issue a new license without the consent of the Kanawha
County Board of Education, which refused his request.
   Michael Means could not be reached for comment; his father said
he has no telephone.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
