<FIRST>u i PM-Argentina 2ndLd-Writethru   05-31 0813</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Argentina, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0582,0838</SECOND>
<HEAD>Food Riots Pressuring Alfonsin to Step Aside; 11 Dead in 2 Days</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Corrects spelling of allotted in lead and 11th graf. Pickup
12th graf, `Civil liberties...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY5</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Congress today increased benefits
for workers and retirees and allotted money for a food distribution
plan in an effort to end looting and riots that have killed 11
people.
   The Senate and House of Deputies, in an all-night session, also
ratified a 30-day state of siege declared Monday by President Raul
Alfonsin.
   President-elect Carlos Menem flew to Buenos Aires from his home
in the western provincial capital of La Rioja and met with Alfonsin
to discuss the crisis and the possibility of an early transfer of
power.
   Officials described major cities as mostly calm this morning
following rioting and sacking of stores Tuesday in several Buenos
Aires suburbs and the city of Rosario, the nation's third-largest.
Rioting also occurred in the cities of Mendoza, La Plata and
Tucuman.
   Shops and offices opened today in Buenos Aires.
   The food riots have increased pressure on Alfonsin to step down
before his six-year term ends Dec. 10, and the country's largest
labor coalition and most influential business group on Tuesday
asked Menem to take office early.
   The economic crisis has been caused by Argentina's $59 billion
foreign debt, a national budget deficit worsened by inefficient
state companies and months of inflation that could top 70 percent
for May.
   The inflation has led to layoffs, food and supply shortages and
declining real wages that have left retirees living on the
equivalent of $25 a month.
   ``The country is dying of hunger. Factories are closing. People
are unemployed,'' Adolfo Perez Esquivel, head of the human rights
group Peace and Justice Service and the 1980 Nobel Peace Prize
winner, said in an interview.
   Under Congress' action today, the minimum pension for retirees
will rise to about $36 and the minimum for widows to about $33. The
lawmakers raised the benefits at the insistence of Menem's
labor-based Peronist Party.
   They also allotted an unspecified amout of money to pay for
distribution of food and medicine.
   Civil liberties were suspended under the state of siege declared
Monday, but looting of groceries continued.
   ``Unfortunately, this government has lost its credibility,''
Saul Ubaldini, head of the 4 million-member General Labor
Confederation, said Tuesday.
   Confederation officials said an early transition is ``the only
possible solution.'' Gilberto Montagna, president of the Argentine
Industrial Union business group, also called on Alfonsin to step
down early.
   After the governing Radical Civic Union was defeated in national
elections on May 14, Alfonsin offered to resign but could not agree
with Menem on terms of the transition.
   Asked Tuesday whether he favored an early transition, Menem
said: ``That would not be opportune in these grave moments the
country is going through.''
   Alfonsin's election in 1983 ended nearly eight years of military
dictatorship.
   The government has blamed ultra-leftist groups for the riots,
but has offered little proof. Vice President Victor Martinez blamed
``groups that do not want to see the current government end its
term and another constitutional government begin.''
   The latest deaths occurred Tuesday in the Buenos Aires suburbs
of San Miguel and Quilmes during a riot in which looters broke
windows and emptied shelves in furniture stores, bars, sports and
shoe stores.
   Looters loading food onto trucks threw stones at police, who
retaliated by firing rubber bullets, killing four, local news
agencies said. A bus driver who tried to prevent the theft of his
bus was shot and killed.
   A sixth person was killed in suburban Moreno but the
circumstances were not clear, the independent news agency Diarios y
Noticias reported.
   Rosario, a meat-packing city of 1 million, has been worst hit by
the unrest.
   On Tuesday, armed bands reportedly drove through its deserted
streets after dark, shot at police stations and looted homes and
stores.
   ``They left practically nothing standing,'' Mayor Santos Mauro
of the suburban town of Villa Gobernador Galvez said. ``They
overwhelmed everything _ supermarkets, shops, shoe stores.''
   In Rosario, 186 miles north of the capital, four people were
shot and killed on Monday and an elderly women died of a heart
attack during looting. Schools remained closed Tuesday and most
businesses did not open.
   In all, several hundred stores and shops in more than a dozen
cities have been sacked the past week. More than 1,500 people have
been arrested, two-thirds of them in Rosario.
   On Tuesday, officials in the provinces scrambled to set up free
food programs and the national minimum wage was more than doubled
to the equivalent of about $57 a month.
   In Santa Fe, the province that includes Rosario, the legislature
unanimously approved a disaster law that allows private property
and merchandise to be confiscated so food and medicine can be given
to the needy.
</TEXT>
