<FIRST>u s PM-TEN--FrenchOpen 3rdLd-Writethru   05-31 2892</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-TEN--French Open, 3rd Ld - Writethru,1219</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with Connors loss; tightens</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW WARSHAW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Sports Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jimmy Connors battled in the sun for almost 4{
hours but ran out of stamina and was beaten 4-6, 6-3, 7-5, 7-5 by
fellow American Jay Berger in the second round of the men's singles
at the French Open today.
   The tenacious Connors, the No.9 seed and possibly making his
last appearance at the French Open at age 36, was cheered on by a
packed, excited Center Court crowd. He tried everything he knew to
fight off Berger and stay in the one Grand Slam event he never has
won.
   But Berger, the world's 28th-ranked player enjoying a season
that has reaped victories over Boris Becker and Mats Wilander, used
his superior fitness to wear down the street-fighting Connors after
4 hours, 26 minutes of energy-sapping baseline tennis.
   ``I practiced with Jimmy and got to know him really well. I
respected him more than other player in the game,'' Berger said.
``This is just a great win for me after losing three times to him.
It was such a battle. I'm so drained right now I can barely talk.''
   Connors said he nothing to be ashamed of after putting on a
typically never-say-die performance.
   ``All I can do is go out and fight till death. It was not
exactly like a walk in the park. I could have played a fifth set.
My mouthpiece wasn't knocked out,'' he said.
   Connors began in typical fashion, rallying from a 4-1 deficit to
win five straight games and take the opening set.
   But once Berger had squared the match, the veteran Connors had a
fight on his hands against an opponent 14 years younger. Berger
broke him to take a 6-5 lead in the third set and Connors' task
