<SECOND>PM-Bridge Collapse, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0500,0444</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Divers Enter River to Prepare for Search</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with police making exploratory
dive today. Picks up in 3rd graf, `Meanwhile, the ...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto CS2</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN NOLAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police officers made an exploratory dive into
the Great Miami River today, a day after the body of the first
victim of a bridge collapse was found snagged downriver in debris.
   The officers were preparing for a search of the river Thursday,
the first to be made since last week when storms caused a temporary
bridge to collapse, dropping at least two vehicles into the water.
   Three other victims are missing, authorities believe. The body
of a woman was found about five miles from the bridge.
   The river's flow is still swift and hazardous to divers,
Whitewater Township Fire Chief Bill Darby said. However, the water
level has dropped to about 10 feet, down from the 23-foot level
when the bridge collapsed at rush hour Friday evening.
   Meanwhile, the firm that designed the bridge raised questions
about its stability before it was built because the contractor was
allowed to alter the plans, a newspaper reported today.
   Elmer Obermeyer Jr., managing partner of the Cincinnati design
firm of Graham Obermeyer and Partners, told The Cincinnati Enquirer
his firm questioned the altered design at a meeting and in a letter
to Hamilton County Engineer Donald Schramm's office last year.
   ``Our design was heavier and had longer spans ... but nobody
really envisioned that (the collapse) would happen,'' Obermeyer
said.
   Schramm said he was aware of Obermeyer's concerns about the
alternative design, which cut the cost and time needed to build the
temporary span, but said the plans met the state Department of
Transportation's standards.
   Recovery teams used sonar Tuesday to detect what appeared to be
two vehicles on the river bottom near the bridge. The currents
remained too strong to allow divers into the water, and officials
said they probably won't send divers in before Thursday.
   Authorities didn't release the identity of the woman whose body
was found, but they said she met the description of a missing
person.
   Before the body was found, police had received reports from
relatives of four people missing, according to Frank Weikel, a
spokesman for the Hamilton County Sheriff's Department.
   The temporary bridge opened Dec. 15 to carry traffic while a
94-year-old bridge is rebuilt a few feet away. Officials said the
strong currents in the river, which crested seven feet above flood
stage over the weekend, and the pounding from debris probably
caused the collapse.
</TEXT>
