<FIRST>r i AM-Asia-Refugees     05-31 0267</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Asia-Refugees,0274</SECOND>
<HEAD>Second Group of Vietnamese Boat People Towed to Island</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government towed a boatload of 168
Vietnamese refugees to a remote island Wednesday in the second such
initiative aimed at discouraging new arrivals to the British colony.
   The latest refugees joined 109 Vietnamese who on Tuesday were
taken to Tai A Chau, an island 20 miles southwest of Hong Kong. The
government said all usual refugee facilities were filled by the
2,300 boat people who flooded Hong Kong in the last three days.
   The refugees were told not to leave their boats, according to a
police spokesman.
   Marine police were to provide the Vietnamese with food, water
and security until the government can find a place for them, the
spokesman said. He said he did not know how long that might take.
   Malaysia, the Philippines and Hong Kong received hundreds of
thousands of Indochinese boat people after communist forces
defeated the U.S.-backed governments in South Vietnam and Cambodia
in April 1975. Thousands of Vietnamese still flee their homeland.
   A year ago, Hong Kong adopted a screening policy that treats all
Indochinese refugees as illegal immigrants subject to repatriation
unless they can prove they fled political persecution.
   Despite the policy, however, the influx continues. Since June
1988, more than 20,000 boat people arrived in Hong Kong and only
1,600 have been screened, according to a government statement. The
number of boat people in the British colony is 23,593, the
statement said.
   Vietnam has agreed to attend an international conference on
Indochinese refugees that is to be held in Geneva June 13-14.
</TEXT>
