<FIRST>u w PM-SpellingBee 3rdLd-Writethru a0591 05-31 0780</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spelling Bee, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0591,770</SECOND>
<HEAD>First 17 Youngsters Eliminated in National Spelling Bee</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 8th graf pvs bgng, `Others eliminated,' to FIX hometown
of Donna Evans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seventeen spellers, stumbling over such
familiar words as ``veneer'' and ``nasturtium'' as well as less
familiar ones including ``seriatim'' and ``inumbrate,'' were
eliminated today in the first round of the 62nd National Spelling
Bee.
   The youngest competitor, 9-year-old Lisa Ishimaru of Sacramento,
Calif., survived, correctly spelling ``mountebank,'' a word for a
clownish person.
   Malinda Shepherd, 10, of Burnsville, N.C., was the first to go,
tripped up by ``seriatim,'' which means arranged one after another
in order. She spelled it ``seriatum.''
   The other five 10-year-olds in the competition, which is open to
scholars as old as 15, advanced to the second round.
   Robert A. Getz, 13, of Lawrence, Kan., had trouble with
``nasturtium,'' spelling it ``nasturtia.''
   Katherine T. Strohmaier, 12, of Lewiston, Idaho, misspelled
``veneer'' as ``vaneer.''
   ``Inumbrate,'' meaning to throw into shadow, tripped up Ana M.
Gordan, 13, of Manchester, N.H., who spelled it with a double ``n.''
   Others eliminated, and the words they missed, were Christopher
J. Simpson, 12, Whitman, Mass., sluice; Travis J. Blow, 14,
Wyalusing, Pa., macadam; Jenny L. Boehm, 11, Oreana, Ill.,
supervene; Casey R. Cornwell, 12, Henderson, Nev., paunchiness;
Kelsey J. Rinella, 13, Clifton Park, N.Y., legibility; Jason T.
Orendorff, 11, Bartlett, Tenn., palmyra; Michelle L. Santos, 12,
Moore, Okla., sonable; Lacretia Rouse, 14, Wilson, N.C.,
secularism; Amanda J. Robbins, 11, Asheboro, N.C., prenuptial;
Angela F. Greaves, 13, Lafayette, La., vacillant; Donna S. Evans,
13, Camden, W.Va., lunule; Aneka A. Walker, 14, Plainfield, N.J.,
tyrannize; and Hanna Yoon, 12, Elk Grove Village, Ill., blas, a
word for a supposed emanation from the stars.
   The two-day competition, which carries $16,350 in prize money,
has attracted 120 girls and 102 boys who survived elimination
contests around the country and in American outposts abroad.
   Last year there were 200 spellers, including the youngest in the
history of the event, Iris Liu, a third-grader from Muncie, Ind.,
who was just short of her 9th birthday. She was eliminated the
first day, stumbling on ``waywiser,'' an instrument used to measure
distances.
   In addition to the six 10-year-olds, there are 24 contestants
who are 11, 45 who are 12, 89 who are 13, 55 who are 14 and two who
are 15. Competition is limited to those who are not yet 16 and have
not passed beyond the eighth grade.
   Contest officials estimated that nearly 9 million students
participated at the local level in contests sponsored by Scripps
Howard newspapers in 13 cities and by 205 other daily, weekly and
Sunday newspapers.
   ``Spellers may not have books, papers, study sheets, word lists,
pens, pencils or other objects that might be construed as a help,''
the youngsters were warned in a schedule handed out in advance.
   They arrived in Washington for registration on Sunday and spent
Monday visiting Gunston Hall, the Virginia home of Bill of Rights
framer George Mason.
   On Tuesday, they toured Washington monuments and public
buildings and took a ride to the National Aquarium in Baltimore.
   Prizes will be presented Friday night at a banquet with a joint
armed forces color guard. First prize includes a cash award of
$1,500. Other prizes are $1,000 for second, $750 for third, $500
for fourth, $400 for fifth, $300 for sixth, $200 for seventh
through 10th, $100 for 11th through 20th, and 202 prizes of $50
each.
   Seven of the contestants are making their third appearance in
the national competition. Among them is Robert Pryor, 11, of
Washington, who had such a nervous stomach last year that he had to
be helped to the microphone on his first appearance. On his second
appearance, he misspelled ``fidgetiness.''
   There have been 64 National Spelling Bee champions, since
co-champions were declared in three years. Of the winners, 35 were
girls and 29 boys. Last year 102 girls and 98 boys competed.
   The first such event was held in 1925 with nine contestants,
under sponsorship of the Louisville Courier-Journal. The Scripps
Howard Newspapers took over the program in 1941. The program was
suspended for three years during World War II.
   In 1988, Rageshree Ramachandran, 13, of Fair Oaks, Calif., won
by correctly spelling ``elegiacal,'' a type of rhymed couplet or a
poem written in such couplets.
   In 1987, Stephanie Petit, 13, of Bethel Park, Pa., won by
spelling ``staphylococci,'' or bacteria infecting the skin and
mucous membranes.
   All but the last round are on a miss-and-out basis. On the final
round, the champion must correct the word missed by the runner-up
and then correctly spell another word.
</TEXT>
