<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     05-31 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0527</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Attack Students at Protest, Arrest 600</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Riot police wielding truncheons
arrested more than 600 radical students who tried to march to the
Roman Catholic cathedral on Wednesday to support anti-government
hunger strikers.
   About 5,000 troopers stopped 1,000 students a few blocks from
Myongdong Cathedral in the city center. Police charged into the
column of protesters several times, dragging away struggling
students in a confrontation that lasted four hours.
   Although most protesters were peaceful, some tried to ram
through police lines to reach the cathedral, where at least 60
students are staging a hunger strike.
   Some riot police kicked and beat screaming demonstrators as they
were hauled away. Police said there were injuries among the
troopers and students but said they had no figures.
   Earlier, 4,000 students took part in rallies at 13 Seoul
colleges calling for the resignation of President Roh Tae-woo.
   They also want the government to admit responsibility in the
death of radical student Lee Chol-kyu, who they say was tortured
and killed by police. A government report said Lee died when he
slipped into a reservoir while fleeing troopers and there was no
evidence of police torture.
   The students shouted ``Down with Roh Tae-woo!'' and ``Bring back
Lee Chol-kyu!''
   The campus protests were peaceful, except at Sogang University,
where 300 students battled police with firebombs and rocks. At
least six officers and students were hurt, police said.
   Hundreds of students hurling rocks also clashed with police in
southern Kwangju, near where Lee's body was found in a reservoir on
May 10.
   About 300 students began the hunger strike May 25 to demand the
government admit that police killed Lee, but their number had
dwindled to about 60 on Tuesday. Student leaders said Wednesday
more students joined the strike and 500 were participating, but
there was no way to check that figure.
   Doctors said eight fasters were hospitalized after collapsing
and scores began eating because of weakness.
   On Wednesday night, riot police blocked the hunger strikers and
about 300 protesters when they tried to march out of the cathedral
for a candlelight parade. Lines of police stopped the march, but
there was no violence.
   Some radical students have called for peaceful protests after
six riot troopers were killed May 3 in a campus demonstration. The
deaths outraged public opinion in South Korea. The radicals lack
public support because of their violent tactics and extreme views.
   Students said the cathedral protest is based on the same tactics
as those used by Chinese students in the pro-democracy protest in
Beijing.
   South Korea's largest dissident group, the United National
Democratic Movement, Wednesday announced plans to become a
full-fledged political party.
   The movement _ about 200 minor dissident groups with an
estimated total membership of 400,000 _ has led many violent
demonstrations against the government, which it labels as
dictatorial.
   It has weakened considerably in recent months after most of its
leaders, including co-chairman Lee Bu-young, were either arrested
or driven underground by police.
</TEXT>
