<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 1315EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w PM-US-Nicaragua     05-31 0198</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Nicaragua,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Expels Two Nicaraguan Envoys</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department today ordered the
explusion of two Nicaraguan diplomats in retaliation for the ouster
of two U.S. envoys from Managua last week.
   The Nicaraguan Embassy was informed that the presence of Roberto
Vargas and William Vigil, both minister counselors, ``was no longer
acceptable to the government of the United States,'' department
deputy spokesman Richard Boucher said.
   They were given 72 hours to leave the country.
   Last Thursday, the Sandinista government expelled Joel Cassman,
economics officer at the U.S. Embassy in Managua, and Kathleen
Barmon, a regional labor attache from the embassy in Honduras who
was on a visit to Managua. They were accused of inciting Nicaraguan
school teachers to join a wildcat strike.
   Boucher said the State Department waited six days before
expelling the two Nicaraguans in hopes that the Sandinista
government would reverse ``its unwarranted, unjustified expulsion''
of the two Americans.
   He said the Nicaraguan government chose not to reconsider its
decision, and the State Department reciprocated by expelling Vargas
and Vigil.
   Nicaraguan Embassy spokeswoman Cecilia Lopez said the two envoys
had arrived in Washington just 10 days ago. She had no further
comment.
</TEXT>
