<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 1327EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Germany Bjt   05-31 0866</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany, Bjt,0897</SECOND>
<HEAD>Summit Successes Shore Up Kohl, Reassure Germans of U.S. Friendship</HEAD>
<HEAD>AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The NATO allies have patched up an
unsettling quarrel over short-range missiles and President Bush has
come to West Germany and declared U.S. friendship with the Germans.
   The two events have lifted Chancellor Helmut Kohl out of the
political doldrums and given West Germans a feeling of pride and
emerging prominence. And in two weeks, Kohl will be welcoming
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev of the Soviet Union for a summit.
   It is a dramatic change.
   Only a few days ago West Germans were in a quandary about the
corner they'd painted themselves into: challenging NATO policy and
the United States by insisting on negotiations to remove
short-range nuclear missiles from Europe.
   But the NATO summit in Brussels produced an compromise agreement
and allowed Bush and Kohl to conduct their two-day summit like best
friends.
   ``The relationship between the United States and the Federal
Republic of Germany has never been better,'' Bush said repeatedly
during his visit.
   The leaders referred often to the first years after World War
II, stoking the emotional embers still burning in many older West
Germans who recall the American role in rebuilding their nation
after the fall of Hitler's Third Reich.
   The nostalgic theme struck the chord it intended, compounding
West Germans' satisfaction over the Brussels success with a
reassurance that the Americans are still on their side.
   Bush's visit was a time of celebration for West Germans, who are
at once pleased to have made their point with NATO partners and
relieved that it didn't cost them any standing with the alliance.
   While many West Germans are opposed to nuclear weapons in their
country, they are fearful of isolation and vulnerability should
they stray too far from their traditional allies.
   ``No nukes, no troops,'' is the warning one senior U.S. official
says he has delivered to West German authorities. It raised the
possibility that if the battlefield nuclear weapons are removed the
thousands of American and British soldiers in West Germany would
soon follow.
   The NATO compromise seemed to blow away the concern, and it was
all smiles at the high-profile presidential visit.
   Larger than expected crowds of well-wishers turned out to greet
Bush and his wife, Barbara, at their public appearances, carried
live on nationwide television. The president's announcement that
West Germans would no longer need visas to visit the United States
drew thunderous cheers.
   ``A Gift From Bush for All Germans,'' the Bild newspaper gushed
in a banner headline, referring to the visa announcement. It
forecast a rosy arms control future, declaring ``Now Peace is
Really Taking Off.''
   West Germans, who often seem insecure about their standing in
the world, appeared to be relishing the international prestige
bestowed on them by Bush's visit and their role in resolving the
NATO dispute.
   Kohl expressed satisfaction with the accord on NATO defense
strategy that put off for at least two years a controversial
project to upgrade the nuclear weapons. Bush took care to share the
limelight _ declaring the compromise a victory for the NATO
alliance, not for any single point of view.
   The chancellor has pointed out repeatedly since the Brussels
accord that he will soon be talking over the new alliance position
with Gorbachev.
   The Kremlin leader arrives in Bonn on June 12 for a four-day
visit that West German officials look forward to as a chance to
keep the disarmament momentum going.
   The chancellor said in a speech in Mainz during Bush's visit
that West Germans ``see a historic chance to overcome the tensions
between East and West.''
   But making clear which side of the European divide West Germany
stands on, Kohl assured Bush, ``We will never allow our commitment
to the alliance to waver. Our future does not lie somewhere in no
man's land between East and West. Our future lies in the community
of free peoples.''
   Kohl's conservative Christian Democratic party has recently
suffered in opinion polls and regional elections because of a
general drift to the left among voters. His popularity sunk to a
dangerous low during the missile dispute, when he appeared to take
the stand against NATO in response to public pressure.
   Some U.S. officials said privately during the Bonn summit that
the compromise reached in Brussels was engineered by the Americans
to rescue Kohl from his political woes.
   Should Kohl lose power during the federal elections in December
1990, the U.S. government would likely be confronted with a
coalition of liberals more skeptical of American and NATO policies.
   Kohl seemed to acknowledge the Brussels outcome as a gift,
thanking Bush for making it possible.
   An unusually ebullient Kohl described Bush to the press as ``a
proven friend who has always stood ready to help me in difficult
times.''
   Asked by reporters whether the Brussels compromise would improve
his re-election chances, the chancellor who usually bristles at
such questions beamed and declared confidently: ``I am completely
certain as to the results of the elections in 1990.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR' NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Carol J. Williams covers West German government
affairs in Bonn for The Associated Press.
