<FIRST>r i AM-Disney     05-31 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Disney,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>Disney Studios Show Anti-Nazi Films for the First Time</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THIERRY BOINET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANNECY, France (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Walt Disney Studios screened six rare
anti-Nazi films made in 1942 and 1943 for the first time in more
than 40 years during an international animated film festival
Wednesday.
   The six clips, starring Mickey Mouse, Donald Duck and other
Disney characters, have been carefully preserved and locked up at
the Disney studios since the war.
   The 1943 clip ``Victory Through Air Power,'' based on a book by
Maj. Alexander de Seversky, depicts the importance of strategic air
bombing to Allied victory.
   Another cartoon shows Donald Duck dreaming he is condemned to
live in Nazi Germany. And in ``Donald Gets Drafted,'' the famous
duck and his friend, Pete, join the U.S. Army.
   The clips will be shown again at a retrospective exhibition in
London in November before they are returned to the studios for
safekeeping.
   Disney is aware of the extremely nationalistic content of the
clips and their use of stereotypes.
   ``It is absolutely acceptable to present these films from the
war period to professionals, to people able to appreciate this type
of animation in its context, but it wouldn't be right to reproduce
them on cassettes or to edit them for the public,'' Disney Studios
Senior Vice President Peter Schneider told The Associated Press.
   ``That would not reflect the spirit of Disney today,'' he added.
``Walt Disney has always had a progressive image, and one must
situate these clips in their right context, which is during a
special wartime period,'' he said.
   Only a thousand or people will be able to see the one-time
screening of the six cartoons. The festival officials received more
than 3,000 requests, mostly from professionals, to attend the event.
   According to Jean Lux Xibera, director of the Annecy festival,
the presence of Disney films in such an event is an event in
itself. ``Except for retrospectives, Disney has never accepted,''
he said.
   Schneider said the studio's presence at the invitation of the
organizers is part of a new policy, and it would participate in
other similar festivals.
   The Animated Film festival ends Thursday. This year, 215 films
were selected out of more than 900 for the competition.
</TEXT>
