<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary-Soviet     05-31 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-Soviet,0314</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands of Soviets Travel to Hungary to Stock Up on Goods</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tens of thousands of Soviets have taken
advantage of relaxed travel restrictions to come Hungary to buy
goods that are unavailable at home, the Hungarian news agency
reported Wednesday.
   Four new border stations were opened on the Hungarian-Soviet
border March 1, and most restrictions on travel for people living
in the border area were lifted.
   Hungary has introduced some of the most liberal travel laws in
Eastern Europe, allowing its citizens to travel as often as they
can afford to. Other East bloc countries still restrict travel of
their citizens to other Soviet bloc countries.
   According to the state news agency MTI, authorities expected no
more than 350,000 people to cross the Soviet-Hungarian border
before the end of the year. In the first three months, however, 1.5
million people have crossed the border, MTI said. Customs officials
processed 98,000 passports on a single day recently, 90 percent of
which were Soviet, MTI said.
   Shops in the border area have insufficient stocks of items in
high demand among Soviet tourists: toothpaste, soap, deodorant,
margarine and brandy, it said.
   The news agency compared the onslaught of Soviet shopping
tourists to the ``invasion'' of Austria in recent months by
Hungarian shoppers stocking up on electronic items and household
appliances. Nearly 1 million Hungarians traveled to Austria in the
week preceding the introduction of new customs regulations in April.
   There are too few currency exchange offices and gas stations in
the Soviet-Hungarian border area, MTI said. Makeshift markets have
appeared in parking lots near the border where money can be
exchanged on the black market and some goods are sold from car
trunks, the news agency said.
   Officials are to meet this week to discuss the opening of more
border-crossing stations, MTI said.
</TEXT>
