<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 1427EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Baltics     05-31 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Baltics,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baltic Parliamentarians Press for Sovereignty</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Representatives of the progressive Baltic
republics challenged the Kremlin's traditional notion of tight
central control Wednesday by pressing the new parliament to endorse
their campaign for sovereignty.
   The most radical demand to the Congress of People's Deputies
came from Anatoly Gorbunov, the president of Latvia, who said the
Soviet Constitution should be changed to ensure that the 15
republics _ not the central government _ hold the major powers.
   ``Only a republic can delegate power to the union because the
republics created the union,'' said Gorbunov, a reform-minded
protege of President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   The Latvian leader proposed recognizing the 15 republics to be
sovereign states with the power to control their own resources,
make their own laws, and conclude a new agreement of union.
   The two other Baltic republics, Estonia and Lithuania, already
have defied Moscow by declaring themselves sovereign with the right
to overturn Soviet laws.
   Gorbunov said a revision of the power structure is needed ``to
eradicate the roots of ethnic tension.''
   ``The U.S.S.R. is a union, a multinational state, formed on the
basis of agreement by equal republics, with self-determination of
nations,'' he said.
   The three Baltic nations were incorporated into the Soviet Union
in 1940 under a secret protocol between Nazi Germany and the
Kremlin, and some residents and local officials have called for the
renunciation of the agreement.
   In a speech, Lithuanian party chief Algirdas Brazauskas demanded
the Kremlin reveal the ``historical truth'' about the pact. He also
complained that Moscow bureaucrats are preventing the Baltic
republics from carrying out plans for economic independence.
   The highest-level comment on Gorbunov's radical proposals came
from Anatoly Lukyanov, elected Monday as vice president. He said
the proposals may go too far in distancing the republics from the
central government.
   ``There should be a melting of centralism, republican
self-management and local management,'' Lukyanov said in an
interview.
   Estonia's premier, Indrek Toome, stressed economic independence
in his speech to the 2,250 deputies, not mentioning his republic's
demand for veto power over laws passed in central bodies. He said
some people were trying to distort the Baltics' demands.
   ``What I mentioned does not mean the desire to somehow separate
from the all-union problems, although some people try to attach
this to us. Such an accusation is not serious because the closed
economiy is doomed. On the contrary, integration between the
republics and regions must deepen,'' Toome said.
</TEXT>
