<FIRST>r a AM-LittlePanhandler     05-31 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Little Panhandler,0217</SECOND>
<HEAD>Couple Arrested After Allegedly Using Young Daughter to Panhandle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A couple accused of sending their 3-year-old
daughter into moving traffic to panhandle money from motorists have
been charged with endangering a child.
   Carol Jean Drew, 33, and Mark C. Drew, 36, were charged Tuesday
with the Class A misdemeanor, and bond was set at $500 each, said
Sgt. William Staney.
   Police said the couple and their three children have been seen
at several busy intersections carrying signs seeking work, money
and shelter.
   Using children to solicit money is not, in itself, illegal,
Staney said. But the couple was charged with endangering a child
after witnesses reportedly told police they saw the pair send the
girl into traffic Monday.
   ``A 3-year-old's not that stable, and she's also very short, so
there's a good chance of her not being seen by some of the drivers.
It was very, very dangerous,'' Staney said.
   The girl was carrying a placard that read, ``Two-year-old _
cannot feed _ homeless _ please help,'' police said.
   The girl's parents were arrested Monday and her two brothers,
ages 10 and 12, were found alone at the family's apartment. All
three children were put in the custody of the Harris County
Children's Protective Services.
