<FIRST>r a AM-People-Hogan 1stLd-Writethru a0642 05-31 0410</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-Hogan, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0642,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>Retransmitting to make correction</HEAD>
<HEAD>Wrestler Hulk Hogan Big Hero For Little Kids</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs lead to CORRECT that Macho Man Randy Savage one person
by deleting comma.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of special education youngsters did what
Macho Man Randy Savage, King Kong Bundy and Big John Studd could
not _ they brought tears to the eyes of champion professional
wrestler Hulk Hogan.
   Hogan, chosen the favorite hero of 100 children with speech,
hearing or other learning disabilities at two public schools,
watched while the youngsters sang songs and showered him with
praise.
   ``He's a hero to us and everybody loves him like a father,''
13-year-old Quincy Brown said after the hour of skits in a
Manhattan school auditorium.
   While Hogan sat in red and black tights by the stage, his eyes
became misty. He raised a hand to one eye and later confirmed it
wasn't allergies or dust in the eye.
   ``I about started crying here,'' he told the youngsters, in
grades one through six.
   The children picked Hogan as their favorite hero in April and
wrote letters asking him to visit.
   Shelley Cohen, principal of Public School 158, said the children
were awestruck. ``I've never seen them work so hard, learn as
quickly and be so intent to impress.
   ``That's awesome power for one man to wield. If the sports
heroes can remain true to their message, they can really make a
difference.''
   For the special education children, ``following directions is a
problem, learning a sentence is a problem,'' said teacher Marcia
Golden.
   Teacher Ruth Herzel said the youngsters seem to know
instinctively who really cares about them.
   ``I think they felt he was a person they could trust, who would
not let them down. I don't think he'll prove us wrong,'' she said.
   Hogan warned the students not to take drugs and to stay in
school.
   ``The toughest fight of all is real life,'' he said. ``It's the
adults who sometimes have a hard time with it.''
   He was cheered not only by boys.
   ``I like him too,'' said 9-year-old Monique Burton.
   ``Hulk Hogan does other things besides fighting,'' Quincy Brown
said from the stage. ``He tells kids to stay in school and don't
fight with each other and most of all he says `Don't use drugs.'
   ``Hulk Hogan is a hero to all kids. He's not a hero like
Superman. Hulk Hogan is a very special hero. He's real.''
</TEXT>
