<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 1449EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-BirminghamMayor     05-31 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Birmingham Mayor,0462</SECOND>
<HEAD>Birmingham Mayor Asks for Special Prosecutor in Alleged Frame Attempt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOYT HARWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BIRMINGHAM, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mayor Richard Arrington asked on
Wednesday that a special state prosecutor be appointed to determine
whether federal agents illegally tried to frame him and other black
Birmingham officials.
   ``I have an obligation to try to remove any cloud of suspicion
over this office,'' Arrington said at a news conference.
   The mayor says a developer, Robert Moussalem of suburban
Trussville, told him FBI and Internal Revenue Service agents were
trying to entrap Arrington in a phony land deal.
   Moussalem, who has been charged with bribery, says agents were
after Arrington and other black officials from Alabama's largest
city, including City Council President William Bell, Councilman
Jeff Germany and state Rep. John Rogers. Arrington became
Birmingham's first black mayor in 1980 and is in his third term.
   The mayor released a letter in which he asked Attorney General
Don Siegelman to appoint H. Lewis Gillis of Montgomery, a former
prosecutor, as a special assistant attorney general to look into
the accusations.
   ``This investigation will focus on whether certain persons
engaged in criminal solicitation, conspiracy, attempted bribery
and-or obstruction'' of the city's governmental operations, the
letter said.
   Arrington said the city would pay Gillis' expenses but that his
investigation would be independent.
   Requests for the appointment of a particular prosecutor are not
that unusual, said Joy Patterson, a spokeswoman for Siegelman,
adding that the attorney general was not immediately available to
comment.
   U.S. Attorney Frank Donaldson has said that Moussalem's
allegations are too absurd to merit comment.
   Arrington's special counsel, Donald Watkins, said Donaldson and
the Justice Department ``have a conflict of interest in this. It
would be a conflict to prosecute Moussalem and use him as a
material witness in another matter.''
   A federal grand jury indicted Moussalem on May 1 on charges that
he tried to bribe undercover agents to call off tax audits and
investigations.
   Arrington released a copy of a Nov. 23 letter from Donaldson to
Moussalem that offered favorable consideration of his criminal
charges in exchange for his cooperation and immunity for any acts
he committed under federal direction.
   ``Unfortunately a number of black elected officials have been
put under a cloud without criminal charges against them,'' Watkins
said. ``We just want to get to the bottom of it and find out what
is going on.''
   He also said that ``there appears to be a concerted effort to
discredit and taint through innuendo certain black officials.''
   Watkins said that ``we want to find out the truth, no matter who
may be affected. Somebody is lying and we need to find out who's
lying.''
  
</TEXT>
