<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--FatherCharged     05-31 0159</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Father Charged,0162</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Charged in Baby Son's Death in Car</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT SMITH, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of leaving his infant son
unattended in a car for two hours has been charged with negligent
homicide in the boy's death.
   Mark Russell Ross, 26, pleaded innocent to the misdemeanor
charge Tuesday and was scheduled for trial Aug. 10.
   Five-month-old Mathew Ross died May 18 of suffocation, the state
medical examiner's office said.
   The child's safety seat tipped over, leaving a strap restricting
his breathing at a time when the temperature was 74 degrees and the
humidity 78 percent, said police Sgt. Bob Hicks.
   According to Hicks, Ross told officers he had left the windows
down on one side when he went into his parents' house, and that the
boy was sleeping when he returned to the car a short time later.
The father told police he found the boy dead the third time he
checked on him.
</TEXT>
