<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 1514EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Time-Swastikas     05-31 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Time-Swastikas,0481</SECOND>
<HEAD>Time Magazine Apologizes for Ad Featuring Nazi Insignia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Time magazine published a full-page apology
Wednesday for an advertisement in its British edition that featured
faded red swastikas and the slogan: ``Poor use of color can ruin
your presentation.''
   The magazine blamed it on ``a lapse,'' while the advertiser and
the ad agency admitted bad judgment and regretted any offense.
   The full-page ad in last week's edition was placed by The
Presentation Co., a London firm that offers expertise in image
enhancement through graphics.
   It showed the kind of microphoned podium used by Nazi leaders to
address crowds, with two large swastikas in the background.
   ``Using inappropriate colors can completely take the edge off an
aggressive presentation,'' the ad said in part, offering to show
``How special effects can excite a flagging audience'' and ``How
symbols can be used to explain ideas.''
   ``We can't promise to get your name in the history books, but it
should find its way into a client's notebook,'' the ad said.
   Miles Johnson, a director of The Presentation Co., said it was
``obviously a terrible error of judgment on behalf of us and our
advertising agency. We wrongly weren't aware of the distress that
it would cause a lot of people.''
   The ad gave the company's telephone number, and Johnson told The
Associated Press he received complaining calls, ``enough for us to
feel that it was offending far too many people.''
   Derek Carstens, of Tilbey and Leeves, the agency that wrote the
ad, said: ``We thought the humor would in fact ridicule the topic.
... The intention was not to offend anybody and insofar we have
offended a section of the community, we are sorry. It was an error
of judgment.'' He said the company received about 14 complaints.
   The ad appeared only in Time International's British edition,
which sells 66,000 copies. The apology, signed ``Time, the weekly
newsmagazine,'' said: ``It understandably offended many readers.
Time maintains strict procedures for acceptance of advertising
materials, but, regrettably, our system failed to prevent the
appearance of the advertisement. We apologize for the lapse.''
   Anita Blandford, in charge of Time's British sales, said the ad
``kind of slipped through the system.'' It arrived late and went
straight to the printer in Holland, she said.
   Like all Time International material, the ad was sent to New
York headquarters for approval, but the reproduction ``didn't
clearly show up the nature of the ad,'' she said.
   In New York, Brian Brown, a spokesman for Time magazine,
confirmed Ms. Blandford's account of what happened. ``The fax had
failed us,'' he said.
   He said once the ``embarrassing'' mistake was discovered, the
company rushed to put an apology in print, and had in fact delayed
the press run so that it might run in the next issue.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
