<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 1517EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon     05-31 0524</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0544</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Aoun Ready to Cooperate with Arabs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian shells exploded sporadically
around Christian ports Wednesday, and newspapers reported
beleaguered Christian Gen. Michel Aoun is willing to negotiate with
Arab League mediators.
   An-Nahar, an independent daily, also quoted a right-wing
Christian militia spokesman as threatening to seek non-Arab help if
the Arab League fails to convince Syria to withdraw its 40,000
troops from Lebanon by November.
   Beirut residents, wearied by the continued shelling and lacking
clear directives from the league, are wondering whether they should
relax or brace for another devastating confrontation.
   ``This is no war and no peace. Are they going to fight a
full-scale war again? No one has an answer,'' said Bahjat Daowe, a
bank clerk in Moslem west Beirut.
   ``Like many others, I don't know what to do. Shall I bring my
family back to Beirut or not? I really don't know.''
   About 750,000 Christians and Moslems evacuated the capital and
surrounding mountains during two months of shelling duels that
started March 8 and killed at least 360 people.
   The uncertainty is reflected in a statement of the syndicate of
non-government schools, which said it is ``considering reopening
schools soon.'' It set no date to reopen the schools closed March
14.
   Syrian gunners kept shelling Jounieh and Byblos ports north of
Beirut on Wednesday, violating a cease-fire called by heads of
state from the 22-nation Arab League.
   Police said 20 howitzer shells exploded around the ports before
dawn. No casualties were reported.
   The barrage is a daily routine by Syrian gunners tying to
prevent boats delivering ammunition to Aoun.
   A police spokesman, who cannot be identified under standing
rules, said Aoun's gunners did not return the Syrian fire.
   An-Nahar newspaper said Aoun is ``fully prepared'' to cooperate
with a three-member committee named by the Arab League last week
after its summit failed to compromise on a Lebanese peace formula.
   The committee _ King Hassan II of Morocco, Saudi Arabia's King
Fahd and Algerian President Chadli Bendjedid _ has six months to
produce a settlement to end Lebanon's 14-year civil war.
   Aoun has welcomed the Arab effort, but An-Nahar quoted an
unidentified spokesman for the Lebanese Forces Christian militia as
saying the summit's outcome was ``a big disappointment for us
because it did not call openly for a Syrian pullout.''
   Arab leaders reportedly want a Syrian withdrawal, but Syria
refused to compromise.
   The Christian militia supports Aoun's ``war of liberation'' to
drive the 40,000 Syrian troops out of Lebanon.
   An-Nahar quoted the militia spokesman as threatening to seek
non-Arab help to force a withdrawal if the committee fails.
   An-Nahar and the leftist daily As-Safir reported that foreign
ministers of Algeria, Saudi Arabia and Morocco met in Rabat,
Morocco, on Tuesday. As-Safir said they discussed establishing a
security committee to supervise implementation of the cease-fire
and monitor ports.
   The present violence broke out after Aoun ordered a blockade of
illegal ports run by Syrian-backed militias that deflect about $100
million in customs duties from government coffers.
   Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt's militia reacted by shelling the
Christian enclave with Syrian help.
</TEXT>
