<FIRST>r a AM-MysteryDeaths     05-31 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mystery Deaths,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>Medical Examiner: Some Bodies Show `Subtle' Strangulation Signs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A re-examination of the bodies of 19 young women
found dead under similar circumstances since 1986 revealed subtle
evidence suggesting some victims were strangled or suffocated, the
medical examiner said Wednesday.
   Most of the victims were cocaine addicts with a history of
prostitution. All but one were black. Their remains were found in
fields and alleys in a narrow area of Miami and neighboring Dade
County, usually in positions indicating recent sexual activity.
   Police have looked at theories ranging from a serial killer to a
previously unknown toxic cocaine reaction to explain the deaths.
Few of the victims showed signs of injury.
   Many of the remains were too badly decomposed to re-examine
thoroughly, but seven bodies showed ``scanty or subtle evidence not
inconsistent with carefully applied neck pressure,'' Dade County
Medical Examiner Dr. Joseph Davis said in a report.
   ``It is my considered opinion that the repetitive pattern of
body position, location and scene circumstances constitute a
reasonable conclusion as to manner of death _ homicide,'' he
concluded.
   The medical examiner said Dr. Richard Souviron _ a specialist in
forensic odontology who helped convict serial killer Ted Bundy by
matching bite marks on his victims _ found ``minute changes to
indicate mild or moderate pressure to the mouth.''
   Debilitated by drug use, the victims could quickly lose
consciousness without putting up much of a struggle, Davis said.
   John Farrell, chief of the Metro-Dade's Police detective
division, said police have the treated the deaths all along as
potential murders.
   ``There's a lot of this we don't understand and we don't have
the answers,'' Farrell said. ``Davis is saying, `It's my feeling
this is homicide, and I'm the boss.'''
   The detective cautioned that the medical examiner, while
suggesting the women were murdered, ``is not saying that
absolutely.''
   He said police were still looking at the theory that a toxic
cocaine reaction, perhaps in conjunction with sex, caused the
deaths. Investigators have also questioned a rapist, now in jail,
with a history of choking his victims into unconsciousness.
   Farrell emphasized that the deaths were all associated with
``people in crack-house environments'' and said that whatever the
cause, there seemed to be little or no risk to the public.
</TEXT>
