<FIRST>r w AM-Secord     05-31 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Secord,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Suggests Nov. 13 as Possible Trial Date</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Iran-Contra trial of Richard Secord might
not take place until November or later, lawyers and a federal judge
said Wednesday.
   At a hearing, prosecutor Reid Weingarten suggested Nov. 13 as
``a possible trial date, with the court's permission.''
   Chief U.S. District Court Judge Aubrey Robinson cautioned that
such a date is ``predicated on no major ... problems'' pertaining
to the use at trial of material that is now classified by the
government.
   Secord's lawyer, Thomas Green, said ``there is some potential
for complications'' because the government may be reluctant to
declassify some of the material for use in the courtroom.
   Secord, enlisted by Oliver North to run arms to the Contras, is
accused in two indictments of conspiring, offering and paying
illegal gratuities to North and of covering up Secord's alleged
profits from the Iran-Contra affair.
   The government wants to consolidate the cases, but Secord says
the nine cover-up charges, brought April 7, should be dismissed.
They represent ``prosecutorial vindictiveness,'' Secord said in
court papers.
   The office of independent counsel Lawrence Walsh wants to
combine them, saying ``proof of the two sets of charges will
entirely overlap.''
   The gratuities counts were brought on March 16, 1988, as part of
a larger indictment accusing Secord of conspiring with North to
defraud the U.S. government by diverting money to the Contras from
secret arms sales to Iran. Also charged with conspiracy and theft
were former national security adviser John Poindexter and Secord
business partner Albert Hakim.
   Due to national security concerns, the prosecution is expected
to abandon the conspiracy and theft counts against Secord.
   Presenting evidence of such charges would entail a significant
amount of now-classified material and for this reason identical
conspiracy and theft charges were dismissed in January against
North.
   ``Hoping to save what is left of the 1988 indictment,'' the
government seeks to combine the ``weak, remaining counts'' with the
new indictment in an ``unfair attempt to create an aura of
wrongdoing about General Secord,'' he said in court papers.
</TEXT>
