<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 1512EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Bush-RiverCruise     05-31 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-River Cruise,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Cruise Provides Picturesque Finale to Visit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KOBLENZ, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   On a riverboat that charges
tourists $17 a ride, President Bush and Chancellor Helmut Kohl
cruised down the Rhine River on Wednesday past hillside vineyards
and ancient castles silhouetted atop rugged ridgelines.
   Of course, Bush did not get the standard tour. And for him, it
was free.
   The three-deck Stolzenfels, occasionally used for state dinners,
was redecorated with Persian carpets on indoor decks.
   It was staffed with white-gloved waiters carrying trays of
champagne, wine and beer and hovering over an elaborate buffet.
   With brilliant blue skies, warm weather and friendly crowds
waving from the shores, the trip was a picture-perfect windup to
Bush's 27-hour visit to West Germany.
   The president called it ``an unforgettable day on the Rhine.''
   To make sure the excursion received maximum television and photo
coverage, the White House chartered a second riverboat for
cameramen and photographers who followed Bush's boat. The photo
boat, with a capacity of 1,000 or more, carried only a handful of
people.
   About 300 guests were invited on Bush's boat from political
circles, the arts, social and industrial fields.
   Bush began the trip by receiving a case of local wines from
Petra Mayer, a queen of the wine-growing region.
   He rewarded her with a kiss on the cheek. At the urging of
photographers, and as his wife Barbara watched on, Bush kissed the
young lady again.
   And for good measure, he kissed her a third time. Mrs. Bush
raised her eyes in mock dismay.
   Bush has been ebullient in the wake of the NATO summit in
Brussels, where he won endorsement for his conventional-arms
proposal to the Soviet Union and helped defuse an alliance dispute
over short-range nuclear missiles.
   The two-hour river trip began at Oberwesel, a town which still
retains a medieval appearance and is dominated by the sight of the
1,000-year-old Schonburg Castle. It concluded at Koblenz, an
ancient city where the Moselle River flows into the Rhine.
   As the Stolzenfels plied the river, a male choir serenaded the
Bushes with the legend of the Loreley, the ``wondrous maiden''
whose siren song lured sailors to shipwreck and death.
   The waterway path through the Rhine's deeply-cut valley is one
of Germany's most popular tourist attractions, followed by millions
each year.
   The path is lined with picturesque castles and carefully tended
vineyards clinging to the hillsides.
   Tourists pay about $17 for a trip as long as Bush's, but they
don't get the same VIP attention.
   A cannon salute marked the beginning and end of Bush's ride.
   Two helicopters hovered high overhead throughout the trip and
four police boats doggedly trailed the ship.
   On both shores, a caravan of police cars and troop vehicles
drove slowly to keep pace with Bush's boat.
   At town after town, crowds of people turned out to wave to the
president.
   Concluding the trip at Koblenz, Bush went to the Deutsches Eck,
a world famous ``memorial of German unity'' where he signed the
town book. He said he hoped this week's NATO summit would be viewed
in the future as one of ``historic consequence.''
   From Germany, Bush flew to London for talks with Prime Minister
Margaret Thatcher and a luncheon Thursday with Queen Elizabeth II.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
