<FIRST>u i AM-Cruise 1stLd-Writethru a0606 05-31 0582</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cruise, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0606,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cancel Tax-Funded Caribbean Cruise for Offenders After Outcry</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughoput with cruise canceled.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVA JANZON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Local politicians, apparently reacting
to public uproar, decided Wednesday not to send a group of teen-age
offenders on a six-month rehabilitation cruise to the Caribbean at
taxpayer expense.
   The social board in the suburb of Kista dropped plans to
participate in the cruise after it received a bomb threat.
   Social commissioner Ragnar Gotestam later announced on TV that
the project had to be canceled because at least two community
social boards had changed their mind about the $80,000 cruise on a
53-foot sailing craft to Saint Lucia and other Caribbean islands.
He said he hoped to pursue the project later.
   Eight teen-agers convicted of crimes such as assault, theft,
burglary and property damage were candidates for the training
cruise. At least three social workers would have accompanied them.
   The program also called for instruction in citizenship, and
authorites had given assurances there would be no chance to escape.
   Sweden's liberal penal system accents rehabilitation rather than
punishment, but it has come under increasing criticism recently as
too lenient.
   The daily newspaper Svenska Dagbladet added its voice to those
critics of the cruise.
   ``How could the district social board in unison make a decision
so distant from reason and judgment and with such total lack of
contact with the way ordinary people think?'' it asked in an
editorial.
   Authorities argued the offenders were influenced by their family
background and rough neighborhoods, and that getting away would be
more helpful than harsh punishment.
   None of the eight is serving prison sentences, although they
must report regularly to the authorities. Their behavior was deemed
so bad that no halfway houses would accept them.
   ``These children need love and security,'' said Stockholm Social
Director Ulf Andersson, defending the Caribbean trip for the
youths, who under press regulations have not been identified.
   ``This is not a vacation, but a working trip,'' said Anders
Roxe, who would have escorted them. He told Swedish Radio that 400
convicts had gone through the training program in Swedish waters
and 200 are employed as officers at sea.
   ``People should be happy to get rid of them, and maybe to see
these people being reintegrated into a working life as new men
after six months,'' he said.
   Among the opponents of the cruise program are National Police
Chief Bjorn Eriksson and Youth Minister Margot Wallstrom. They
ridiculed the idea of sending the youths to an area where drugs
abound.
   Last year, a similar public furor forced authorities to scrap
plans to send a convicted criminal on a trip to the Egyptian
pyramids. The authorities had said it would help the convict, who
was about to be released, to readjust to society.
   Swedish prisons have a generous furlough program. After
completing one-third of their sentence, prisoners are eligible for
up to six 48-hour passes a year. The prison service reported 287
violations out of 8,951 furloughs granted in 1987.
   Prisons also have frequent conjugal visits for most inmates.
   The system came under scathing attack when Sweden's most
notorious spy, Stig Bergling, slipped away while on furlough in
1987 and apparently escaped with his wife to the Soviet Union.
   In another experiment, long-term prisoners can spend two-week
vacations relaxing with their families in an unguarded holiday
village in central Sweden, with skiing in winter, hiking in the
woods, or swimming in summer.
</TEXT>
