<FIRST>u w AM-FactoryOrders     05-31 0382</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Factory Orders,380</SECOND>
<HEAD>Factory Orders Up Strong 2.7 Percent in April</HEAD>
<BYLINE>With Economy Bjt ^By JOHN D. McCLAIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders to factories for manufactured goods
rose in April for the second straight month in the biggest increase
since December, the Commerce Department reported Wednesday.
   The strong 2.7 percent April gain followed a 0.7 percent hike in
March and 1.2 percent and 2 percent declines in January and
February. Orders had soared 4.7 percent in December.
   Total orders registered $239.4 billion on a seasonably adjusted
basis in April.
   Robert Brusca, an economist with Nikko Securities Co.
International Inc. in New York, compared the factory orders report
with the Index of Leading Economic Indicators which Commerce also
released on Wednesday.
   Factory orders were ``absolutely surprising,'' he said, while
the indicators showed a slower 0.8 percent increase after falling
for two months.
   ``It means,'' he said, ``the porridge is not too hot, not too
cold and it isn't just right. We're just vacillating between the
two, I think.''
   Bruce Steinberg of Merrill Lynch Capital Markets in New York
said the orders report ``means that in April the economy picked up
from a depressed level in March.
   ``And yet ... orders were not higher in April than in
December.'' Steinberg said. ``So although the industrial sector of
the economy is still advancing, it doesn't have anywhere the kind
of momentum it had in 1988.''
   Commerce said both durable and nondurable orders rose in April,
with durables up 3 percent to $129.2 billion. It said all major
industries expect fabricated metals participated in the increase.
   Electrical machinery orders were up 9.3 percent to $20 billion;
primary metals such as steel up 6 percent to $12.6 billion and
transportation equipment up 1.4 percent to $37.6 billion. The
highly volatile transportation segment was up 11 percent in March
and down 7.6 percent in February.
   Orders for non-durable goods jumped 2.4 percent to $110.2
billion, the department reported. Nearly half the increase was in
the petroleum refining industry.
   The overall increase would have been higher except for a 15.8
percent drop in defense orders which are subject to wide swings
depending on when big contracts are signed.
   Excluding defense, orders rose 3.6 percent after falling 0.3
percent in March and 2.7 percent in February.
</TEXT>
