<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 2019EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-North     05-31 0521</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-North,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>North Says Judge Should Set Aside His Convictions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oliver North says a judge should set aside his
convictions in the Iran-Contra affair because the prosecution made
critical errors, including failure to show any principal figure
``intended to violate the law.''
   In court papers filed late Tuesday, North said the government
neglected to show that anyone intended to obstruct Congress when
North, in November 1986, assisted in assembling a false chronology
of an arms shipment to Iran.
   North was convicted of aiding and abetting the obstruction, but
``a fundamental requirement of any conviction for aiding and
abetting is that the jury first find a guilty principal,'' the
court papers said.
   The government ``did not demonstrate that any principal intended
to violate the law and to obstruct Congress in November 1986,''
North's lawyers said in their filing in U.S. District Court.
   Former national security adviser John Poindexter is charged with
obstruction and making false statements to Congress in connection
with the chronology. Poindexter is expected to go on trial later
this year.
   The false chronology said no one in the U.S. government knew
until January 1986 that a November 1985 shipment to Iran contained
arms. Evidence presented at North's trial showed he and more than a
dozen U.S. officials received intelligence in 1985 detailing the
shipment's contents.
   North also was convicted of altering and destroying official
documents he wrote to national security adviser Robert McFarlane
detailing North's assistance to the Nicaraguan Contra rebels.
   North is scheduled for sentencing June 23.
   In the court papers, North said he should be acquitted because
testimony at the trial showed he wasn't the custodian of the
documents.
   North also was convicted of accepting a $13,800 home security
system from Iran-Contra co-defendant Richard Secord. North, who
lives outside Washington in northern Virginia, said the charge
should have been brought in courts there, rather than in Washington.
   If the court refuses to acquit North, he should be granted a new
trial on the three charges for which he was convicted, he said.
   The former National Security Council aide said U.S. District
Court Judge Gerhard Gesell had given improper instructions to the
jury. Gesell, according to North's lawyers, placed too many
restrictions on North's defense, which was based on the assertion
that all of the actions for which he was charged with crimes were
authorized by his superiors.
   Gesell's instructions ``unconstitutionally limited the jury's
consideration'' of evidence in the case, said North.
   On Wednesday, Secord opposed a prosecution motion to consolidate
two sets of criminal charges against him in the Iran-Contra affair.
   Secord was indicted on March 16, 1988. Among the charges were
conspiring, offering and paying illegal gratuities to North.
   Enlisted by North to run arms to the Contras, Secord also was
indicted April 7 for covering up from Congress his alleged profits
from the Iran and Contra initiatives.
   The government wants to combine charges from the two
indictments, but Secord said in court papers that the latest
indictment reflects ``prosecutorial vindictiveness'' and fails to
state a criminal offense. Secord is seeking to dismiss the new
charges.
</TEXT>
