<SECOND>AM-Bush-Servicemen,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soldiers, Families Hail President's European Trip</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE BOEHMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 2,000 American servicemen
and their families gave President Bush an enthusiastic sendoff from
Rhein Main Air Base on Wednesday, expressing hope that his
disarmament initiatives succeed.
   Bush flew by helicopter to the sprawling Air Force base just six
miles south of Frankfurt on the last stop of his West German visit
before leaving for London.
   The crowd gathered on the tarmac at the airbase cheered,
applauded and waved small American flags when the president arrived.
   First Sgt. Marcelles Sneed, 40, of Millington, Tenn., said he
had followed news of the president's trip closely.
   ``It's been impressive the stand he has taken with (Soviet
President Mikhail) Gorbachev,'' Sneed said. ``He's met the
challenge. I hope it works, but I don't know if I trust the
Russians.''
   Master Sgt. Carlton Bryan, of Cambridge, Md., commenting on
Bush's proposal to reduce U.S. troop strength in Europe, said: ``I
think a lot of people back home will be happy about that.''
   Debbie Barton, 30, of Monticello, Ill., waited for Bush's
arrival with her son Chris, 12, and 9-year-old daughter Amber.
   Mrs. Barton, who said she has been in West Germany for three
years with her husband, Capt. Ron Barton, said she was enthusiastic
about Bush's European trip.
   ``I have high hopes for what he's doing,'' Mrs. Barton said.
   Asked if she also hoped that Gorbachev would respond with
further disarmament initiatives, Mrs. Barton said: ``I think if
they can work together, then we won't be so scared of each other.''
   One of the happiest people was Jeanine Greenwood of Rapid City,
S.D., who waited more than two hours for Bush to arrive, and got to
shake the president's hand.
   What did she say to Bush? ``I said `God bless you' and he said
`Thank you, m'am.'''
   Counting servicemen and family members, about 10,000 Americans
are assigned to Rhein Main Air Base.
