<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     05-31 0596</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0623</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright &amp; Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Motorists who parked on a one-way street and
later found that the street direction had been changed _ and that
they had been ticketed for parking the wrong way _ can get their
tickets thrown out.
   The statement came in response to news stories about hapless
motorists who parked on one-way streets near the federal court
building April 19.
   Johnny Miller, a security officer for the federal appeals court,
said he saw parking officers writing tickets before workers even
finished changing the signs.
   Parking against the flow of traffic is a $15 offense in New
Orleans.
   ``Anyone who has already paid a ticket can request a refund from
the administrative hearing office,'' said Tuesday's news release
from Betty Jo Everett, director of the Streets Department.
   Those who haven't paid the ticket yet can have it dismissed by
contacting city officials, she said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Rambling With Gambling,'' a morning talk show
on which a Gambling named John has been host for 64 years, logged
its 20,000th live broadcast Wednesday on radio station WOR.
   ``And we're going to attempt to keep it going as long as we can,
because it's too much fun to give up,'' John R. Gambling told his
listeners.
   John R., 38, joined his father, John A., as co-host in 1985.
   John A., 59, had taken over the show in 1959 from his father,
John B.
   John B., who died in 1974, was a studio sound engineer who
started it all by chance in September 1925. The host of a morning
calisthenics program couldn't make it and ``Sparks'' Gambling was
pressed into service.
   Under John B., the program evolved from exercise to music and
entertainment.
   ``Then it changed to information and news and moves along pretty
sprightly,'' said John A.
   Among the show's numerous firsts on local air were newscasts,
school closing bulletins, airborne traffic reports and other
listener information services that have become staples of wake-up
radio.
   For show No. 20,000, John R. and John A. set up their studio in
the Rainbow Room on the 65th floor of the RCA Building and served
breakfast to 200 fans who won their invitations in a contest.
   The Gamblings maintain that filling 4{ hours of air time five
mornings a week is a snap.
   ``There's usually not enough time,'' said John R. ``Today is a
perfect example. We have hours of tape that we never got to.''
   With lines of well wishers waiting to shake his hand, John R.
said he'd hang around for about an hour, ``then go back to the
studio and start preparing for tomorrow, for 20,001.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Venice Beach can remain the ``Skating Capital
of the World.''
   Armed with nearly 2,000 signatures and the support of
Councilwoman Ruth Galanter, skating enthusiasts scored a victory in
their ongoing battle with authorities to keep roller skating and
skate boarding legal in Venice Beach.
   The City Council voted 9-1 Tuesday to begin a repeal of the
decade-old ban of the pastime along Ocean Front Walk in the beach
community.
   ``Skating, all right!'' said Harry Perry, a Venice street
musician who attended the council meeting with a guitar slung over
his shoulder, a white turban wrapped around his head, shin guards
and roller skates.
   ``We are the victors!'' he exclaimed.
   ``It's unfair to enforce a law no one was ever told about,'' Ms.
Galanter told her colleagues.
   Perry, who has been skating the boardwalk since 1976, said the
next battle is to give skaters access to bike paths.
