<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 2102EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Khashoggi     05-31 0386</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Khashoggi,0397</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Seeks Extradition of Saudi Arms Dealer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY CZUCZKA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Switzerland received the formal U.S. request
Wednesday for extradition of Adnan Khashoggi, the jailed Saudi
financier and arms dealer accused of helping Ferdinand and Imelda
Marcos plunder the Philippines.
   The American request, accompanied by 243 pages of evidence,
arrived six weeks after police arrested Khashoggi, 54, while he was
having breakfast at a luxury hotel in Bern. The U.S. Embassy had
asked that he be detained.
   A Justice Ministry statement said the Swiss federal police were
studying the extradition request. Ministry spokesman Joerg Kistler
said it was too early to tell when a decision would be made.
   Lawyers for Khashoggi said a few days after his arrest April 18
that they would do everything possible to prevent extradition, but
have not taken legal steps to challenge his detention.
   Ralph Zloczower, Khashoggi's Swiss lawyer, was not available
Wednesday night. A secretary at his Bern office said he would have
no comment.
   If Switzerland decides the U.S. charges have legal foundation,
Khashoggi will be granted a hearing, the Justice Ministry said. An
extradition order can be appealed to the Federal Tribunal,
Switzerland's supreme court.
   Khashoggi, the Marcoses, five other people and a California bank
were indicted in October by a U.S. District Court in New York. The
indictment accuses the ousted president and his wife of stealing
more than $100 million from the Philippine treasury to buy real
estate and expensive art in New York.
   The U.S. government says Khashoggi posed as owner of some of the
assets as a cover, according to prosecutors.
   Khashoggi is charged in the indictment with racketeering,
conspiracy, obstruction of justice and mail fraud. Racketeering
alone carries a penalty of up to 20 years in prison.
   Swiss authorities said a U.S. diplomatic note asking that
Khashoggi be arrested cited four buildings in Manhattan and a
collection of paintings that disappeared from a Manila museum.
   Pierre Schmid, deputy director of the Swiss federal police, has
said Khashoggi allegedly bought them for his friend Marcos as part
of ``obfuscation maneuvers.''
   Khashoggi is said to have been the main financier and middleman
of the Iran-Contra affair, in which proceeds of secret U.S. arms
sales to Iran where channeled to rebels fighting the leftist
Sandinista government in Nicaragua.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
