<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 2054EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SecondAbduction     05-31 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Second Abduction,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mother Who Reported Two Babies Abducted Is Indicted in 1986 Infant
Death</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERSEYVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who said masked gunmen abducted
her two baby girls nearly three years apart was indicted Wednesday
on charges of concealing a homicide and obstructing justice in the
1986 death of one daughter.
   The grand jury indictment charged Paula Sims of Alton with
concealing a homicide and three counts of obstructing justice in
the death of 13-day-old Loralei Sims.
   Investigators have said the disappearance and death in late
April of the Sims' second daughter, 6-week-old Heather, renewed
interest in the earlier case.
   No charges have been filed in Heather's death, which came after
Mrs. Sims and her husband, Robert, moved to neighboring Madison
County, where an investigation is under way.
   Jersey County State's Attorney Richard Ringhausen brought the
charges against Mrs. Sims in Loralei's death earlier this month,
then presented evidence and witnesses to the grand jury.
   Donald Groshong, attorney for the Simses, would not comment on
the indictment.
   Mrs. Sims remains free on a $10,000 cash bond and no court date
has been set.
   By asking a grand jury, rather than a judge in open court, to
bring the case to trial, Ringhausen was able to keep secret
information from the pending Madison County investigation, he said.
   In 1987, the couple claimed Fifth Amendment protection against
self-incrimination and refused to testify before a Jersey County
grand jury that conducted an earlier investigation into Loralei's
death.
   That grand jury returned no indictments and the case remained
open.
   Robert Sims, 37, told police last month he suspected his
29-year-old wife may have killed both babies accidentally,
investigators have said.
   In each case, Mrs. Sims said a masked gunman took her baby girl
while her husband was at work.
   Loralei was reported abducted in June 1986. Her body was
discovered a week later in a wooded area about 150 yards from the
Simses' home.
   Heather was reported abducted on April 29. Her body was
discovered four days later in a trash can in West Alton, Mo.,
across the Mississippi River from Alton.
   A third Sims child, a 16-month-old boy, has been in the custody
of the Department of Children and Family Services since shortly
after Heather's disappearance.
</TEXT>
