<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 2108EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Women     05-31 0415</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Women,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey Says Israelis Favor Affirmative Action for Women</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most Israelis favor affirmative action for
women, tax breaks for child care, and a longer school day to allow
more mothers to work full time, according to preliminary results of
a survey conducted Wednesday.
   The informal survey, described by Israel Radio as the most
extensive done in Israel, was organized by Naamat, the women's
organization of the Histadrut Trade Union Federation.
   The goal was to demonstrate to Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir's
government and the public that there is strong support for Naamat's
campaign for greater economic rights for women.
   While the level of education of Israeli women is comparable to
that in other developed countries, the women's movement has not won
the same support here as in the United States and Europe.
   Ethia Simcha, the prime minister's adviser on the status of
women, noted that 51 percent of all government workers are women,
but only 11 percent hold management jobs. Only 2 percent of all
government-run companies are headed by women, Ms. Simcha said.
   ``There is not enough consciousness about women's rights in this
country,'' said Naamat spokeswoman Carmel Eytan. ``One of the aims
of the poll is to raise public debate on these questions.''
   Ms. Eytan said more than 500,000 surveys were turned in, about
one-third of them by men.
   She said according to results based on about half the survey
responses:
   _ Ninety percent support extending the school day past 2 p.m. so
more mothers may work full time.
   _ Seventy-four percent approve of tax breaks for child care.
   _ Seventy-five percent support changes in the tax law that would
allow women to file separate returns.
   _ Only about two-thirds of the respondents support affirmative
actions programs for women.
   ``Most people against were men,'' she added.
   Israeli women and men lined up at about 2,000 sites set up in
banks, day care centers, supermarkets and on sidewalks across the
country to take part in the survey.
   At a busy intersection near a Tel Aviv shopping center,
organizers set up a cardboard box on the pavement. In a 15-minute
period, about 40 people dropped off questionnaires.
   ``I'm really surprised by the number of people voting. I don't
know what I'll do when our box is full,'' said a Naamat volunteer.
   Ms. Eytan said she hoped that several hundred thousand Israelis
over 18 would participate in the survey. Israel has a population of
4.2 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
