<DOCNO> AP890531-0159 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 1634EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i RebelsImposeTransportBan;RightistPresidenttoTakeOffice
    05-31 0583</FIRST>
<SECOND>Rebels Impose Transport Ban; Rightist President to Take Office</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE CABRERA </BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist rebels paralyzed public
transportation Wednesday and said they would make this Central
American nation ungovernable on the eve of the inauguration of a
rightist president.
   Alfredo Cristiani of the right-wing Republican National
Alliance, also known as Arena, takes office Thursday in El
Salvador's first transfer of power from one elected president to
another.
   But Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front rebels called on
the nation's 5.5 million citizens to boycott public transportation
for an indefinite period starting Wednesday. There was no urban or
inter-city bus service on the ban's first day, dispatchers said.
   Troops in the capital seized a large cache of weapons blonging
to the rebels who have waged a nine-year civil war against the
government, police said in a communique. The seizure netted more
than 350 Soviet-made rifles, 300 sticks of dynamite and more than
1.5 million bullets, police said.
   Cristiani, 41, a businessman and coffee grower, was elected on
March 19 in an election with the lowest voter turnout in a decade.
The low turnout was partly attributed to a rebel transport boycott,
and many said the rebel action cost the centrist candidate the
election.
   The transport ban has been a favorite tactic of rebels, who
threaten to shoot at or set fire to cars or buses found on the
roads. Five traffic bans were enforced last year.
   Wednesday's boycott paralyzed all collective and cargo
transporation nationwide.
   ``There is nothing. No buses have left and the terminal is
empty,'' said a dispatcher in one of San Salvador's bus terminals.
``We are 100 percent paralyzed. The companies are stopped because
nobody wants their equipment destroyed,'' the dispatcher said.
   Guerrillas have been bombing power lines and utility poles
nightly.
   The military has mounted a security operation for the election
that includes air and land surveillance patrols nationwide.
   According to the armed forces public information office, seven
guerrillas have died and eight government soldiers have been
injured in incidents around the country since Tuesday. The rebel
radio station, Venceremos, said guerrillas killed eight soldiers
and wounded 22, but did not list figures for its own fighters.
   Three Central American leaders are scheduled to be among 36
countries sending delegations to Thursday's inauguration. The
Foreign Ministry said the Central American presidents attending
would be Vinicio Cerezo of Guatemala, Jose Azcona of Honduras and
Oscar Arias of Costa Rica.
   President Jose Napoleon Duarte, 63, who is dying of liver
cancer, will be the first elected Salvadoran president to hand
power to another elected civilian.
   Cristiani's first task in his five-year term will be to convince
the political opposition and international community that he is in
charge. Arena opponents and even some party regulars say that
Cristiani is a front for business interests. They also express
concern about his party's connection to right-wing death squads.
   Arena was founded in 1981 by a cashiered army major and alleged
death-squad leader, Roberto d'Aubisson, who still is considered the
party's leader. The party has been linked to death squads which are
blamed for up to half the 70,000 deaths in the civil war.
D'Aubisson and Arena deny any connection to the death squads.
   But the U.S. has decided to continue supporting the Salvadoran
government unless death squad activity, which has lessened in
recent years, resumes in full force. The United States pumps more
than $1 million daily into El Salvador in economic and military
aide.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
