<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A private judge has been hired to consider a
settlement offer in the palimony lawsuit filed by actress Sondra
Locke against movie tough guy Clint Eastwood, a newspaper reported
Wednesday.
   Neither side has disclosed the name of the judge or where the
closed hearing will be held, but the Los Angeles Times said
attorneys for the stars were to go before the judge Wednesday.
   Miss Locke, who was Eastwood's companion for 13 years while
legally married to another man, offered a settlement that included
a Bel-Air home the couple shared; a Hollywood Hills house Eastwood
was said to have bought for Miss Locke and her husband, sculptor
Gordon Anderson; monthly payments of as much as $15,000 for the
next seven years, and a $250,000 one-time payment.
   Eastwood rejected the offer, but it will likely be discussed in
a hearing, the newspaper reported.
   Since the wait for trial in civil lawsuits filed in Los Angeles
County is routinely three to five years, many litigants are turning
to private arbitration or to rent-a-judge firms. The wait for a
judge is about a month and many disputes are settled in a matter of
hours. Also for those seeking to keep their trial proceedings
secret, the news media can be barred from rent-a-judge courtrooms
if both parties agree.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>Eds: A version of the following has moved on the sports wire.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Detroit Tigers' team physician isn't issuing
any timetables for Manager Sparky Anderson's return but does say
he's optimistic.
   Anderson was sent home to California May 19 to recuperate from
exhaustion.
   Dr. Clarence Livingood wouldn't predict Tuesday how long
Anderson will remain on his rest and recuperation leave, but said
the Tiger manager is playing golf, resting and getting better.
   ``It won't be long before Sparky is itching to come back, now
that he is feeling better. He still might want to come back before
it's advisable to come back, so we're going to be very cautious,''
Livingood said. ``We can't let him return to a busy schedule before
he's completely rested.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Bob Hawke is to star
with his granddaughter in a television special on the environment.
   A spokesman announced Wednesday that Hawke and 4-year-old Sophie
will introduce a 90-minute award-winning program called ``Climate
in Crisis'' next Tuesday.
   In his introduction, Hawke says: ``Sophie's now 4. In the year
2000 she will be 15 _ not all that far from adulthood, with her own
dreams and aspirations.
   ``How successfully she and other children can fulfill their
goals depends increasingly on how we look after our environment and
how we best use this planet's natural resources.''
   The environment has become a major political issue in Australia,
where conservationists are waging a strong campaign again logging
of the country's rainforests and beach pollution off Sydney, the
most-populated city.
