<TEXT>
   When tennis pro Ivan Lendl isn't collecting Grand
Slam titles and trophies, he's busy collecting the works of an
artist of the Belle Epoque famous for posters and packaging.
   Taking time away from the French Open tennis tournament, the
world's No. 1-ranked player toured the Musee de la Publicite, where
more than 100 works by Alphonse Mucha from Lendl's personal
collection are on display through July 17.
   ``The drawings are beautiful, but the colors are fascinating,
especially the red,'' said Lendl.
   The show also features a glimpse of Lendl relaxing at home.
Every wall of his 15-room Connecticut mansion is decorated with a
Mucha poster, painting, calendar or package wrapping, even in the
bathrooms.
   Like Lendl, Mucha was born in Czechoslovakia. The graphic
artist, who died in 1939, is best known for distinctive designs of
sweet-faced girls with flowing tresses that graced objects from
cookie jars to perfume atomizers.
