<FIRST>r i AM-Taiwan     05-31 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Taiwan,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Premier Announces Minor Cabinet Shuffle</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHIRLEY LAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The newly appointed premier Wednesday
named three Cabinet ministers and fired four in a minor government
shake-up, the ruling Nationalist Party said.
   The new 25-member Cabinet will be sworn in Thursday, officials
said.
   Lee Huan on Tuesday replaced 75-year-old Yu Kuo-hwa as Taiwan's
premier. Yu, who was premier for five years, was criticized for his
cautious approach to the country's economic and political troubles.
He had been considered a political liability in upcoming
parliamentary elections.
   Lee made only minor changes in the Cabinet because he helped
groom many of the incumbent ministers as ruling party
secretary-general, officals said.
   Clement Chang, speaker of the Taipei City Council, was named
minister of communications. He replaces Kuo Nan-hung who was made a
minister without portfolio.
   The new premier also fired two ministers without portfolios, Kao
Yu-shu, and Shen Chun-shan, and named law professor Chang Chien-han
to fill one of the vacancies. The second post was not filled.
   Lee's Cabinet changes were unanimously approved by both
President Lee Teng-hui and by the Nationalist Party's policy-making
committee. The party also appointed James Soong, 47, to succeed Lee
as secretary-general.
   Lee, 72, was secretary-general of the Nationalist Party from
1987 until his appointment as premier. His reformist approach is
popular with the public, and party officials expect this to benefit
the Nationalists in December elections.
   Professor Chang Ling-chen, a political scientist at National
Taiwan University, said Lee can be expected to respond to public
demands for a clearcut policy toward mainland China, and tackle
Taiwan's worsening labor, pollution and economic problems.
   The Nationalists, who fled to Taiwan in 1949 after losing a
civil war on mainland China, claim they are the legitimate rulers
of all China.
   They have rejected any official contacts with the Chinese
Communists, but two years ago adopted a more lenient policy that
has permitted Taiwanese and Chinese to exchange visits and trade
through third countries.
</TEXT>
