<FIRST>r w AM-NursingShortage     05-31 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>njpas</SECOND>
<HEAD>AM-Nursing Shortage,380</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bills To Ease Nursing Shortage Criticized by Federal Officials</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Department of Health and Human Services
gave a tepid reception Wednesday to bills aimed at helping to
alleviate the nursing shortage by allowing nurses from other
countries to remain in the United States after their visas expire.
   ``It is unclear to us how much benefit will be gained by the
various immigration proposals that are before this committee,'' Dr.
J. Jarrett Clinton told members of the House Judiciary Committee's
subcommittee on immigration, refugees and international law.
Clinton is director of the department's bureau of health
professions.
   The subcommittee was hearing testimony on a bill introduced by
Rep. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., that would create a new visa category
for foreign nurses whose visas are on the brink of expiring. The
subcommittee was also looking into portions of a broader bill
introduced by Rep. Gary Ackerman, D-N.Y.
   Schumer said he was worried about thousands of Filipino nurses
in New York City hospitals. Many hold visas which allowed them to
stay in the country for five years. Last year, the Immigration and
Naturalization Service extended those visas for one more year but
Schumer's bill would create a new immigration category to enable
the nurses to become U.S. residents.
   Rep. Bruce Morrison, D-Conn., subcommittee chairman, pressured
Clinton to outline the administration's policy on these nurses,
noting that the department sent a representative to the hearing
with great reluctance.
   ``We're not seeing the leadership we need,'' Morrison said. ``We
would like to know more about where HHS is going in the overall
planning and ... what role foreign nurses play in the long run, so
that our immigration policy can be integrated with other policies.''
   But Clinton downplayed the problem of foreign nurses, noting
that of some 1.6 million registered nurses working in the United
States, perhaps 16,000 are working under visas like those of the
New York City nurses.
   ``It looks to me like less than 1 percent, and we have to decide
whether it's worth the energy it takes,'' he said.
   James Puleo, assistant commissioner of adjudications and
nationality in the Immigration and Naturalization Service, said his
agency found the Schumer bill ``too generous in its requirements
for special immigrant status.''
   Stephen H. Cooper, vice president of the Hospital Association of
New York State, said Schumer's bill ``is important to American
nurses.''
   ``Without foreign nurses, our already over-extended nurses would
be unable to cope,'' he said in prepared remarks.
</TEXT>
