<FIRST>u i AM-Israel-Lebanon     05-31 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Lebanon,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Warplanes Raid Targets in South Lebanon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By AHMED MANTASH</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SIDON, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Israeli warplanes attacked south Lebanon
bases of Palestinian guerrillas and a pro-Iranian militia Wednesday
in response to increased guerrilla activity in the border area.
   Police said four jets fired six rockets at a cluster of
Palestinian bases east of Sidon, provincial capital of south
Lebanon at 7 p.m.
   A two-story command post used by three radical guerrilla
factions was demolished, they said, and at least five guerrillas
were missing and presumed dead. Nine guerrillas were wounded, the
police reported.
   Six F-4 fighter-bombers fired eight rockets at bases of the
pro-Iranian Shiite militia Hezbollah in the Bekaa Valley of
southeast Lebanon at 7:15 p.m., according to the police report.
   A spokesman said Hezbollah's headquarters in Suhmor village east
of Mashgara was destroyed, along with a nearby ammunition dump and
a garage used to repair guerrilla vehicles.
   He said several Israeli helicopter gunships hovered over the
bases near Sidon more than two hours after the raid.
   ``They dropped parachute flares that lit the night sky as
guerrillas were searching with torchlights for the missing victims
under the rubble,'' he said. ``We don't know if the helicopters
also bombed.''
   The Israeli air raids were the fifth and sixth inside Lebanon
this year. By police count, six people were killed and 45 wounded
in the four previous attacks.
   In Jerusalem, the Israeli army command said the jets hit ``two
terrorist targets,'' east of Sidon and east of Mashgara in the
Bekaa.
   It described the targets as ``headquarters and ammunition dumps
of Hezbollah and Abu Nidal'' at which infiltrations were planned.
   Lebanese police said the bases east of Sidon belonged to the
Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine, the Fatah
Revolutionary Council led by terrorist Abu Nidal and the Palestine
Liberation Front.
   The three organizations have joint bases in hills facing
positions of the Israeli-sponsored South Lebanon Army militia in
Kfar Falous, six miles east of Sidon, the spokesman said. The
militia helps patrol the ``security zone'' Israel maintains on
Lebanese territory just north of its border.
   An Israeli army spokesman said earlier that Israeli troops shot
and killed three guerrillas near the Lebanese village of Hula,
about a mile from the Israeli border town of Kiryat Shmona.
   Two other encounters between Israeli soldiers and guerrillas
were reported in the area Sunday and Tuesday, ending a two-month
lull in attempted infiltrations of Israel from Lebanon.
</TEXT>
