<FIRST>r a AM-Pepper-Fla     05-31 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pepper-Fla,0468</SECOND>
<HEAD>Portrait of Pepper Unveiled in Florida Legislature</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Pepper</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT KALLESTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A portrait of U.S. Rep. Claude Pepper
was unveiled Wednesday in the Legislature, where he began his
political career six decades ago, and the governor asked that a new
building be named in his memory.
   The Miami Beach Democrat, champion of the elderly and weaver of
the nation's social-welfare safety net died of cancer Tuesday at
age 88, the oldest member of Congress.
   The unveiling in the Florida Senate of the portrait awarded by
the Easter Seal Society was previously scheduled for Wednesday, and
Pepper was to have attended. The portrait will hang in the
Tallahassee-Leon Civic Center.
   ``He always wanted to serve,'' Senate Majority Leader Jack
Gordon, a Miami Beach Democrat, said at the unveiling. Gordon, who
has served in the Senate since 1972, is considered a potential
successor to his longtime friend.
   Sen. Ileana Ros-Lehtinen, a Miami Republican, said Pepper had
always been a friend to Miami's Cuban community and other refugee
groups.
   ``He did not worry about color; he did not worry about party; he
did not worry about creed,'' said Sen. Carrie Meek, a Miami
Democrat.
   Gov. Bob Martinez urged the Legislature to name the state's new
Department of Education building for Pepper.
   ``It would be fitting to name this important building in state
government after a man who, decade after decade, stood tall for the
interests of the people he served,'' said Martinez.
   Pepper's public service began with his election to the Florida
House in 1928 at age 28. He went to the U.S. Senate during the
administration of President Franklin D. Roosevelt. He was defeated
in 1950 but was elected to the U.S. House in 1962.
   Pepper was to lie in state in the U.S. Capitol Rotunda for five
hours Thursday, a final honor previously granted to only 26
Americans.
   A spokeswoman for Pepper's office, Rochelle Jones, said a
viewing will be held in Florida's Old Capitol on Sunday and a
funeral will be at the First Baptist Church. Pepper will be buried
here next to his wife, Mildred.
   The governor said he will not set a date for a special election
to choose Pepper's successor until after the services.
   ``I think the focus ought to remain on Senator Pepper,'' said
Martinez.
   Republicans mentioned as possible candidates in the 18th
congressional district, where about half the voters are Hispanic,
include U.S. Attorney Dexter Lehtinen; his wife, Ileana, and state
Reps. Lincoln Diaz-Balart and Alberto Gutman.
   Besides Gordon, the Democrat possibilities include Miami Beach
Mayor Alex Daoud, Hialeah Mayor Raul Martinez, Metro Dade
Commissioners Barbara Carey and Joseph Gersten and Miami
Commissioner Rosario Kennedy.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
