<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 2214EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ArmsSale     05-31 0133</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Arms Sale,130</SECOND>
<HEAD>Taiwan Parts Sale Outlined</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon notified Congress on Wednesday it
had approved the sale of aviation spare parts worth more than $100
million to Taiwan.
   Assuming there are no congressional objections, the Pentagon
said spare parts for F-5, F-100, F-104, T-33, T-28 and C-130
aircraft would be sold to the Taiwanese government.
   The sale also includes various types of aviation radar and
navigation systems and is expected to total $108 million, the
Pentagon said.
   The U.S. Air Force will be responsible for overseeing the
transaction ``and the procurement of these items will be from the
many contractors providing similar items to the U.S. armed forces.''
   ``The sale of this equipment and support will not affect the
basic military balance in the region,'' the Pentagon added.
</TEXT>
