<FIRST>r a AM-NeighborMurder     05-31 0211</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Neighbor Murder,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jury Selection Starts for Ex-Police Officer's Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EXETER, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A line of 150 potential jurors on Wednesday
stretched out the front door of a courthouse where a former police
officer went on trial on charges he murdered his neighbor for
revenge.
   Robert McLaughlin, who was a policeman for 18 years in coastal
Hampton, surrendered last summer and admitted to the killing. But
during a pre-trial hearing this month, he said his wife, Susan,
pulled the trigger.
   She was convicted last month of being an accomplice to murder
and is serving a life sentence without parole.
   Prosecutors charge McLaughlin killed Robert Cushing, 63, a
prominent real estate agent and former teacher, with two shotgun
blasts on June 1, 1988. McLaughlin and his wife went to Cushing's
home to settle a grudge that dated to 1976 when Cushing accused
McLaughlin of brutality in making a traffic arrest, authorities
said.
   Because of publicity the case received, Superior Court Judge
Robert Temple brought in an unusual number of potential jurors. The
number present Wednesday was three times the number lawyers took a
week to interview in Susan McLaughlin's trial.
   Temple instructed the potential jurors for two hours about their
responsibilities if they are chosen to sit on the panel.
