<FIRST>r i AM-Bush-Britain     05-31 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-Britain,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Hits Sunny London; So Do Striking Subway Drivers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush is in London for a relaxed day of
talks with Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher and lunch with Queen
Elizabeth II, but Londoners face the chaos of another subway strike
Thursday.
   As the presidential motorcade whisks Bush to Buckingham Palace
and Mrs. Thatcher's 10 Downing Street residence, the capital is
likely to endure more than its usual share of traffic jams.
   The subway drivers are holding their fifth 24-hour walkout this
year, demanding an extra $101 a week for operating new driver-only
trains. Management is offering $47 plus 14 days' extra annual
vacation.
   Following in the footsteps of Ronald Reagan who came here in May
1988, Bush is to have talks with Mrs. Thatcher and then head to
Buckingham Palace for his royal lunch engagement.
   In contrast to the imposing palace, Downing Street is an
unostentatious cul de sac in the heart of London, too short to
accommodate a full presidential motorcade. No. 10 has been the home
of British prime ministers for 2{ centuries.
   While Bush is at Downing Street, his wife Barbara will be just
across the Thames River, visiting an adult education center in the
borough of Lambeth.
   Bush is winding up his European tour in a city which has just
enjoyed its warmest, driest May since records began 156 years ago.
   The London Weather Center said Wednesday that temperatures
averaged 61 degrees Fahrenheit, with a high of 84. London had 308
hours of sunshine, the brightest May since the 315 hours in 1909,
and just 0.03 inches of rain, an all-time low for the month.
   But it forecasts colder weather and showers Thursday.
   Bush will visit the U.S. Embassy in the afternoon, and may get
in a game of tennis before heading back to Downing Street for a
banquet given by Mrs. Thatcher. He flies home Friday morning.
   The president arrived at dusk Wednesday aboard Air Force One
from West Germany, and was greeted by Mrs. Thatcher and her husband
Denis on the tarmac at London's Heathrow Airport.
   Armed police guarded the airport and sniffer dogs were used to
check for explosives.
   After a red-carpet welcome with a military band playing the U.S.
national anthem, Bush boarded a U.S. military helicopter with an
easy wave and smile to the dignitaries.
   Mrs. Thatcher joined him on the 15-mile flight to Winfield
House, the Regent's Park official residence of U.S. Ambassador
Henry Catto.
</TEXT>
