<FIRST>r w AM-US-Cambodia     05-31 0326</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Cambodia,330</SECOND>
<HEAD>State: Wants To Strengthen Cambodian Resistance</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSANNE M. SCHAFER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration reaffirmed on
Wednesday that it wants to ``strengthen'' the non-communist
resistance in Cambodia, as it refused to deny a report that it will
seek congressional support for a covert program supplying weapons
to the guerrillas.
   There has been opposition on Capitol Hill to such a move, on the
grounds such support could fall into the hands of the Communist
Khmer Rouge.
   Led by Pol Pot, the Khmer Rouge ran Cambodia from 1975 through
1978 and presided over the period in which 1 million Cambodians
died.
   State Department Richard Boucher, asked about the report
published in The New York Times, said the United States has an
assistance program for the non-communist groups that seeks ``an
acceptable, comprehensive and stable political solution'' in
Cambodia.
   ``We believe it is important to strengthen the Cambodian
non-communist resistance,'' Boucher said, adding the administration
believes this is important in light of Vietnam's announcement that
it intends to withdraw its forces from Cambodia at the end of
September.
   The spokesman said ``appropriate assistance'' would strengthen
the non-communist resistance and ``enhance its position and that of
Prince Sihanouk,'' who is trying to oust the Phnom Penh government
and its Vietnamese backers. The prince's forces are part of a
coalition of armed groups that includes the Khmer Rouge.
   Asked if that meant whether he could rule out military aid as a
way of strengthening the non-communist resistance, Boucher replied,
``I have nothing here that would rule it out, no.''
   Boucher said the administration was ``unalterably opposed'' to a
return to power by the Khmer Rouge.
   The New York Times reported on Wednesday that the covert aid
program would be used to strengthen Sihanouk's position in
negotiations with the Phnom Penh government and the Khmer Rouge.
   The newspaper attributed the report to unidentified Bush
administration officials, but efforts to confirm the report were
unsuccessful.
</TEXT>
