<FIRST>r i AM-Hungary-History 1stLd-Writethru a0685 05-31 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hungary-History, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0685,0375</SECOND>
<HEAD>Communist Party Reverses Official View on Leader of 1956 Uprising</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 4 grafs of background</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Communist Party leadership said
Wednesday that former Premier Imre Nagy, who led the failed 1956
anti-Soviet uprising, has become the symbol of reform and a
``significant figure'' in postwar history.
   The reversal of official policy on Nagy, who was executed in
1958, amounted to political rehabilitation.
   It comes just two weeks before his remains are to be reburied at
an officially sanctioned ceremony June 16 in the same spot where
his body and those of his associates were dumped in unmarked graves
31 years ago.
   ``Nagy is a significant figure of Hungarian post-1945 history,''
said a party statement read on Hungarian TV.
   He ``fought to stop Stalinism in Hungary and ... against foreign
intervention and against the counterrevolutionary actions taking
place during the uprising,'' it said.
   Until earlier this year, Nagy was said to not have taken steps
to combat the ``counterrevolutionaries'' involved in the 1956
uprising.
   In February, the party partially reassessed its view of the
revolt, admitting that it began as a popular uprising.
   The statement, drafted by a Central Committee panel headed by
Politburo reformer Rezsoe Nyers, further reassessed the uprising.
   ``During the 1956 events, in the midst of the contradictory
circumstances on both sides of the opposing forces, many fought
heroically and died for causes they believed to be just,'' it said.
   ``The tragedy was the fratricide itself, and all of the dead are
a loss to the nation,'' it said.
   Mass demonstrations began Oct. 23, 1956, for political reforms
and withdrawal of Soviet military forces. Soviet soldiers and tanks
rolled into Budapest on Nov. 4 to end the uprising.
   Official figures said 5,000-6,000 people were killed, but
Western estimates put the number at 32,000.
   At a meeting this week, the party Central Committee agreed that
Nagy was ``executed in the wake of a show trial and that his
sentence was a violation of the law,'' party spokesman Laszlo Major
told reporters Tuesday.
   Last week, official media said June 16 would be a day of
mourning in Hungary for Nagy and his ``fellow martyrs.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
