<FIRST>r i AM-Flight103     05-31 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flight 103,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Reported Convinced Pan Am Bomb Was Planted at Frankfurt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The British Broadcasting Corp. said Wednesday that
Scottish police were convinced the bomb that blew up Pan Am Flight
103 over Lockerbie, Scotland, killing 270 people, was put on board
the plane at Frankfurt Airport.
   It also indicated detectives thought one passenger, a student,
checked in the suitcase containing the bomb for someone else,
perhaps innocently, and intimated that West German authorities were
hindering the investigation.
   ``The Scots now think they know whose baggage the bomb was in.
The case containing the bomb is now firmly believed to have been
loaded at Frankfurt Airport,'' the BBC said.
   Police refused to comment.
   But John Boyd, chief constable of Dumfries and Galloway who has
led the Lockerbie investigation, said the investigation was now at
a stage police had not envisioned when they started.
   ``That means that I am hopeful and optimistic for a reasonable
conclusion,'' said Boyd, who is moving to a new post as chief
investigator of constabulary for Scotland.
   John Prescott, transport spokesman for the opposition Labor
Party, urged Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher to discuss the issue
with President Bush, who arrived in London Wednesday night at the
end of his European tour.
   ``If the German security authorities are hindering the inquiries
by the British and the Americans, then something must be done to
stop that,'' Prescott said.
   The Pan Am flight originated in Frankfurt, West Germany, and
blew up over Lockerbie on Dec. 21 while bound from London to New
York, killing all 259 people on board and 11 on the ground.
   No arrests in the bombing have been announced. But on May 22 the
West German magazine Stern said an Arab bomb expert linked to the
sabotage was arrested in October with 15 other people in raids on
Palestinian homes that also netted explosives and weapons.
   Stern identified the man as Jordanian-born Marwan Khreesat. It
said he was released 15 days later because he worked for the West
German intelligence service, and then returned to Jordan.
   A spokesman for the service denied the man was a West German
agent.
   Hans-Juergen Foerster, spokesman for West Germany's chief
federal prosecutor's office, said May 22 that investigators could
not find enough evidence to keep Khreesat in custody, despite
suspicions about him.
   Stern said Khreesat was believed to make bombs for the radical
Arab group Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine-General
Command.
</TEXT>
