<FIRST>r a AM-BlacksOusted     05-31 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Blacks Ousted,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>Black Woman Says She Was Forced Out Of House Days After Moving In</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By A.J. HOSTETLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHILADELPHIA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A black woman who says racial harassment
forced her and her two young children to abandon the first house
she ever owned said Wednesday she will not try to return to the
all-white neighborhood.
   ``They don't want me, I'm not going to fight,'' said Rosa
Toussaint. ``Those people just don't want me to live there.''
   Ms. Toussaint, 29, grew up in Puerto Rico, served in the Army
and works for a nonprofit agency that monitors abused and neglected
children. She said she and her children, ages 1 and 2, moved into
the home May 13 and left eight days later.
   ``I was naive when I came here. I just wanted to live in a nice
neighborhood,'' she said. ``I thought all that black and white
stuff was something from the '60s. I didn't meet it in Puerto Rico
or in the Army or even in Alabama.''
   She said she heard a racist comment the first day in the
neighborhood. Two days later, she said, she found her garbage can
overturned and a fish skeleton on her doorstep. Later, she said,
rocks were thrown through two windows.
   Some residents said Brunner Real Estate, which handled the sale
of the $27,250 row house, never should have shown her a house in an
all-white neighborhood and should have warned her that it was not
mixed.
   ``Blacks start moving in and property values go down and white
people start running,'' Frank Sintic said. ``They shouldn't run, in
my opinion, but they do and realtors end up making fortunes.''
   Pizza shop owner Sandy Borschell said the real estate company
``made that woman a victim of society.''
   Bob Coyle, who sold Ms. Toussaint the home, said the real estate
company did exactly what the law dictates. ``The woman came in here
and wanted to buy a house and we sold her a house,'' he said.
   City Commission on Human Relations spokesman Jack Fingerman said
he could not comment on the agency's investigation.
   Lt. Marshall Smith of the Police Department's Conflict
Prevention and Resolution Unit said his team's investigation will
be extremely difficult ``unless someone is willing to step forward
and tell us who did it.''
   ``Had she stayed there, maybe we could have done more,'' he
said. ``The incidents would have continued and we could have made
an arrest.''
   Smith said his unit investigated 175 such incidents in the city
last year and that reports of harassment have remained steady over
the past few years.
   Ms. Toussaint, who is staying with friends, said she plans to
stay in Philadelphia.
   ``First, I have to sell the house,'' she said. ``I want to move
where there are blacks and Hispanics in the neighborhood.''
</TEXT>
