<FIRST>u w AM-SpellingBee 2ndLd-Writethru a0684 05-31 0676</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spelling Bee, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0684,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Word by Word by Word by Word by Word _ ``Seriatim'' _ the Bee Begins</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates in top 5 grafs with windup for the day; edits to tighten</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HARRY F. ROSENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Words such as ``shimmery,'' ``carnivore,'' and
``hopperdozer'' flowed trippingly over the tongue Wednesday but
``blas,'' ``nasturtium'' and ``macadam'' proved too difficult as
the 62nd National Spelling Bee winnowed out the best from the just
very, very good.
   The record field of 222 local champions was cut by 71 in the
first three rounds. The 151 remaining will battle through more
difficult rounds on Thursday until there are just two vying for the
title. One will miss, one will succeed and the national champion
will be crowned.
   By the end of three rounds, 601 words had been spelled, a lot of
tears had been shed but there also were some very happy _ and,
often, lucky _ survivors.
   Thirteen-year-old Natalie Tarrant of San Antonio, Texas, almost
_ but not quite _ made it through ``machtpolitik,'' power politics.
But she spelled it with a ``c'' at the end.
   Nine-year-old Lisa Ishimaru, a fourth-grader from Sacramento,
Calif. _ the youngest contestant _ made it through all three rounds
with ``mountebank,'' ``blolly'' and ``reflorescence.'' Russell
Murdock, 13, of Raytown, Mo., survived ``empirical'' and
``ellipticity'' but failed on ``mignonette.''
   There was one small moment of drama when 11-year-old Susan
Bonner, a 6th grader from Fort Necessity (La.) High School spelled
``scordatura'' so softly that the judges had to replay a tape
recording that officials use for such situations.
   She waited nervously as the judges listened to the tape two or
three times. They finally decided she had misspelled the word by
using a ``t'' instead of a ``d.'' The word means tuning of an
instrument to produce a special effect.
   When 14-year-old Angela Martin of St. Petersburg, Fla., got the
word ``boulevardier,'' she asked several times to have the word
repeated and then said ``Oh, God, can I buy a vowel?'' _ a steal
from the game show ``Wheel of Fortune.''
   In this competition, however, there is no such help available.
   Ten-year-old Malinda Shepherd of Burnsville, N.C., one of the
youngest contestants, was the first to be eliminated, misspelling
``seriatim'' as ``seriatum.'' The word means ``in a series.''
   Malinda took advantage of contest rules that allow the speller
to ask for a definition of the word, then its use in a sentence,
and even what it is derived from. She took her loss bravely and
walked off the stage with a contest official's arm around her.
   The two-day competition, which carries $16,350 in prize money,
has attracted 120 girls and 102 boys who survived elimination
contests around the country and in American outposts abroad.
   Travis Blow, a 14-year-old from Sayre, Pa., foundered on
``macadam,'' spelling it ``mecadom.'' Robert Getz, 13, from
Lawrence, Kan., spelled ``nasturtia'' instead of ``nasturtium,''
and Hanna Yoon, 12, of Elk Grove Village, Ill, had ``blasse''
instead of ``blas.'' The word means ``to blow.''
   Christopher Simpson, 12, from Whitman, Mass., spelled ``sluice''
as ``sluece,'' and Jenny Boehm, 11, from Oreana, Ill., left the
final ``e'' off ``supervene.''
   ``Veneer,'' became ``vaneer'' from Katherine Strohmaier, 12, of
Lewiston, Idaho.
   In the competition at the start were six 10-year-olds, 24 who
are 11, 45 who are 12, 89 who are 13, 55 who are 14 and two who are
15. Competition is limited to those under 16 and not yet beyond the
eighth grade.
   Nearly 9 million students participated at the local level in
contests sponsored by Scripps Howard newspapers in 13 cities and by
205 other daily, weekly and Sunday newspapers.
   The winner will receive a cash award of $1,500. Other prizes are
$1,000 for second, $750 for third, $500 for fourth, $400 for fifth,
$300 for sixth, $200 for seventh through 10th, $100 for 11th
through 20th, and 202 prizes of $50 each.
   Seven of the contestants are making their third appearance in
the national competition; 30 are here for the second time.
</TEXT>
