<DOCNO> AP890531-0187 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 2251EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-BeachBombs     05-31 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Beach Bombs,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Beach Bomb Scare Traced To Performance Art Show</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The discovery of bogus exposive devices
that closed part of a coastal highway during Memorial Day weekend
was traced to a ``performance art'' show that went awry.
   The show Sunday night included an act in which realistic black
powder canisters were distributed among the 2,500 people who paid
$8 a ticket to see the performance, staged in a parking lot, said
officials of Survival Research Laboratories, producers of the show.
   Three objects that looked like bombs were found Monday along the
Great Highway near Ocean Beach, and two more were found in the
Marin County Headlands. Another canister was found Tuesday on the
beach, and three others near the lot where the late-night show was
staged.
   The palm-size canisters, with lettering reading ``High Explosive
_ { pound of TNT,'' actually were filled with plaster of Paris.
   ``But they looked like the real thing, like Army ordinance
canisters,'' said U.S. Park Service Police Sgt. Jerry McCarthy.
   As the park service and FBI began investigating, Survival
Research Laboratory officials said Tuesday night that the canisters
were among 100 to be used in the show.
   ``The fake bombs were supposed to have been hoisted in 30-gallon
trash bags by a big remote-controlled crane with an electromagnetic
plate attached to the bottom of the lift,'' said one production
company employee, who asked that his name be withheld.
   When the show ended, a number of people scrambled to pick up the
devices, putting them in their pockets, the employee said.
   Survivial Research Laboratories was created by a group of
engineers, welders and artists who stage machine demolition derbies.
</TEXT>
