<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet 1stLd-Writethru   05-31 0906</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0714,0933</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yeltsin Blames Gorbachev, Party For Economic Decline</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS with 14 grafs to RECAST and UPDATE with vice president's
response to proposals on Baltics. Pick up 13th pvs, `Moscow Deputy...'
SUBS penultimate graf, `Vice President...' to conform.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto MOSB1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Populist firebrand Boris N. Yeltsin urged the new
parliament Wednesday to take power and end 72 years of Communist
Party rule. He blamed the party and President Mikhail S. Gorbachev
for continuing economic decline.
   Yeltsin, a member of the party leadership, told fellow deputies
of the Congress of People's Deputies that the presidency is
accumulating too much power and could become a dictatorship.
   ``The Congress must take power into its own hands'' if the
political and economic restructuring begun by Gorbachev is to
succeed, Yeltsin said on the sixth day of the popularly elected
parliament's inaugural session,
   He called for an immediate transfer of authority from the party
and suggested the president submit to an annual referendum on his
performance.
   The session, broadcast live to the nation, has seen
unprecedented public criticism of the Soviet leadership.
   Gorbachev kept a stoic face throughout Yeltsin's speech and
scanned the hall for reaction. Most deputies politely applauded.
Members of the party's ruling Politburo who attended the session
and sat in a special section of the hall did not clap.
   Gorbachev's performance of the past four years has been
criticized since the Congress convened, and many deputies
questioned him sharply before they elected him to a second term as
president last week. At that time, Gorbachev promised he would not
take advantage of the increased powers of the presidency.
   Another deputy proposed constitutional amendments recognizing
the 15 Soviet republics as sovereign states with the power to
control their own resources, make their own laws and shape a new
relationship with the Kremlin.
   Estonia and Lithuania, which have defied the Kremlin by
declaring themselves sovereign with the right to overturn Soviet
laws, had been expected to propose such amendments.
   But the sponsor turned out to be a Gorbachev protege, Latvian
President Anatoly Gorbunov.
   ``The U.S.S.R. is a union, a multinational state, formed on the
basis of agreement, equal republics, with self-determination of
nations,'' Gorbunov said. ``Only the republics can delegate power
to the union.''
   He said a redistribution of power was needed ``to eradicate the
roots of ethnic tension.''
   Gorbunov whispered with Gorbachev during the following speech
and conferred again during the next break, but the president did
not respond publicly to the proposal.
   The highest-level comment on Gorbunov's radical proposals came
from Anatoly Lukyanov, elected Monday as vice president. He said
the proposals may go too far and called for a combination of
central, republic and local control.
   Moscow Deputy Yuri Vlasov ripped into Gorbachev for denying
knowledge of what happened when troops that were dispatched to
break up a pro-independence demonstration in Tbilisi, capital of
Soviet Georgia, killed 20 people.
   ``In no circumstances is it possible to accept that the head of
state doesn't know the circumstances of the case,'' Vlasov said.
``Otherwise, what kind of head of state is he?''
   The Congress on Wednesday approved a commission to investigate
the incident.
   Vlasov also criticized the long-sacrosanct KGB secret police,
charging that ``the best people of the country were tortured in its
basements'' and it remains almost uncontrollable, continuing to
dominate the lives of all citizens.
   Yeltsin's speech was packed with proposals, and his fellow
deputies sat riveted to their seats when he demanded the Congress
seize power from party leaders who are ``the same people who have
not managed to get society out of its crisis in politics, the
economy, finances and the standard of living.''
   Yeltsin, who became a hero to many Soviets by demanding a better
life for the common people, said ``the threat of financial collapse
has become real'' since Gorbachev was named Kremlin leader in March
1985. Tens of millions of people live in poverty, he said.
   Yeltsin proposed the Congress grant free medicine and mass
transit to invalids and the poor and suggested it convert special
hospitals and clinics for the elite to health centers for mothers
and children.
   Yeltsin, a member of the party's Central Committee, also called
for removal of many of that policy-making body's members, saying
they have proved incapable of solving the nation's problems.
   Despite his harsh words for Gorbachev, Yeltsin's proposal on
transferring power from the party to the government could have
Gorbachev's support, Deputy Revaz Tabakashvili said later.
   Gorbachev has said his reforms are designed to separate the
government and party bureaucracies, get the party out of day-to-day
public affairs and let the popularly elected Congress and its
full-time legislature set policy and law with the guidance of a
strong president.
   One deputy noted that Gorbachev chose Wednesday's speakers,
including Yeltsin, from among the 440 deputies who asked to comment
on Gorbachev's address on Tuesday.
   Since Gorbachev heads the party and the government, he would not
be threatened by Yeltsin's proposal. But thousands of party
bureaucrats in every organization in the country, from a tiny
Siberian factory to the ruling Politburo, could stand to lose power.
   Vice President Lukyanov told reporters afterward, ``I think the
party's position in our country is just fine and precisely defined
in Article 6 of the Constitution.''
   The article says the Communist Party is ``the leading and
guiding force of Soviet society and the nucleus of its political
system.''
</TEXT>
