<FIRST>u w AM-Gray 1stLd-Writethru a0710 05-31 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gray, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0710,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gray Complains of Leak; Thornburgh Orders a Probe</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Recasts and edits throughout to delete source material</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. William H. Gray III, in an uncomfortable
spotlight after a Memorial Day visit from FBI agents, wrote an
angry letter Wednesday to the Justice Department demanding a probe
of news leaks.
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh assured the fourth-ranking
House Democrat that he had ordered ``a full investigation'' into
leaks saying the FBI had begun a preliminary probe into allegations
that Gray may have had a ghost employee on his payroll.
   Jon Plebani, Gray's staff director, said Wednesday, ``Every
employee who works for Bill Gray comes to work and does work. He's
a very demanding boss.''
   Gray is seeking the post of majority whip being vacated by Rep.
Tony Coelho, D-Calif. In his letter to Thornburgh, Gray questioned
why the department waited ``until the eve of Democratic leadership
changes to inform me or ask my cooperation.''
   Rep. David E. Bonior, D-Mich., one of Gray's opponents in the
whip's race, also complained, ``The American people are fed up with
the effort to use innuendoes and rumors to discredit our public
officials. We must stop this destructive politics of character
assassination.''
   Government sources told several news organizations Tuesday that
Gray had been visited by FBI agents who were conducting a
preliminary inquiry. Gray denied that he had done anything wrong
and suggested in an evening news conference Tuesday that the
allegations were politically motivated.
   ``I was told over and over again I was not the subject of an
investigation,'' Gray said. He said he'd been told that the bureau
was ``looking into allegations about an employee or employees.''
   Gray wrote a sharply worded letter to Thornburgh demanding an
independent investigation of the source of any leak. Thornburgh
responded, ``Prior to receiving your letter, I had ordered a full
investigation of the apparent unauthorized disclosure of
information in this matter.''
   The purpose of the investigation, Thornburgh said, ``is to
uncover any possible wrongdoing within the department or elsewhere
and to prevent such leaks in the future.''
   In Philadelphia, FBI spokesman John Kundts said Wednesday that
the bureau would not ``confirm nor deny that there is an
investigation under way.''
   Justice Department spokesman David Runkel disputed suggestions
that top department officials leaked information for political
reasons.
   ``If that is going on, it's going on at a lower level of the
department,'' Runkel said.
   The spokesman described Thornburgh as ``disturbed by leaks that
have come out of the department concerning matters which have led
to news stories on members of Congress.''
   ``If there is some attempted interference here in the actions of
the House Democratic Caucus it is of concern to us,'' Runkel said.
   Last Thursday, the attorney general asked Assistant Attorney
General Edward S.G. Dennis ``to look into the unauthorized
disclosure of information'' leading to stories that Coehlo and Los
Angeles Mayor Tom Bradley were being investigated by the FBI.
   The Los Angeles Times reported last week that the FBI was
conducting a preliminary inquiry into investments that Coelho and
Bradley made through the investment firm of Drexel, Burnham and
Lambert.
</TEXT>
