<FIRST>r a AM-CottonClub     05-31 0626</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cotton Club,0645</SECOND>
<HEAD>Actor Says Slain Producer Feared Trouble On Night He Disappeared</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Actor Demond Wilson testified Wednesday that
slain movie producer Roy Radin feared ``there might be some
trouble'' on the night he disappeared because of Radin's ties with
the film ``The Cotton Club.''
   On May 13, 1983, Radin assigned Wilson, former star of TV's
``Sanford and Son,'' to follow him with a gun as the producer
headed for a business dinner at a swanky Beverly Hills restaurant,
Wilson said.
   Wilson's testimony came in a preliminary hearing in the ``Cotton
Club'' case in Municipal Court to determine if four people should
stand trial for the abduction-slaying of Radin.
   ``He asked me to follow and just watch and see if anything
happened,'' Wilson said. ``He said that there might be some
trouble. He said that something might happen to him as a result of
his association with the ... `The Cotton Club.'''
   Wilson, who acknowledged that he had drug habit at the time,
said he lost Radin's limousine in traffic on Sunset Boulevard and
never saw him again.
   The 33-year-old New York businessman's body was found a month
later in a dry riverbed about 65 miles north of Los Angeles. He had
been shot in the head repeatedly.
   Wilson's testimony conflicted with that of his former secretary,
who testified earlier that she was with Wilson and saw Radin pull
off the boulevard followed by another car full of men, but said she
and Wilson did not follow.
   Under questioning, Wilson said he used cocaine, alcohol and
pills in 1983. Asked by an attorney whether he underwent a drug
rehabilitation program, he said, ``No, sir. I found Christ.''
   Wilson is now an evangelical preacher in Washington, D.C.
   Defense attorneys attacked Wilson's account of Radin's last
night, saying the actor never before told anyone that Radin
expressed fear.
   ``He was pretty fearful,'' Wilson insisted. ``There was a lot of
anxiety around him. ... It was not a fear that somebody's hands
were shaking. It's something that a friend knows.''
   Deputy District Attorney Sally Thomas had Wilson describe his
friendship with Radin and the last night the producer was seen
alive.
   The prosecution contends that reputed drug dealer Karen DeLayne
``Laynie'' Greenberger arranged Radin's murder after they fought
about her share of profits from ``The Cotton Club.'' She is charged
with murder along with Alex Lamota Marti, William Molony Mentzer
and Robert Ulmer Lowe, former bodyguards for Hustler magazine
publisher Larry Flynt. Lowe is fighting extradition in Maryland.
   On the night Radin disappeared, Wilson said he visited Radin in
his hotel suite and ``That was when I saw the crux of his anxiety.''
   He said Radin asked if he had a gun, which Wilson did, and
arranged for him to come along to La Scala restaurant, where Radin
was to dine with Mrs. Greenberger. Wilson was assigned to follow in
his own car. The actor said he offered to call the police, but
Radin declined.
   Wilson brought his secretary and also had a reservation for
dinner. But he said the plan went awry when he lost Radin's
limousine in traffic.
   He said he began to follow but got stopped at a red traffic
light. By the time he turned onto Sunset Boulevard, he said, he was
about 10 cars behind Radin.
   He said he continued on to the restaurant, but Radin never
showed up.
   Attorney David Kenner, representing Marti, attacked Wilson's
story, pointing out discrepancies between his current account and
what he told police in interviews following Radin's disappearance.
   Kenner then asked, ``Do you have a recollection of telling
anybody before today that Mr. Radin was expressing fear,
nervousness or anxiety on May 13, 1983?''
   ``No,'' said Wilson.
</TEXT>
