<FIRST>r i AM-Afghan-Shiites     05-31 0182</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghan-Shiites,0187</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shiite Negotiations With Interim Guerrilla Government Deadlocked</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three days of negotiations on a share
in the Afghan guerrilla government for minority Shiite Moslems
ended in deadlock Wednesday, but the main Shiite leader said more
talks would be held.
   Karim Khalili, leader of the eight Afghan guerrilla groups based
in Iran, said a six-member commission had been formed to maintain
contact between his alliance and guerrilla leaders headquartered in
Pakistan.
   Khalili and the Shiite minority want seven Cabinet posts in the
provisional government and have been offered four. They also demand
representation on a council controlled by leaders of the
seven-party coalition based in Pakistan.
   About 15 percent of Afghanistan's people are Shiites, and the
rest follow the main Sunni sect of Islam.
   The guerrillas present the provisional government as an
alternative to the Soviet-sponsored Marxist regime in Kabul.
   Moslem guerrillas began fighting after a communist coup in April
1978 and Soviet soldiers entered country in December 1979. An
estimated 115,000 were in Afghanistan when the Red Army began its
withdrawal, which was completed Feb. 15.
</TEXT>
