<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 2337EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-LocalRails     05-31 0178</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Local Rails,170</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Votes to Subsidize Local Freight Rail Lines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate voted Wednesday to continue
subsidizing local freight railroad lines that otherwise would be
abandoned because of little traffic.
   As a budget-reducing measure, President Bush had called for
ending the 16-year-old subsidy program once the $10 million
appropriated for this year was spent.
   But on a voice vote with no dissent, the Senate approved a bill
by Sen. Tom Harkin, D-Iowa, to continue the program with the intent
of providing some $50 million in new aid through 1993.
   However, the new legislation increases from 30 percent to 40
percent the local share required for federal matching funds to
acquire and repair tracks and terminal facilities. None of the
federal aid can be used to subsidize the operating costs of the
lines.
   The program originated in the government's bailout of the Penn
Central Railroad in the early 1970s when shippers and local
communities were faced with the prospect that thousands of miles of
track would be abandoned. It was expanded nationwide in 1976.
</TEXT>
