<FIRST>r i AM-Antigua-Body     05-31 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Antigua-Body,0242</SECOND>
<HEAD>Find Body Of Opposition Leader's Wife</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. JOHN'S, Antigua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said the partially naked,
manacled body of the wife of a political opposition leader was
found on a beach early Wednesday, three days after she was reported
missing.
   Arah Hector, wife of Caribbean Liberation Movement leader Tim
Hector, disappeared from their farm Sunday. Swimmers found her body
at Jabberwalk Beach north of St. John's, the capital.
   Police said they had detained a man employed at the farm, where
Mrs. Hector's glasses and parts of her clothing were found on the
ground Sunday. They said there was no indication of the motive.
   The body was partially buried in the sand, with the hands tied
behind the back and clothes wrapped around the neck, police said.
They speculated that she was killed on the farm and buried at the
beach.
   Mrs. Hector, in her early 40s, had three sons and led the
Marxist party's Women's Action Group. Tim Hector was in London on
Wednesday and was traveling in North Africa last week.
   The Hectors and their party, which is not represented in the
15-seat legislature, recently began a campaign against drug
trafficking on the island. In recent editorials, the party
newspaper Outlet denounced government corruption and accused some
ministers of involvement in the drug trade.
   The Foreign Ministry of the former British colony said the
government had asked Scotland Yard's assistance in the
investigation.
