<FIRST>r w AM-US-ChinaRights     05-31 0299</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-China Rights,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kampelman Tells Bush to Use Full Leverage to Protect Chinese Rights</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GENE KRAMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush should make full use of U.S.
leverage to discourage Chinese leaders from cracking down on
students demonstrating for democracy, a former chief U.S.
disarmament negotiator said Wednesday.
   In the coming days, ``hard-line elements in the government and
the armed forces may crack down on the students and workers in
China's democracy movement,'' involving serious abuses of human and
political rights, former negotiator Max Kampelman said in a letter
to Bush.
   Kampelman now is chairman of Freedom House, an independent
U.S.-based policy organization that promotes human rights and civil
liberties throughout the world.
   The United States and China cooperate on military, economic,
cultural, scientific and educational programs ``which the Peoples
Republic of China finds very much in its interest,'' Kampelman said.
   ``This is the time for the ... United States to make it clear
that such relationships as these may come under greater public
scrutiny in our country and may not be sustainable if the
established Chinese leadership attempts to preserve its rule by
abusing the basic political rights and civil liberties of the
Chinese people,'' Kampelman's letter said.
   Kampelman returned last month to Freedom House after more than
three years as chief negotiator for former President Reagan's
administrator in the strategic arms reduction talks with the Soviet
Union.
   ``We at Freedom House believe it is wrong now not to hold China
to the common standards the United States uses in judging a
country's performance with regard to human rights,'' Kampelman said.
   In the past, the United States has ``understandably refrained''
from criticizing human rights abuses by allies and other friendly
countries, he said, but ``too often that reluctance has proved
ill-founded and short-sighted.''
</TEXT>
