<FIRST>u i AM-Argentina 1stLd-Writethru a0702 05-31 0779</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0702,0800</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shop Owners Kill Two Looters; Menem Declines to Take Office Early</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with more deaths. Picks up 7th
graf, `Police fired... with minor editing to conform and trim; ADDS 2 grafs
on Venezuelan reax.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Provincial governments opened
soup kitchens and Congress increased social benefits Wednesday in
bids to end a week of food rioting and looting that has killed 15
people, most of them trying to get food.
   President-elect Carlos Menem met on Wednesday with outgoing
President Raul Alfonsin, who was forced to declare a state of siege
two days earlier. Menem indicated he will work closely with the
government on the economic crisis that sparked the looting, but he
again refused to take office early.
   ``I don't want to interfere with the desire of President
Alfonsin to serve out his mandate,'' Menem, of the labor-based
Peronist Party and winner of May 14 national elections, told
reporters. Alfonsin is to step down Dec. 10.
   The two agreed to review the 1989 budget and put more money into
health and nutrition programs, increase state revenue from customs
taxes, and coordinate policy on public salaries, utility rates and
the $59 billion foreign debt, Menem said.
   Small-scale looting was reported in the provincial capitals of
Corrientes and Mendoza, and in the working class neighborhoods of
Moreno, San Miguel, Jose C. Paz and Munro in Buenos Aires'
industrial belt.
   Two teen-age boys and a 50-year-old man were killed during a
raid on a supermarket and food warehouse in Moreno on Wednesday,
and a 9-year-old boy died of shotgun wounds suffered the day before
in rioting in San Miguel.
   The independent news agency Diarios y Noticias quoted police as
saying they arrested shop owners who shot and killed the Moreno
looters, but did not say how many were involved in the shooting.
   Police fired rubber bullets and tear gas to disperse a crowd
trying to break into a supermarket in western Mendoza, Argentina's
fourth-biggest city.
   ``I had hoped to live what's left of my life in peace and quiet,
but now it seems more likely that I'll die in the middle of a
war,'' said Buenos Aires resident Matilde Alvarez.
   In general, however, the violence appeared to subside.
   ``Calm reigns throughout the country,'' Interior Minister Juan
Carlos Pugliese said before Wednesday's deaths were reported.
   But there were none of the confrontations the past two days
brought between security forces and mobs in Buenos Aires and
northern Rosario city.
   Six people were killed Tuesday in the capital and five the day
before in Rosario. At least 70 looters and bystanders have been
shot and wounded, and dozens more injured by tear gas, stones,
sticks, broken glass and fists. More than 2,000 people have been
arrested.
   An elite coast guard squadron was sent Wednesday to Rosario, 186
miles north of the capital, to help 2,000 border guards there
establish order.
   Police were stationed at supermarkets throughout the country.
   ``They took everything, even the bones,'' a butcher in San
Miguel said Wednesday, moments after his store was sacked.
   Cesar Melville's nearby supermarket was looted the day before.
``I asked them to just take the food, but they grabbed clothing,
wine and coffee,'' he said as he mopped up spilled milk and
mayonnaise.
   The riots began last week in Mendoza and Cordoba, the
second-biggest city, after months of devaluations caused price
rises far ahead of wage increases and prompted nationwide layoffs
and shortages.
   Real wages have shrunken to 35 percent of what they were in
December 1983 when Alfonsin took office, according to a survey by
the conservative Center for a New Majority.
   Congress on Wednesday approved the 30-day state of siege,
increased state pensions and allocated more money for social
services.
   At the insistence of the Peronists, legislators raised the
minimum pension for retirees to $36 a month and for widows to $33.
   On Tuesday, the monthly minimum wage was more than doubled to
$44.
   Provincial governments on Wednesday set up soup kitchens and
charity drives, lowered water and electricity tariffs, began
negotiating with businessmen to prevent layoffs, and made plans to
halt building projects and funnel more money to social programs.
   In Caracas late Tuesday, President Carlos Andres Perez of
Venezuela called the Argentine situation ``extremely difficult,
because their economic situation keeps getting worse.'' He blamed
industrialized nations for not offering solutions to Latin
America's economic crunch, saying ``they close the doors on us''
when it comes to negotiating the region's $410 billion debt.
   Venezuela suffered looting and rioting in February after Perez
announced economic reforms, with 300 people listed officially as
killed.
</TEXT>
