<FIRST>r w AM-CosmeticSurgery     05-31 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cosmetic Surgery,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>FTC Chairman Says States Must Regulate Cosmetic Surgery Industry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   State regulators, not the federal government,
must take the lead against false and misleading advertising and
promotions involving cosmetic surgery and other medical procedures,
a federal official said Wednesday.
   That assertion by Daniel Oliver, chairman of the Federal Trade
Commission, was challenged by other officials who told a
congressional panel that states sometimes are hampered by federal
policies.
   Oliver said ``False and misleading advertising for cosmetic
surgery is, and should be, a matter of concern to all agencies and
organizations, public and private, at both the federal and state
level.''
   But, he added, ``Such procedures are generally practiced and
promoted at a local level and, therefore, consumer protection must,
at least initially, be the prime responsibility of the state
medical boards and the state consumer protection authorities.''
   Oliver also rejected any commission responsibility for physician
competency in an appearance before the House subcommittee on
regulation, business opportunities and energy.
   But the subcommittee's chairman, Rep. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., said
Oliver's view was ``an absurd rewriting of the FTC role in
protection of consumers.''
   He said Oliver was trying ``to make the states ... take the lead
in areas the states say they are powerless to deal with.''
   Richard G. Gannon, executive director of the Kansas Board of
Healing Arts told the subcommittee the issue of false and deceptive
medical advertising is too complex and costly for the states to
handle.
   ``Various FTC and court rulings have made it extremely difficult
to discipline a doctor solely on the basis of advertising with the
exception of the most blatant violations,'' Gannon said, although
he was unable to provide an example.
   Oliver contended the commission's antitrust law enforcement
program presented no obstacles to effective state regulation and
said rules that might suppress broad categories of truthful
advertising were not the answer to the problem.
   Instead, Oliver said, the agency's 1979 order lifting the ban on
medical advertising and all subsequent orders expressly instructs
or permits medical professionals ``to deal effectively with all
forms of deceptive advertising.''
   But Gannon said the only recent communication his state has had
with the FTC was when the commission questioned whether the state's
censure of two doctors for deceptive and misleading advertising
might place illegitimate restrainst on truthful advertising.
   ``Contacts by federal agencies whenever such actions are taken
does cause consternations and may have a chilling effect if the
result is to become embroiled in actions brought by the Federal
Trade Commission,'' Gannon said.
   Rep. Tom Campbell, R-Calif., suggested state regulators could
remove federal jurisdiction from issues like medical advertising
through action by state legislatures.
   Dr. Hugh Johnston, chairman of Oregon's Board of Medical
Examiners, testified he'd been instructed by the state attorney
general ``to stay out of advertising'' because the state couldn't
be sure of what constituted false advertising.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
