<FIRST>r a AM-HouseLeadership-Foley     05-31 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-House Leadership-Foley,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foley's Likely Ascension to Speaker Greeted Enthusiastically</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-House Leadership, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN K. WILEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPOKANE, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prospect that Rep. Tom Foley will
replace Jim Wright as speaker of the House was greeted
enthusiastically Wednesday in the majority leader's home state and
congressional district.
   ``It's no secret that we feel he would be the best choice for
the job,'' said Karen Marchioro, state Democratic Central Committee
chairwoman. ``Personally, he's very urbane and civil. He's a rock,
really, and right now, that may be what we need.''
   Foley has been a steadfast supporter of Wright, and during
appearances in Washington state last week repeatedly urged the
speaker not to step down. But in the wake of a House ethics
investigation into his financial dealings, Wright said he would ask
for a Democratic caucus in the House to elect a new speaker on
Tuesday.
   Foley, a 13-term congressman, is not expected to face a
challenge to succeed Wright by moving up from his No. 2 position in
the House Democratic leadership.
   Foley, 60, was a protege of Washington state's two most powerful
politicians, the late Sens. Warren Magnuson and Henry M. ``Scoop''
Jackson.
   A self-described parliamentarian and pragmatist, Foley is best
known for his attempts to build bipartisan coalitions, rather than
clinging to party ideologies.
   ``Although I wish to proclaim I've always been totally satisfied
with the innocence of Speaker Wright, I think that (Foley's
speakership) will be a tremendous boon to the state of Washington,
to the eastern district of the state, and to the nation,'' said
Carl Maxey, a prominent Spokane lawyer and Democrat.
   ``Tom Foley's my good friend,'' said Maxey. ``I would personally
advise him to beware of being too compromising with these
Republicans, because I'm satisfied the actions against the
Democrats are a political ploy, much like the McCarthyism of the
'50's.
   ``He's going to have to learn to fight.''
   In his 13 campaigns, Foley has rarely had to fight, earning a
reputation for gentlemanliness and always saying nice things about
outgunned opponents in his largely rural 5th Congressional District.
   ``He certainly represents a district that would be one of the
more conservative districts in the state, but he represents our
party well,'' said Mrs. Marchioro. ``He's got to be, next to Scoop
and Maggie (Magnuson), one of the most popular elected officials in
this state.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890531-0206 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 1954EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Foley     05-31 0667</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Foley,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tom Foley: A Team Player Whose Watchword Is Compromise</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-House Leadership Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The burden of ending what House Speaker Jim
Wright called ``this season of bad will'' now rests with Thomas S.
Foley, the Washington Democrat who will inherit Wright's job next
week. And virtually no one thinks there's a better man for the
challenge.
   Foley, who presided over the House on Wednesday as Wright
defended his honor and abdicated his office, will lay full claim to
the gavel when he is formally elected to Congress' most powerful
job. He will bring to the speakership a less partisan style that
fits perfectly with President Bush's call for accommodation between
the executive and legislative branches.
   As House majority leader, Foley, 60, has won admiration from
both sides of the aisle for his command of issues and tireless
negotiating skills. He is a master at finding consensus and
striking compromise.
   Wright acknowledged in his farewell address that ``perhaps'' he
had been ``too partisan, too insistent, too abrasive, too
determined to have my way.'' Foley is none of those things, as any
Republican will tell you _ to the dismay of some Democrats.
   Like Wright, Foley's political roots trace to the New Deal of
Franklin Roosevelt, but he is no knee-jerk liberal _ and wouldn't
have lasted in the House if he were. Unlike most leaders whose
seats are ``safe,'' he is from a distinctly Republican and
conservative district that has put him through many close
elections, though he won last year with 77 percent of the vote.
   Though hand-picked for the House's elite by Wright and his
predecessor, former Speaker Thomas P. ``Tip'' O'Neill, Foley never
shared their penchant for bashing the Reagan-Bush administration or
other Republican opponents. O'Neill admired Foley most for
qualities he admittedly didn't possess himself _ meticulous
craftsmanship of legislation, thorough command of the issues,
attention to organizational detail.
   ``Tom Foley,'' O'Neill once said, in both exasperation and
respect, ``is a man who can see three sides of every issue.''
   ``The reality is that in a modern, participatory Congress ...
the responsibility of leadership and the necessity of leadership is
to constantly involve members in the process of decision and
consensus,'' Foley says.
   According to Rep. Pat Williams, D-Mont., the troika of Wright,
Foley and soon-to-resign Democratic Whip Tony Coelho of California
has worked like this: ``Jim ... the captain, Tony the oar drummer
and Tom the navigator. Democrats in the House and most Republicans
have great respect for the navigator.''
   Foley's office furnishings reflect his eclectic approach.
Instead of the big, imposing desk preferred by most members of
Congress, he has a coffee table surrounded by enough sofas and
chairs to accommodate at least 18 visitors. He does his paperwork
at a small writing table in the corner.
   And Foley and his coffee table have been at the center of some
of the most important legislation, invariably compromises, to
emerge from Congress in this decade.
   Just this year, Foley was host of the extraordinary talks that
in mid-April produced a budget agreement for the next fiscal year,
and he was pivotal in the bipartisan deal with the Bush
administration over Central America policy.
   A year earlier, he chaired the economic summit sessions that
followed the October 1987 crash of the stock market. Prior to that,
he engineered the final agreements on the Gramm-Rudman budget law,
and arms control policies shared by Congress and the White House.
   ``Tom Foley is just a very able, capable individual,'' says Bob
Michel of Illinois, the House Republican leader. ``He's well-liked
on our side, and he's also recognized as a very formidable
opponent, one who will state the case well, and is eminently fair.''
   ``He's a man of total integrity,'' said Senate Republican Leader
Bob Dole, R-Kan. ``He knows the players, knows the issues.'' And
this, from Rep. Henry Hyde, R-Ill.: ``I wish he were a Republican.
If he were, he could be a presidential candidate.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890531-0207 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 1954EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-HouseSuccession     05-31 0365</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-House Succession,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Foley Expected to Become Speaker; Scramble Underway for Other Posts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Majority Leader Thomas S. Foley,
D-Wash., is in line to become Speaker of the House next week with
the resignation of Jim Wright. But a scramble is underway for other
Democratic leadership posts.
   Foley, who has been in the No. 2 post for the past 2{ years, was
the only candidate for the top House position although he did no
campaigning for the post prior to Wright's announcement.
   ``Now there is a vacancy,'' Foley spokesman Jeff Biggs said late
Wednesday, adding that he expected Foley would begin calling his
colleagues.
   A caucus of the ruling Democrats was scheduled for Tuesday to
nominate Foley for the speakership.
   Jockeying was intense for the other top party positions, which
will turn over both because of Wright's resignation and the
announcement last week by the third-ranking House Democrat,
Majority Whip Tony Coelho, D-Calif., that he would step down.
   It was not immediately clear on Wednesday whether those
positions would all be elected at Tuesday's caucus, but party
leaders were said to be eager to get the party organized and moving
forward in the wake of its unprecedented congressional crisis.
   Rep. Richard Gephardt of Missouri, who ran unsuccessfully for
the Democratic presidential nomination last year, was considered
the favorite to replace Foley as the majority leader. His
competitor for the post was Rep. Ed Jenkins, a more conservative
Georgia Democrat.
   The race for Coelho's post of majority whip, the speaker's chief
vote-counter, was a wide-open contest among several prominent party
members, including:
   _William H. Gray III of Pennsylvania, currently the chairman of
the House Democratic Caucus. Gray is fighting bad publicity from
reports that the Justice Department is conducting a preliminary
inquiry into allegations that a no-show employee was carried on his
office payroll.
   _David Bonior of Michigan, currently the chief deputy whip.
   _Beryl Anthony of Arkansas, chairman of the Democratic
Congressional Campaign Committee.
   _Henry Waxman of California, a powerful member of the House
Energy and Commerce Committee.
   Two lawmakers were running to become Democratic Caucus chairman,
Steny Hoyer of Maryland and Barbara Kennelly of Connecticut.
</TEXT>
