<FIRST>r w AM-Lugar-ElSalvador     05-31 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lugar-El Salvador,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lugar To Attend Inauguration in El Salvador</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAWRENCE L. KNUTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Richard Lugar will represent the United
States at the inauguration Thursday of Alfredo Cristiani as
president of El Salvador, Lugar's office said Wednesday.
   Lugar, R-Ind., a former chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee, headed the U.S. delegation that observed the 1988
provincial and municipal elections in the war-torn Central American
state.
   President Bush will be in London on Thursday at the conclusion
of his European trip.
   Cristiani, a member of the right-wing Arena party, succeeds
ailing President Jose Napoleon Duarte, a Christian Democrat known
for his moderate views.
   Cristiani, a U.S.-educated businessman, has impressed members of
Congress during visits here both before and after his landslide
election victory on March 19.
   But some U.S. lawmakers worry about what they regard as
extremist elements within his political party.
   Some Arena party members are accused of having links with
death-squad activities and are scornful of U.S. emphasis on
protection of human rights, contending it impairs the war effort of
the Salvadoran army against leftist guerrillas.
   But the Bush administration appears to have convinced Congress
that El Salvador should continue to receive substantial U.S.
military aid, arguing successfully that Cristiani should not be
penalized before he even takes office.
   Administration officials and congressional sources have said
U.S. military aid to El Salvador in fiscal 1990 is expected to
remain at $85 million, about $12 million less than the State
Department had requested.
   Lugar planned private meetings with both Cristiani and Duarte
and will play host on Thursday to all foreign officials and
dignitaries attending the inauguration.
   ``These are exciting times in which change toward greater
freedom is sweeping the world,'' Lugar said in a statement.
   ``But we must all remember that with burgeoning freedom comes
sobering responsibilities for leaders everywhere _ responsibilities
to protect human rights such as free speech and peaceful life.''
</TEXT>
