<FIRST>r w AM-US-Germany     05-31 0161</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Germany,140</SECOND>
<HEAD>Von Weizsaecker, Beethoven Mark German-American Relations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   West German President Richard von Weizsaecker
presided on Wednesday at a gala concert featuring Beethoven's Ninth
Symphony with its ``Ode to Joy'' to celebrate 40 years of U.S.-West
German relations.
   Von Weizsaecker arrived in Washington on Wednesday afternoon, a
day after he was host to President Bush at a reception in Bonn.
Bush went to the West German capital following the NATO summit
conference.
   ``With whom could we better rejoice over 40 years of stable
democracy than with our American friends?'' said von Weizsaecker in
prepared remarks to about 400 guests at the Kennedy Center for the
concert by the orchestra of Deutsche Oper Berlin and the University
of Maryland Chorus.
   Von Weizsaecker noted that a number of Americans had played a
role in the building of West German democracy. The occasion marked
the 40th anniversary of the promulgation of the Basic Law
establishing the Federal Republic of Germany.
