<FIRST>u w AM-FauntroyProbe 1stLd-Writethru   05-31 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fauntroy Probe, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0778,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fauntroy Probe Expanded</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS graf 6, ``Fauntroy refused,'' to reflect Reop. Savage also
declining to comment.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Justice Department investigation into the
personnel practices of Walter Fauntroy, the District of Columbia's
non-voting delegate to Congress, has been extended to examine all
of his hiring records for the last five years, The Associated Press
has learned.
   As part of the wide-ranging inquiry, a grand jury intends to
begin hearing testimony from current and former employees of
Fauntroy, a Democrat, and Rep. Gus Savage, D-Ill., over Fauntroy's
hiring of Savage's son, according to sources familiar with the
investigation.
   Thomas John Savage, the son of Rep. Savage, was paid $21,398
while on Fauntroy's payroll between September 1987 and June 1988,
but swore on Illinois election documents that he was living in
Chicago during that time. Those records were filed as part of his
unsuccessful bid to win an Illinois House seat.
   Individuals from the Fauntroy and Savage offices will be
subpoenaed to appear before a grand jury within the next month, and
investigators have already subpoenaed payroll documents and office
personnel data from the two congressmen, said sources, who spoke on
the condition of anonymity.
   Those records have been requested to determine whether the
younger Savage, his father or Fauntroy falsified payroll documents
or offered false statements to investigators.
   Fauntroy and Rep. Savage declined to comment when asked whether
documents from their offices had been requested by federal
authorities.
   When contacted by telephone in Chicago, Thomas John Savage
declined to comment Wednesday.
   In addition, investigators are examining the personal banking
records of Thomas Savage to learn whether he returned any money to
his father or Fauntroy, the sources said.
   Investigators are also closely examining accounts of the younger
Savage's job duties submitted voluntarily to federal officials by
Johnny Barnes, Fauntroy's chief aide, and several other Fauntroy
staffers, sources said.
   Barnes refused to comment on the documents when contacted
Wednesday by a reporter.
   While the statements from Fauntroy's staffers describe Thomas
Savage as regularly showing up for work, the AP has reported that
investigators have been told that the younger Savage showed up in
Rep. Savage's Chicago office on an almost-daily basis during the
period he was supposedly in Washington.
   On several occasions, the AP reported, office workers there
allegedly were told by staffers in Rep. Savage's Washington office
to keep the younger Savage away from windows to prevent anyone
passing the storefront office from seeing him.
   The FBI opened the case with a 90-day preliminary investigation
in December, shortly after the AP reported on Fauntroy's hiring of
the younger Savage.
   Officials at the Justice Department's Criminal Division then
recommended that Atorney General Dick Thornburgh appoint a special
prosecutor to look into the case under the terms an order by his
predecessor, Edwin Meese III. That rule, instituted by Meese just
days before he left office last August, required an independent
prosecutor to examine cases of alleged wrongdoing by members of
Congress.
   However, Thornburgh scuttled the Meese order and turned the
probe back to the Justice Department's criminal division, which
traditionally handles such cases.
</TEXT>
