<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     05-31 0406</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0416</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cold Front Clashes With Warm Air To Make For Moist Conditions</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Showers and thunderstorms drenched sections of the Midwest on
Wednesday, threatening floods in sections of Ohio and Michigan.
   Rain and thunderstorms also doused southern Iowa, southern
Wisconsin, northern Illinois and northwest Indiana.
   The precipitation came from a cold front stretching from the
upper Great Lakes region across the middle Mississippi Valley to
the Texas Panhandle.
   Scattered showers and thunderstorms fell along the front from
southwest Texas to western Missouri.
   In Ohio and Michigan, saturated ground, swollen rivers and
streams and the threat of more heavy rainfall prompted flood
watches Wednesday night for the southern two thirds of Michigan and
the northern third of Ohio.
   Heavier rainfall during the six hours ending at 2 p.m. EDT
included almost an inch at Youngstown, Ohio, more than two-thirds
of an inch at Dubois, Pa., and a half inch at Houghton Lake, Mich.
   The temperature differed as much as 30 degrees across the cold
front in Kansas. Northwest Kansas had temperatures in the mid-50s,
while southeast Kansas had readings in the mid-80s.
   Widely scattered showers and thunderstorms fell across the
northern Rockies. Light snow fell across southwest Wyoming before
sunrise and an inch of snow dusted the mountains near Pinedale, Wyo.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 42
degrees in Rock Springs, Wyo., to 96 degrees in Carlsbad, N.M., and
in Laredo and Beeville, Texas. The low for the 48 contiguous states
was 20 degrees in Truckee, Calif.
   The forecast for Thursday called for scattered showers and
thunderstorms from New England to the Great Lakes, Ohio Valley, the
middle Mississippi Valley, parts of Oklahoma and west Texas, with
thunderstorms most numerous from the lower Great Lakes to the
middle Mississippi Valley; and widely scattered showers and
thunderstorms over the Florida Peninsula, parts of the northern and
central Plains, the lower Mississippi Valley, central and eastern
Colorado and southeast Wyoming.
   High temperatures were predicted in the 60s across the upper
Great Lakes and sections of the central Rockies and central Plains;
the 90s from the desert Southwest to the southern Rockies, much of
southern and eastern Texas and the lower Mississippi Valley, the
Gulf Coast states, the Tennessee Valley and the middle and southern
Atlantic Coast; near 100 degrees along the Rio Grande Valley of
Texas; and in the 70s and 80s in the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
