<FIRST>u i AM-MarineCrash 1stLd-Writethru a0610 05-31 0490</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Marine Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0610,0505</SECOND>
<HEAD>14 Marines Presumed Drowned After Helicopter Crash</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with U.S. calling off search, IDs
of eight rescued, details. No pickup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANICE FUHRMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. military officials called off the search for
14 U.S. Marines missing after their helicopter crashed in the ocean
off Okinawa, and all are presumed dead, a spokesman for American
forces in Japan said Thursday.
   However, the Japanese coast guard continued its search for
survivors Thursday morning, replacing three boats that searched
overnight with seven boats and two aircraft, said spokesman
Toshiaki Kawabata.
   The U.S. spokesman, Marine Master Sgt. Jake Rodrigues, said
American efforts were called off Wednesday night.
   Eight other Marines aboard the helicopter were rescued after the
CH-46 Sea Knight, based at Kaneohe Bay, Hawaii, crashed just before
midnight Tuesday soon after taking off from the USS Denver in an
amphibious training exercise.
   By Thursday morning, the search in calm waters off Kiyan Cape
found only four pieces of metal, all believed to be from the
helicopter, said Kawabata, of the Okinawa office of the Maritime
Safety Agency, Japan's coast guard.
   The pilot was not wearing night-vision goggles, said Capt. Lenny
Ryan, spokesman at the Kaneohe Marine Corps Air Station.
   There is no requirement that night vision goggles be worn during
night operations, although they significantly enhance vision by
amplifying ambient light, said Maj. Kerry Gershaneck, public
affairs officer at the air station.
   He did not comment on whether lack of goggles could have figured
in the crash.
   Four survivors are in good condition and being treated for
injuries at Camp Lester Hospital in Okinawa, said Gershaneck.
   He identified them as Lance Cpl. Keith A. Brower, 20, of Washoe
County, Nev.; Lance Cpl. Marvin T. Cook, 22, of Bonneville County,
Idaho; Cpl. George S. Sanchez, 20, of Denton County, Texas, and
Pfc. Jason S. Wiggins, 18, of Ouachita Parish, La.
   Gershaneck said the following four survivors were treated and
released back to duty on the Denver: Sgt. John R. Becker, 24, of
St. Tammany Parish, La.; Lance Cpl. David M. Fleming-Jones, 19, of
Pierce County, Wash.; Cpl. William R. West, 22, of Jefferson
County, Colo., and Hospitalman 3d Class J.K. Largent, 23, of
Barboursville County, W.Va.
   Identifications of the missing Marines were being withheld until
the families were notified.
   Investigation into the crash is continuing, Gershaneck said.
   The helicopter disappeared at 11:55 p.m. Tuesday about 35 miles
south of Kadena Air Force Base on Okinawa, and the search by U.S.
vessels continued until 7:30 p.m. Wednesday, said Rodrigues.
   It was the third crash of a U.S. military helicopter in East
Asia this year.
   Nineteen Marines were killed and 16 injured March 20 when a
CH-53D Sea Stallion crashed and four were killed March 17 in the
crash of a CH-46. Both helicopters went down in South Korea during
joint military exercises, and the causes have not been announced.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
