<FIRST>u i AM-Chile 1stLd-Writethru a0758 05-31 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chile, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0758,0461</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chile's Military Goverment, Opposition Agree on Reforms</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with Pinochet announcement, details;
no pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lame-duck military President Augusto
Pinochet on Wednesday said his government and the opposition have
agreed on democratic reforms in Chile's constitution, including
replacing a ban on Marxism.
   In a speech broadcast on national radio and television, the
73-year-old president and army commander called the accord ``an
expression of the national will to find the best ways to achieve
the full democracy we all want.''
   Hours before Pinochet's speech, Patricio Aylwin, spokesman for a
17-party opposition coalition, said the parties gave ``a green
light'' to the changes drafted by the government for the 8-year-old
constitution written by the military.
   The agreement came after two months of unprecedented
negotiations between the 15-year-old right-wing military government
and its foes. The negotiations put Aylwin face-to-face with
Interior Minister Carlos Caceres, and leaders of two pro-government
conservative parties also took part.
   Pinochet came to power in a military coup in 1973 that toppled
the elected government of President Salvador Allende, a Marxist.
   Pinochet is scheduled to hand over power on March 11, 1990, to
the winner of an election set for Dec. 14. He had to call the
election after his bid to extend his term until 1997 was
overwhelmingly rejected by voters in a referendum in October.
   Aylwin is considered the most likely opposition candidate in the
election.
   Full details of the proposed changes were not immediately
disclosed, but Pinochet said they include replacing a controversial
article banning Marxism with another that ``ensures in a better way
a responsible political pluralism.''
   The government also agreed to the opposition's demand to change
the make-up of the future Senate, he said. It had offered to
increase the number of elected senators from 36 to 38, diluting the
influence of nine appointed senators.
   Aylwin said the government did not accept all the reforms sought
by the opposition ``but there was some clear progress.''
   The government submit the proposed changes to the four-man
military junta. Junta approval is considered certain, as is
approval in a subsequent national referendum expected in August.
   Another article strongly opposed by the opposition establishes a
military-dominated National Security Council empowered to
``represent'' its views on key matters to future civilian
governments.
   Pinochet said that clause would also be amended but did not
elaborate. The government indicated earlier it is prepared to add
another civilian member.
   Aylwin said the opposition will continue to push for changes
that lead to ``an authentically democratic regime.''
   Ricardo Lagos, a socialist opposition leader, said, ``This is a
first step, and a step that is positive for the country.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890531-0223 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 0535EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DigestBriefs     05-31 0611</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Digest Briefs,0631</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The body of Rep. Claude Pepper will lie in
state in the Capitol Rotunda as a tribute to a half-century
political career in which he championed the elderly and the poor,
his former colleagues promise.
   Pepper's political odyssey, one of the longest in American
history, ended Tuesday with his death at age 88. A Florida Democrat
who served as a state representative before his election to the
U.S. Senate in 1936, Pepper later served in the House after 12
years out of office and became its oldest member.
   ``He was always a voice for the voiceless and a helping hand for
the helpless,'' said House Speaker Jim Wright, D-Texas. Wright said
the House will adopt a resolution today so that Pepper can lie in
state Thursday.
   The Senate was also expected to approve the resolution today,
Wright said. Lying in state in the Rotunda is the highest final
honor an American can receive. It has been accorded presidents, and
more recently to the unknown soldier from the Vietnam war.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new Congress met today to choose a commission
that Mikhail S. Gorbachev said should ``get down to the roots'' of
the troop assault that claimed the lives of 19 pro-independence
demonstrators in Soviet Georgia.
   Boisterous debate in the Congress of People's Deputies on
Tuesday far overshadowed the Soviet president's earlier address on
foreign and domestic policy.
   The heated session featured a standing ovation for a Georgian
delegate, heckling of the military commander for the southern
republic and a soul-searching speech by the chief of the Georgian
Communist Party.
   More than 400 of the 2,250 deputies have signed up to respond to
Gorbachev's state of the union address, in which he called the
Georgian violence an example of ``tragic events with the loss of
human life'' that can happen among the Soviet Union's more than 100
national groups.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Transplant doctors predict pigs will become a
main source of donor organs for people once the many technical
problems of cross-species transplantation are resolved.
   While primates such as chimpanzees and baboons might be a better
match, pigs are cheaper, more plentiful and easier to breed, says
Dr. Hugh Auchincloss Jr., assistant professor of surgery at Harvard
University.
   ``What could change, I suppose, is that we could become better
at making artificial organs than we are now. Then we wouldn't need
the animal organs. But I don't see that as coming first,''
Auchincloss said Tuesday at the annual meeting of the American
Society of Transplant Physicians.
   Only 50 to 60 chimpanzees are available in any given year for
all types of research, according to Auchincloss.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   High schools are requiring students to read
almost exactly what they did 25 years ago: heavy on Shakespeare but
light on works by female and minority authors, according to a
survey.
   Eighty-four percent of public high schools assign students
``Romeo and Juliet,'' the tearful Shakespearean play that tops the
list of required works, according to the nationwide survey by the
Center for the Learning &amp; Teaching of Literature at State
University of New York at Albany.
   But only one of the top 10 most frequently assigned works was by
a female author _ ``To Kill A Mockingbird,'' by Harper Lee. No
works were by minorities, according to the survey of 322 public
schools, 80 Catholic schools and 86 private schools conducted last
spring.
   ``I think the survey shows schools are still very much concerned
with emphasizing good literature. They continue to assign classics
complemented with modern and accessible works,'' said the survey's
author, Arthur N. Applebee.
</TEXT>
