<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Billionaire Marvin Davis and Pan Am Corp.
said they submitted acquisition proposals for NWA Inc., but
declined to outline specifics of their bids.
   NWA, parent of Northwest Airlines, had set a Tuesday deadline
for receiving bids in its buyout auction but declined to disclose
who the suitors were or how many proposals it had received. NWA
stock closed up $1.25 at $107.25 a share on the New York Stock
Exchange.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of new homes were up a strong 10.9
percent in April, the government reported, but housing economists
say the industry will remain sluggish at least into summer because
of high interest rates.
   The increase in sales to 620,000 units on a seasonally adjusted
annual basis reported Tuesday was due to an aberration in sales in
February and March, when sales dropped 10.9 percent and 10.4
percent, respectively, economists said.
   The April increase was the steepest since a 13.9 percent jump in
February 1988.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A dozen investments of more than $1 billion
each helped increase foreign direct investments in the United
States to $65 billion last year, a 61.3 percent rise over 1987's
$40.3 billion, the Commerce Department reported.
   Britain and Japan led the world in buying or establishing
business enterprises in the United States and each had four of the
dozen $1 billion-plus investors, the department said Tuesday. Two
Canadian investments also also topped the $1 billion mark.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar slipped below 2 West German marks in
late trading in a choppy session dominated by speculation about an
interest-rate increase by the West German central bank.
   The dollar finished Tuesday above the levels in reached last
Friday in New York but below where it traded Monday in Europe. The
U.S. and British currency markets were closed for Memorial Day
holiday on Monday.
   Last week the dollar rose above 2 marks for the first time in 2{
years and went over 140 Japanese yen for the first time in 1{ years.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan's central bank announced it will raise its
official discount rate by 0.75 percentage points to 3.25 percent,
in the first increase in the key rate in almost a decade.
   Bank of Japan Governor Satoshi Sumita said Tuesday the decision
to raise the rate effective Wednesday resulted from the bank's
desire to stem inflation and strengthen the yen, which has fallen
against the U.S. dollar in recent months. Commercial bank interest
rates will rise in mid-June, officials said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A partnership of Quantum Chemical Corp. and the
investment firm First Boston Inc. has agreed to buy the Petrolane
propane gas business from Panhandle Eastern Corp. and public
shareholders in a deal valued at $1.18 billion.
   QFB Partners, the newly formed combination, will pay $450
million to Panhandle Eastern for Petrolane Inc., which consists of
a 44 percent interest in Petrolane Partners L.P. and a 100 percent
interest in a company that owns and leases propane tanks to the
partnership. The deal was announced Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jack D. Kuehler was elected president of
International Business Machines Corp., but the technology-minded
executive is not in line to be chairman because he is older than
the current officeholder.
   Kuehler is 56. John F. Akers, the chairman and chief executive,
is 54. The new job for Kuehler is a recognition of his
contributions in a 31-year career at the company, IBM spokesman
Peter Judice said Tuesday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CLEVELAND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   LTV Steel Co. said that parent company LTV
Corp. has agreed to sell its bar division as part of an employee
stock ownership plan.
   The presidents of United Steelworkers union locals in the steel
division last week voted 5-3 for the plan. LTV Steel confirmed the
sale Tuesday.
   Officials said 4,700 salaried, hourly or senior management
employees in the bar division initially will work for the new
company, which is expected to produce about 1.2 million tons of
steel annually.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Avon Products Inc. has told Mary Kay Corp. that
Avon isn't for sale and sees no potential benefit from combining
the two cosmetics sellers.
   James E. Preston, Avon's chairman and chief executive officer,
made the statement in a letter to John Rochon, Mary Kay vice
chairman, released Tuesday.Preston also indicated Mary Kay has had
a longstanding interest in Avon.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>By The Associated Press</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market fell Tuesday as a wave of computerized program
selling overwhelmed buyers returning from the Memorial Day weekend.
The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks ended down 18.22
points at 2,475.55, its biggest one-day loss in a week.
   The dollar slipped in choppy trading.
   Bond prices were mixed.
   Cocoa futures prices plunged on a report that Ivory Coast, the
world's largest cocoa producer, will slash the prices it pays
farmers. Grain and soybean futures fell; precious metals were
mixed; frozen pork bellies were lower; and petroleum futures were
mixed.
</TEXT>
