<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 0226EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Mexico-Oil     05-31 0242</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mexico-Oil,0250</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mexico Evaluating New Discovery Of Light-Type Crude</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ISAAC A. LEVI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Experts are evaluating an extra-light type of
crude oil recently discovered in at least three fields in
southeastern Mexico to determine if it is profitable for marketing,
according to a source at the state petroleum monopoly Pemex.
   The new Toltec crude is at least 40 degrees on the American
Petroleum Institute's gravity scale _ the lightest found so far in
Mexico, said the source, who spoke Tuesday on condition of
anonymity.
   It was discovered at the beginning of the year at ``great
depth'' in the Juju, Tecominuacan, Paredon and other onshore fields
that lie between the Gulf of Mexico port of Coatzacoalcos and
Villahermosa, the capital of Tabasco state.
   ``We are still making studies of the characteristics of this
crude. We are taking a series of samples and analyzing them to see
what characteristics they have, their yield and what (production)
problems are involved,'' the source added, refusing to say more.
   The Toltec is even lighter than the Olmec variety, measuring 38
to 39 degrees, discovered by Pemex last year in the state of
Tabasco and Chiapas states and now being exported in small
quanitities.
   One of Mexico's two other traditional varieties, the Isthmus
measures 33 API and the heavy Maya 22. The Olmec has been found to
contain very little sulphur and metals. Lighter crude is easier to
refine.
</TEXT>
