<FIRST>r f PM-Northwest Bjt   05-31 0584</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Northwest, Bjt,0602</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pan Am, Marvin Davis Meet Bidding Deadline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   NWA Inc., parent of Northwest Airlines, has
started to evaluate buyout offers, including bids by billionaire
Marvin Davis and Pan Am Corp.
   Davis and Pan Am said they met NWA's Tuesday afternoon deadline
for submitting acquisition proposals, but declined to outline
specifics of their bids. Northwest, the nation's fourth-largest
airline, would not disclose who the suitors were or how many
proposals it received.
   NWA's stock closed up $1.25 at $107.25 a share Tuesday on the
New York Stock Exchange.
   James Fingeroth, a spokesman for Davis, said the Los
Angeles-based oil and real estate mogul made an offer but retained
a limited right to pursue his outstanding hostile tender offer of
$2.7 billion, or $90 a share, for NWA. The tender offer was
scheduled to expire this afternoon, but likely would be extended,
Fingeroth said.
   Fingeroth declined to provide details of the latest Davis offer,
which was submitted to NWA's financial adviser, First Boston Corp.
A spokeswoman for First Boston said none of the bidders or bids
would be disclosed.
   Pan Am indicated earlier Tuesday that it had obtained $2.7
billion in bank financing for a buyout plan that it submitted by
the deadline, but declined to disclose terms of the bid. The
proposal also includes at least $400 million in new equity
financing from a group that includes Prudential-Bache Securities
Inc. and the partnership Airlie Group L.P.
   Other potential bidders that have expressed interest in NWA
included an investment group led by former Marriott Corp. executive
Al Checchi; Northwest's 20,000-member machinists union, which has
indicated it might team with an outside investor to buy a major
stake in the airline; and the Wall Street buyout firm Kohlberg
Kravis Roberts &amp; Co.
   Checchi did not return phone calls Tuesday and a KKR spokesman
in New York said the firm would not comment. Guy Cook, president of
the International Association of Machinists District Lodge 143,
also did not return calls seeking to determine if the union had
submitted a buyout plan.
   NWA has directed four of its outside directors to review all
offers, but Chairman Steven Rothmeier repeatedly has said the board
could ultimately decide not to sell.
   Possible alternatives for NWA include acquisition of another
company, a partial or complete liquidation of the airline, a
repurchase of shares, payment of a special dividend, or the sale of
a bid stake to a ``white squire'' group that would obtain a
controlling interest but would support current management.
   Northwest, based in suburban Eagan, has said it would like to
make a decision in the takeover battle by the end of June.
   The NWA board has pushed for a single round of bidding, but
analysts said the process could start over if a higher bid arrives
after the deadline.
   Cooperation from Northwest's unions is considered crucial to the
bid by Pan Am.
   Industry analysts have been cautious about Pan Am's prospects
because of that company's $900 million in debt, $535 million in
outstanding pension liabilities and continuing operating losses.
   Pan Am Chairman Thomas Plaskett told investors last week that
should his bid for NWA succeed, he plans no sales of operating
assets and no sale or lease-back of planes.
   Plaskett also has said he was not counting on any revenue from a
sale of NWA's real estate in Japan, but would save $240 million by
streamlining the new carrier's corporate headquarters, marketing
operation, maintenance and other support services.
</TEXT>
