<FIRST>r f PM-IBMSupercomputers     05-31 0257</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-IBM Supercomputers,0267</SECOND>
<HEAD>IBM Announces Supercomputing Equipment, Software</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. has
announced supercomputing equipment that an executive said would
``compete very favorably against the other manufacturers of
supercomputers in the world.''
   IBM offers equipment and software that can be added onto its
most powerful mainframe computers so they function as
supercomputers. Although Cray Research Inc. is considered the
world's leading supercomputer manufacturer, IBM has actually sold
more units when its souped-up mainframes are counted.
   IBM developed the new offerings in cooperation with partners
including Cornell University and Los Alamos National Laboratory,
said the IBM executive, Thomas Jarosh, director of scientific and
technical computing marketing in the United States.
   Jarosh declined Tuesday to specify the peak speed of the systems
so no direct comparison is possible with machines made by Cray and
other supercomputer makers.
   Prices will be announced in 60 days and installations will begin
no later than the last quarter of 1989.
   IBM's most powerful mainframe computer is the ES-3090 Model 600,
which has six processors. New hardware and software will allow
customers to hook two of those machines together so a job can be
run across as many as 12 processors at once.
   Also announced was a communications channel that can transfer
data at 800 million bits a second. IBM said it was the first
channel to meet a draft standard established by the American
National Standards Institute.
   In addition, IBM said new software would speed up the computer's
ability to find and place data in storage devices.
</TEXT>
