<SECOND>PM-Polaroid,0315</SECOND>
<HEAD>Polaroid Discusses Strategy At Stockholders Meeting</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WELLESLEY, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polaroid Corp. outlined new corporate
strategies at its annual stockholders meeting, but the company's
successful defense against a hostile takeover was mentioned only
briefly.
   The topic of Polaroid's hard-fought battle to repel a $3.1
billion bid by investor Roy E. Disney, made through his Shamrock
Holdings Inc., came up when a shareholder asked a nominal question
about it Tuesday, officials said.
   The meeting instead focused on new marketing, product
development and manufacturing strategies by the company, based in
nearby Cambridge.
   Polaroid President I. MacAllister Booth told the group of about
1,200 stockholders at Wellesley College that the company in 1988
re-evaluated ``its technology, its marketplace, its organization
and its behavior, making a rapid, quantifiable leap forward in
profitability.''
   ``We are in the midst of a major turnaround in this company, and
because of the progress we have made, I have confidence that this
turnaround will continue,'' said Booth.
   Polaroid Group Vice President William J. O'Neill said the
company is aiming for a 50 percent increase in the growing imaging
field by 1995. Imaging refers to the storage of pictures or
documents through electronic means, as opposed to photographic
means.
   Carl J. Yankowski, vice-president of marketing, said Polaroid
will develop new market-driven technologies, especially in imaging.
   Yankowski said dealer and consumer response to Polaroid's new
conventional ``OneFilm'' has been favorable. The film represents
the first time Polaroid has ventured out of its specialty,
self-developing film. OneFilm is made for Polaroid by Minnesota
Mining &amp; Manufacturing Co., or 3M.
   Polaroid reported a first-quarter profit of $25.9 million on
revenue of $442.3 million, compared with a profit of $14.2 million
on revenue of $410.1 million for the same 1988 period. Polaroid
said it spend $38.5 million to fight off Shamrock in the period.
</TEXT>
