<FIRST>r f PM-Eastern-Ad Bjt   05-31 0542</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Ad, Bjt,0566</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Runs First TV Ad Since Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an effort to persuade consumers it is
reliable, punctual and run by experienced workers, Eastern Airlines
has started advertising on television for the first time since the
start of a bruising strike.
   Eastern recently began running the commercial in Miami, New
York, Washington and Atlanta, at a cost of more than $500,000. The
beleaguered airline already had been advertising in major
newspapers.
   ``We're trying to build awareness and provide some
information,'' George Brennan, Eastern's vice president of
marketing, said Tuesday in a telephone interview.
   In recent weeks, Miami-based Eastern has been promoting its new
plan to rebuild as a smaller carrier and sell about $1.8 billion of
assets.
   The plan still must be approved by federal bankruptcy court in
New York, where Eastern filed for Chapter 11 protection and
reorganization shortly after the March 4 strike began.
   But U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Burton R. Lifland has given Eastern
permission to sell its Northeast shuttle service to developer
Donald Trump for $365 million and to lease 14 Boeing 727-200s to
Pan Am Corp. for $57.9 million over three years.
   Frank Lorenzo, chairman of Eastern's parent Texas Air Corp., has
been defending his plan in meetings with media organizations such
as USA Today, The Associated Press and NBC News.
   Eastern's unions, on the other hand, are pushing for a sale of
the entire airline.
   Of the 31,200 pilots, Machinists union members and flight
attendants employed by Eastern before the strike, only a few have
crossed picket lines. The airline has hired about 500 new pilots
and 60 skilled mechanics.
   Eastern's operations have been sharply reduced by the strike and
it has run only about 10 percent of its normal flight schedule.
   The TV ad doesn't mention the strike or bankruptcy filing. It
features a pilot who has flown for Eastern for 31 years and a
21-year maintenance manager speaking to the camera while seated at
a desk. The words ``Experience,'' ``Commitment'' and ``On-Time
Performance'' flash at intervals.
   The maintenance manager, Charlie Fisher, emphasizes what he
calls the cooperative attitude and ``esprit de corps'' of Eastern
workers. The pilot, Hal Harley, says that more than 5,000 Eastern
flights have arrived on time since April 1.
   ``We've got a brand new Eastern Airlines with a bunch of old
pros,'' Fisher says. ``We're taking off'' is flashed on the screen.
   The average age of newly hired pilots is 39 years, up sharply
from the pre-strike average of pilots in their late 20s, according
to the company.
   Fisher said the commercial was made in about six hours with no
script and no rehearsing. ``I think most employees would have given
anything to be in my place,'' he said in a phone interview from
Miami. ``I think the message we wanted to say got across.''
   Striking pilots disagreed.
   ``It's sad to see these lost sheep supporting Frank Lorenzo and
Texas Air,'' said Dan Ashby, a union spokesman.
   In New York, meanwhile, the ad agency Scali, McCabe, Sloves Inc.
announced it had won the ad contract for the Trump Shuttle.
Advertising for Eastern's shuttle had been handled by Lintas, which
does ads for the rest of the airline.
</TEXT>
