<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 0156EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-HealthCosts Bjt   05-31 0625</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Health Costs, Bjt,0641</SECOND>
<HEAD>Study: Insurers Must Consider Cost-Effectiveness Of New Medical Technologies</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER CALLAHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Faced with spiraling medical costs, insurers
must begin weighing not only the health benefits of new medical
technologies but their costs and whether improved care justifies
the added expense, says a study by New England's largest health
maintenance organization.
   ``Cost is a legitimate consideration in making coverage
decisions,'' said a report issued Tuesday by the Harvard Community
Health Plan. ``Even when it is established that a new, more
expensive therapy is better than the existing alternatives, one
must question whether the added benefit is worth the added cost.''
   The report said that without a framework to evaluate the cost
and effectiveness of technologies, decisions on what should be
covered by insurance will be ``put off until time of crisis (and
then) are more likely to be influenced by emotions or political
expedience than by medical efficacy.''
   ``Not only might underserving technologies be approved, but the
most deserving technologies may be overlooked,'' the report said.
   The study said new technologies must first be investigated to
see if they represent an improvement in health care.
   The study pointed to rapid adoption of tissue plasminogen
activator, a genetically engineered drug for dissolving blood clots
that cause heart attacks. The report said it remained unclear
whether the drug, at $2,000 per dose, is any more effective than
Streptokinase, a competing drug, at $200 a dose.
   The report, based on the findings of a three-year study by a
special commission appointed by Harvard Community Health, also
suggested that older procedures be periodically evaluated.
   ``It was once thought that the minimal dangers of circumcision
were far outweighed by health benefits to the child, and so the
practice was commonly covered by insurers. Recent findings have led
many in the medical community to question whether the procedure
provides any health benefit,'' the commission said.
   But beyond comparing the effectiveness of various technologies,
insurers also should weigh the relative worth of new technologies
that are proven to be more effective. Insurers should ``avoid
treatments that cost far more than any benefits they might bring
about are worth,'' the study said.
   ``Few, if any, health plans now acknowledge considering cost in
their coverage decisions. The result is that cost effectiveness is
rarely analyzed in any rigorous way, and there is little pressure
on the proponents of new therapies to establish their relative
effectiveness.
   ``Those technologies that offer the greatest incremental gain
for the incremental cost ought to be adopted first,'' the
commission said. In addition, the panel said, new technologies that
benefit the largest number of members should be selected before
``those whose benefits would be limited to a few members.''
   The commission suggested a cap on the cost of new technologies
based on ``how many years' worth of earnings ought to be devoted to
extending a member's life for one year.''
   ``As more and more resources are devoted to extending a life for
a short time, it becomes clear that choices must be made between
competing goods,'' the panel said.
   Harvard Community Health created the commission in 1985 after
the Brookline, Mass., health organization became the nation's first
HMO to provide coverage for heart and liver transplants.
   ``The increasing sophistication and cost of new technology poses
a dilemma for all HMOs and health insurers: the HMO or insurer must
balance the welfare of the individual patient against the welfare
of all the people who pay premiums into the fund,'' wrote Thomas O.
Pyle, the HMO's president.
   ``By presenting this summary, we do not mean to imply that HCHP
endorses all of the commission's conclusions. Our goal is to
stimulate discussion in the hope that the community will benefit,''
said Pyle.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890531-0260 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 0157EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Avon-MaryKay Bjt   05-31 0583</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Avon-Mary Kay, Bjt,0606</SECOND>
<HEAD>Avon Says `No' to Mary Kay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Avon Products Inc. has told Mary Kay Corp. that
Avon isn't for sale and sees no potential benefit from combining
the two cosmetics sellers.
   James E. Preston, Avon's chairman and chief executive officer,
stated in a letter Tuesday to John Rochon, Mary Kay vice chairman:
``We strongly believe our opportunities will be better achieved by
Avon continuing with our business plan.''
   In the letter, released by Avon, Preston indicated Mary Kay has
had a longstanding interest in Avon.
   ``As I told you last January, we see no advantage to combining
our operations through some form of leveraged buyout or other
arrangement,'' Preston said.
   The reference was to a Jan. 11 New York dinner meeting between
Preston and Rochon, Avon spokesman John Cox said. The two had no
other face-to-face contact and spoke by telephone only once, to set
up the meeting.
   During the meeting, attended only by the two executives, Rochon
extolled the advantages of being a private company and asked
Preston to take Avon private and unite with Mary Kay.
   Rochon has been given much of the credit for the financial
success of the the 1985 leveraged buyout of the Dallas-based
door-to-door cosmetics company.
   Rochon also told Preston an LBO could provide Preston with a
financial windfall, allowing him to leave the company in a few
years several million dollars richer, Cox said.
   Preston replied that he wasn't interested and even if he were
contemplating a leveraged buyout he wouldn't need Mary Kay to do
it, according to the Avon spokesman.
   Although the meeting occurred in January, Avon had been aware of
Mary Kay's possible intentions earlier.
   The first hint came two years ago when Joel Stern of the
investment firm Stern Stewart &amp; Co. approached Avon about the
possibility of buying Mary Kay. He said he was working as a
consultant for Mary Kay, according to Cox.
   Avon's management evaluated the idea and decided the two direct
sellers wouldn't make a good match, he said. Plus, Avon sales
representatives probably would have reacted negatively because, in
some areas of the country, the Mary Kay sales force is the main
competition.
   Several months later in 1987 word came to Avon that someone was
preparing a hostile bid, Cox said. At about the same time, a public
relations firm Avon had hired resigned the account on the grounds
there might be a conflict with another client's business. The other
client was Mary Kay.
   Over the two years, Avon has been told Mary Kay has searched
unsuccessfully for investment partners to help buy Avon, Cox said.
Avon also learned Mary Kay wasn't interested in Avon's
international business, due to concerns about the risk of currency
fluctuations.
   Avon has learned that Mary Kay started buying Avon shares last
Nov. 10 but stopped short the threshold that would have triggered
federal ownerhip disclosure requirements, Cox said.
   No one at Mary Kay was available to comment on Avon's portrayal
of the events, a public relations representative said.
   Rochon publicly conveyed his company's feelings about Avon in a
letter to Preston last week that was released by Mary Kay. No terms
of proposed merger have been mentioned by Rochon.
   Earlier this month, Avon's board rejected an offer by Amway
Corp. to buy Avon for $39 a share, or about $2.1 billion. Amway
later withdrew the offer.
   In composite New York Stock Exchange trading Tuesday, Avon
closed at $35.62{ a share, down $1.12{.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890531-0261 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 0736EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-US-EuropeTrade     05-31 0292</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-US-Europe Trade,0300</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Embargoed for release at 6 a.m. EDT; time set by source. Also
moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<HEAD>U.S.-European Talks on Exports to Resume</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Talks will resume this summer to set standards
under which U.S. products could be exported to Europe after
internal trade barriers are lifted there in 1992, it was announced
today.
   Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher and Martin Bangemann,
European Commission vice president, announced the resumption of
talks in a joint communique released here and in Paris. The talke
are to be held in Brussels, Belgium.
   ``The issues of how standards will be set and what they will be
is a top concern of the American business community,'' Mosbacher
said in a statement released by the Commerce Department. ``With
this agreement to establish a dialogue, we have made significant
progress toward easing that concern.''
   The 12 nations comprising the European Community have agreed to
remove trade barriers in 1992 and operate as a single $4 trillion
market with 320 million consumers. Some government and business
leaders fear the regulations and technical standards being written
for the transition could result in barriers against U.S. goods.
   Mosbacher and Bangemann, who met Tuesday in Brussels, where
President Bush was attending the NATO summit, agreed that products
imported into the new European market would have the same access to
testing and certification procedures as European products.
   They also agreed there should be exploratory talks on
negotiations to ensure mutually recognized arrangements for product
safety and quality, the Commerce Department statement said.
   ``Establishing this dialogue between the United States and the
European Community is an important step for us to take together,''
Mosbacher said. ``It reassures American business and holds great
promise for the entire world trading system.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
