<FIRST>r f BC-Japan-Investment     05-31 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Japan-Investment,0384</SECOND>
<HEAD>America Biggest Investor in Japan; U.S. Top Spot For Japanese Investors</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American companies were the biggest investors in
Japan, while the United States was the number-one destination for
Japanese investment overseas last year, Finance Ministry officials
said Wednesday.
   Investment by foreign countries in Japan jumped sharply last
year, and investment by Japan overseas hit a record high, they said.
   Despite the high yen, which makes investing in Japan expensive,
foreign companies increased their investment in Japan 46.5 percent
to $3.24 billion during the fiscal year ended March 31. American
companies took 54.7 percent of the total, according to a report
released Wednesday by the Finance Ministry.
   American investment in Japan jumped 89.1 percent over the
previous year to total $1.77 billion, the report said.
   During the same period, Japan's direct overseas investment hit a
record high for the fifth year in a row, jumping 40.9 percent in
fiscal 1988 over the previous year to $47.02 billion, a ministry
official said, citing a report released Tuesday.
   The United States attracted the most direct investment from
Japan _ $21.7 billion in fiscal 1988, up 47.6 percent from the
previous year.
   A total of $3.95 billion from Japan went to Britain during the
period, up 60 percent, while investment in the Netherlands nearly
tripled to $2.39 billion, the report said.
   Ministry officials attributed the increase in Japanese direct
investment overseas to active expansion of overseas production by
Japanese manufacturers and of overseas activities by financial and
real estate companies.
   By industry, direct overseas investment by machinery makers
totaled $1.43 billion, more than double the level in fiscal 1987;
investment by the chemical sector rose 42.1 percent to $1.29
billion; the steel and non-ferrous metal sector rose 73.9 percent
to $1.36 billion; and electric makers were up 25.6 percent to $3.04
billion, the report said.
   In the services sector, financial and insurance firms together
invested $13.1 billion overseas, up 22.8 percent from the previous
year. Real estate firms invested $8.64 billion, up 59.2 percent,
the report said.
   The report counted as direct overseas investment any investment
of more than 10 percent in an overseas firm, investment in overseas
branches by home firms and expansion of their subsidiaries in
foreign countries.
</TEXT>
