<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 0836EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-BiasCase     05-31 0379</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Bias Case,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Subsidiaries of Japanese Company Face Bias Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In an unusual move, the vice chairman of
the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission has charged two U.S.
subsidiaries of Japan's Recruit Co. with ``blatant'' employment
discrimination based on race, sex, age and national origin.
   Commissioners rarely bring charges themselves, but EEOC vice
chairman E. Gaull Silberman said she believed that
Interplace@Transworld Recruit and Recruit USA are continuing to
violate anti-discrimination laws.
   In addition, a judge for the U.S. District Court in Northern
California issued a temporary restraining order Tuesday prohibiting
the company from destroying, altering or removing from the country
any documents relating to an EEOC investigation.
   Recruit Co. was at the center of Japan's bribery scandal that
led to the recent resignation of Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita.
   With headquarters in Los Angeles, Interplace is an employment
agency with nine offices in cities that include New York, San
Francisco and San Mateo. Recruit USA shares a headquarters office
with Interplace and publishes help-wanted magazines in the United
States to advertise job openings in Japan.
   Richard Kelley, a senior vice president with Interplace, said
his company and Recruit USA would have no comment until their
lawyers had a chance to examine the charges.
   Court documents include an Interplace memo that describes a code
the company allegedly used on job orders to indicate when a client
wanted an employee of a particular age, sex or race.
   As detailed in the memo, ``Talk to Maria'' meant the client
preferred Hispanics, ``Mary'' meant Caucasians, ``Mariko'' meant
Japanese, ``Adam'' meant men, ``Eve'' meant females and
``Maryanne'' meant blacks. ``Suite 20 to 30'' meant age 20 to 30.
   Last year, after a former employee threatened to expose the
practice, Interplace executive vice president Hideyo Harada ``told
employees in Los Angeles that she had just been instructed `from
the top' to erase codes from all job orders in the computer
database,'' said Linda Krieger, a senior trial attorney with the
EEOC in San Francisco.
   ``We can prove Interplace was violating Title VII (of the Civil
Rights Act) from the job orders we have,'' she said.
   Most charges are filed by aggrieved parties rather than
commissioners themselves. But when employment agencies
discriminate, rejected applicants usually do not know they have
been harmed.
</TEXT>
