<FIRST>r f BC-Mexico-Debt     05-31 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Mexico-Debt,0335</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mexico Reaches Agreement With Creditor Nations To Cut $2.6 Billion
Of Debt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mexico has reached an agreement with 16
creditor nations designed to cut its debt by $2.6 billion and
refinance 80 percent of its debt interest over the next decade, the
government announced.
   The Treasury Department in Mexico announced late Tuesday that
the agreement with the Paris Club, made up of representatives of 16
primary creditor nations, was reached in Paris earlier in the day.
   Under the agreement, Mexico's foreign debt would be cut by a
refinancing of credits for exportations to the 16 creditor nations
involved.
   Mexico currently suffers from a $107.4 billion debt and is among
the largest debtor nations in Latin America, second only to Brazil.
   New President Carlos Salinas de Gortari and Treasury Secretary
Pedro Aspe have made refinancing of the foriegn debt a national
priority and Aspe has made numerous trips to Washington for debt
negotiations.
   Mexico in recent months has been presenting creditor foreign
banks and governments with a menu of options designed to reduce
real servicing costs on the foreign debt.
   The country paid $9 billion in interest and $5 billion in
principal in 1988 and servicing costs are expected to reach $16
billion this year.
   In a statement released Tuesday night, the Treasury Department
called the agreement ``exciting'' and said it was ``a solid
additional step in the firm and serious renegotiation of the
foreign debt.''
   It said members of the Club of Paris had accepted the plan,
presented by a Mexican delegation headed by Jose Angel Gurria,
deputy treasury secretary in charge of international financial
affairs.
   The International Monetary Fund announced in Washington on
Friday that it had formally approved a $4.1 billion credit line to
Mexico, which was first outlined in a letter of credit announced
several weeks ago.
   Of the total, Mexico is to use some 40 percent to pay off its
foreign debt.
</TEXT>
