<FIRST>r f PM-Hasbro-Hassenfeld     05-31 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hasbro-Hassenfeld,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hasbro Chief Hospitalized for Pneumonia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stephen D. Hassenfeld, chairman and
chief executive of toymaking giant Hasbro Inc., has been
hospitalized in New York City with pneumonia and is in intensive
care, the company announced.
   The company issued a brief statement Tuesday announcing
Hassenfeld's illness, but did not provide details. The Providence
Journal-Bulletin said a spokeswoman at Columbia Presbyeterian
Hospital in New York confirmed that Hassenfeld, 47, was
hospitalized there.
   The spokeswoman declined to provide details at the request of
Hassenfeld's family, the newspaper said. A Hasbro spokesman said
Hassenfeld was in stable condition.
   John T. O'Neill, Hasbro's chief financial officer, said
Hassenfeld was hospitalized Friday, but The Wall Street Journal
said the executive was hospitalized Wednesday following more than a
year of speculation that he was seriously ill. Hassenfeld
repeatedly has denied rumors that he is suffering from acquired
immune deficiency syndrome or any related illness, the newspaper
said.
   The speculation began after he missed 10 weeks of work beginning
in July 1987 because of a bacterial infection of the heart lining.
Hassenfeld, who maintains homes in Bristol, R.I., and New York,
also was hospitalized at Columbia Presbyterian for that health
problem.
   Hassenfeld, the grandson of the company's founder, is credited
with building Hasbro into one of the country's major toy companies
through a series of acquisitions, including Milton Bradley Co., and
introduction of consistently successful new products. Among
Hasbro's well-known toys are GI Joe and Transformers.
   The company had sales of $1.34 billion last year, compared with
$104.3 million in 1980.
   Hasbro's stock climbed $1.25 per share on Tuesday, closing at
$20.62{ on the American Stock Exchange, on speculation that Hasbro
might be a takeover target because of Hassenfeld's illness.
   ``There's lots of speculation going on, but probably very little
of substance,'' said Richard W. Morsilli, manager of the Providence
office of Smith Barney, Harris Uphanm &amp; Co.
   ``For every 10 takeover stories I hear, maybe one happens.''
   O'Neill said Hassenfeld had been running a high fever, ``and he
finally got to the point that his doctors advised him to have a
rest and get into the hospital. The hope and the intent is that
Stephen will mend and will be back to running this company.''
   Hassenfeld's pneumonia did not appear to be linked to his
previous heart infection, O'Neill said.
   Alan Hassenfeld, Stephen Hassenfeld's 40-year-old brother who is
Hasbro's president and chief operating officer, will run the
company in the interim, O'Neill said.
   The Hassenfeld family owns 13.1 percent of the company stock and
Warner Communicatons owns 13.6 percent, which is held in a voting
trust controlled by the Hassenfeld brothers. Hasbro has the right
of first refusal to purchase Warner's stock.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
