<FIRST>r f BC-CluettPeabodyBid     05-31 0200</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Cluett Peabody Bid,0207</SECOND>
<HEAD>Union Plans Bid for West Point-Pepperell Division</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Amalgamated Clothing and Textile Workers
Union says it intends to use an employee stock ownership plan in a
bid to buy Cluett, Peabody &amp; Co., the men's apparel division of
West Point-Pepperell Inc.
   Chicago-based Farley Inc., which acquired West Point early this
year, said last month that it had retained Drexel Burnham Lambert
Inc. to find ways ``to maximize the value of West Point-Pepperell
Inc.'s Cluett Peabody &amp; Co.''
   Published reports have indicated that several companies may be
interested in acquiring Cluett, including Phillips-Van Heusen
Corp., a large manufacturer of shirts.
   No details of the union's plans, such as financing arrangements,
were available.
   The union intentions became known after it issued a notice of a
news conference scheduled for Friday. The Wall Street Journal
reported Wednesday that the news conference was canceled after the
union learned that Farley would meet with the union soon.
   Cluett's three divisions are Arrow, which makes men's shirts; J.
Schoeneman, which makes men's tailored suits; and Gold Toe, a maker
of men's socks.
   Its factories in Georgia, Alabama, Maryland, North Carolina,
Pennsylvania and Delaware employ more than 8,000 workers.
