<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   05-31 0341</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grain Futures Gain on Notions That Losses Were Overdone</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were mostly
higher in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade,
partially reflecting notions that prices have fallen too far, too
fast in recent weeks.
   The soybean market posted the strongest early gains, with the
price for September delivery of new-crop soybeans opening at $6.58
a bushel, 7{ cents above Tuesday's close.
   Grain and soybean prices sank on Tuesday, continuing a
three-week trend that has taken soybeans for July delivery from
about $7.45 a bushel to less than $7.15, and July corn from about
$2.75 a bushel to less than $2.65 since May 1.
   The recent, broad decline in prices is due to increased rainfall
in the Midwest, which has reduced fears of a second consecutive
drought year.
   ``The weather pattern has obviously been different and that has
been weighing on the markets and the whole thing has been going
down,'' said Dale Gustafson, a grain-market analyst with Drexel
Burnham Lambert Inc. in Chicago.
   In early trading, wheat was { cent lower to 1{ cents higher with
the contract for delivery in July at $3.91 a bushel; corn was 1
cent to 2{ cents higher with July at $2.62} a bushel; oats were 1}
cents to 2{ cents higher with July at $1.67\ a bushel; soybeans
were 2 cents to 8 cents higher with July at $7.19 a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .35 cent lower to .25 cent higher with June at
68.95 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .20 cent lower to .13 cent
higher with August at 76.65 cents a pound; live hogs were .08 cent
lower to .13 cent higher with June at 47.40 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were .02 cent lower to .23 cent higher with July at
29.45 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly lower on Tuesday with
pork bellies down sharply.
</TEXT>
