<DOCNO> AP890531-0274 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 1215EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-PennwaltPlea     05-31 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pennwalt Plea,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Won't Accept Pennwalt Plea Without Company Executive Present</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TACOMA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge refused to accept a guilty
plea from Pennwalt Corp. in the settlement of a pollution case
because none of the top corporate officers of the chemical company
showed up in the courtroom.
   ``Are we going to let lawyers plead guilty for them?'' U.S.
District Judge Jack Tanner said Tuesday. ``Why? What happens to the
deterrence we talk about?''
   Individuals who plead guilty to crimes are required to appear in
court, Tanner said. ``Why should we treat corporations different
than individuals?'' he said.
   Prosecutor David Marshall, a special assistant U.S. attorney,
replied that the law allows attorneys to plead guilty on behalf of
corporations.
   ``Maybe that's one of the problems,'' Tanner said, adding,
``What message is sent to them?''
   Marshall said the company's willingness to pay $1.1 million as
part of the plea agreement would deter others.
   ``They just throw money at it that they just pass on to the
public,'' Tanner said.
   The case involved a 1985 spill of a cancer-causing agent into a
Tacoma waterway.
   The company's attorney, Thomas Kelly Jr., of the Seattle law
firm Preston, Thorgrimson, Ellis &amp; Holman, said Pennwalt's board of
directors had approved the plea agreement.
   Kelly said the board and Pennwalt's top officers took the case
seriously.
   Tanner said it wasn't fair for an unknown board of directors to
allow an attorney to plead guilty by submitting a written plea
agreement.
   Marshall then asked Tanner if he wanted Pennwalt's chief
executive officer or another top executive to appear in court.
   Tanner didn't specify what officer would be appropriate but said
he wouldn't accept ``some official who is going to retire in six
months.''
   The charges stemmed from the spill of at least 75,000 gallons of
a chemical containing sodium dichromate into Tacoma's Hylebos
Waterway in 1985 after the rupture of a 180,000-gallon storage tank
that had been poorly maintained.
   Sodium dichromate is a toxic compound containing hexavalent
chromium, a cancer-causing agent.
   The agreement called for the company to plead guilty to five
misdemeanor counts _ two counts of negligently failing to maintain
adequate storage tanks at its Tacoma plant, two counts of
discharging pollutants, and one count of failing to promptly report
the 1985 spill to the Coast Guard.
   The company agreed to pay the $1.1 million, $600,000 of it to be
placed in an environmental trust fund to be used by the Coast Guard
to protect Puget Sound.
   In exchange, the government agreed to drop criminal charges
against three company executives in Pennsylvania.
   After the hearing, Kelly said he expected a company officer to
appear before Tanner. A new hearing is expected in the next few
weeks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
