<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 1248EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Nicaragua-Devaluation     05-31 0179</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Nicaragua-Devaluation,0188</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nicaragua Devalues Currency Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government devalued the cordoba
against the dollar for the 18th time this year, effective
Wednesday, and raised the price of gasoline.
   The 4.81 percent devaluation, announced Tuesday night, was
accompanied by a 5.19 percent rise in the price of gasoline.
   The dollar will now fetch 8,300 cordobas, up from 7,900 per
dollar since May 25.
   The price of gasoline increased from 14,600 to 15,400 cordobas
per gallon on Tuesday, the government said. Prices of public
transportation will rise proportionally, the government said.
   Nicaragua depends entirely on imports for gasoline.
   The government announced a 15.5 percent rise in consumer prices
during May, after 12.3 percent inflation during April. Prices rose
more than 20,000 percent last year.
   The government has made severe budget cutbacks by eliminating
the government payroll and freezing salaries to try to control
inflation.
   The Sandinista newspaper Barricada on Wednesday quoted Central
Bank officials as saying the devaluation ``is something normal
within the policy the government has been pursuing for several
months to keep exports competitive.''
</TEXT>
