<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 1406EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-HelpWanted     05-31 0176</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Help Wanted,0183</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Release at 6:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Demand for Labor Increased in April, Conference Board Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Demand for labor as measured by the volume of
help-wanted advertising increased slightly during April, according
to an analysis released Wednesday.
   The Conference Board, a business research organization, said its
monthly Help-Wanted Advertising Index rose to 157 in April from 151
in March.
   The index tracks the volume of classified advertising in 51
major American newspapers and is considered sensitive to changes in
demand for labor and general business conditions.
   Advertising volume rose in all sections of the country except
the West South Central and Mountain regions. Substantial gains in
volume were noted in the South Atlantic and West North Central
regions, the Conference Board said.
   Ken Goldstein, a Conference Board economist, said the
Help-Wanted Index and other indicators point to continued job
growth.
   However, the gain in the index contrasted with a Labor
Department report that job growth slowed in April while
unemployment jumped to 5.3 percent from 5 percent during March.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
