<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 1615EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-ChryslerPlant     05-31 0511</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chrysler Plant,0527</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chrysler Breaks Ground for New Assembly Plant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A quintet of shovel-wielding corporate, union and
government officials broke ground Wednesday for Chrysler Corp.'s
$1-billion Jefferson North assembly plant, which Lee Iacocca called
``a big risk.''
   The five officials _ Iacocca, chairman of the corporation; UAW
Vice President Marc Stepp; Gov. James Blanchard; Sen. Carl Levin
and Mayor Coleman Young _ verbally patted each other on the back at
the ceremony held under a canopy in a gravel-filled mud field.
   ``Some risks have to be taken,'' Iacocca said before the shiny
shovels turned dirt in a small box on a stage. ``For us, this is a
big risk.''
   The plant, which will involve a total investment of about $1
billion, will replace the aging Jefferson Avenue plant and will
begin production of a new line of sport-utility vehicles in January
1992.
   It will employ about 3,000 people and continue a tradition of
Chrysler and its forerunners building vehicles at the site on the
city's east side since 1907.
   Before the first spade of dirt was turned Wednesday, the
Jefferson North plant has been the focus of controversy.
   There have been lingering questions of how much the city paid
for land and equipment when it was getting the property together
for the plant. The state Department of Natural Resources was called
in after reports of toxic substances being found at the site.
   Last week, a controversy arose over Chrysler's hiring of a
Japanese company to do some design and engineering work for the new
plant's paint shop.
   ``We're talking 20 people in the next year and a half,'' Iacocca
said after the ceremony. ``A couple of million dollars, maybe two,
maybe three tops, to do some work on a design board.
   ``It's minuscule. It's so small that it's tough to talk about in
the context of a billion bucks,'' he said.
   Chrysler will make a sport-utility vehicle code-named ``ZJ'' for
Jeep and Dodge dealers at the new plant.
   The company is betting that the sport-utility market, which it
relies upon for much of its profits, will remain strong into the
next decade. Chrysler and French automaker Renault will begin
producing a smaller sport-utility vehicle, the ``JJ,'' shortly
after the ``ZJ'' begins rolling off the assembly line.
   The ``ZJ,'' to be offered in two models, will be larger than the
Jeep Cherokee, now made at Toledo, Ohio. Further details about the
``ZJ'' will be unavailable until closer to production. The Dodge
and Jeep vehicles will receive other names later.
   Chrysler officials have said the ``ZJ'' will not replace the
Cherokee, which still will be made in Toledo after 1992, when the
company's five-year contract with the United Auto Workers union
expires.
   The Jefferson Avenue plant makes the Dodge Omni and Plymouth
Horizon subcompacts. Company officials have said they were unsure
whether those nameplates will continue after 1992.
   The plant is the second assembly plant to be built within
Detroit in the last decade. General Motors Corp.'s Hamtramck plant
began production in 1985.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
