<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 1511EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f BC-HughesLayoffs     05-31 0207</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Hughes Layoffs,0215</SECOND>
<HEAD>6,000 Layoffs Planned Because of Defense Cuts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hughes Aircraft Co. will lay off 6,000
workers in the next six months because of anticipated cuts in
defense spending, the company announced Wednesday.
   The cuts, which amount to 8 percent of the company's workforce
of 75,000, will be in all areas of management, engineering and
manufacturing, the company said.
   Hughes has operations in 12 states, but the bulk of its
workforce is in Southern California, with 6,000 in Tucson, Ariz.
The company, which is owned by General Motors Corp., makes
air-to-air missiles, radar for fighter jets, satellites other
military gear.
   The decision was based on executives' expectation, widely shared
in the defense industry, that defense budgets under the Bush
administration will be smaller than they were in the Reagan era.
   ``We're getting down to fighting trim,'' said Malcolm Currie,
Hughes' chairman and chief executive officer.
   Hughes will try to cushion the blow by trying to make some staff
cuts through attrition and voluntary resignations, and will offer
retraining and job-hunting help.
   The cuts aren't in response to government action on any one
contract, said Hughes spokesman Mike Murphy. No one contract
accounts for more than 6 percent of sales, he said.
</TEXT>
