<FIRST>r f AM-Jackson-Drexel     05-31 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jackson-Drexel,0437</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jesse Jackson's Son Quits Drexel Internship; Cites Press Calls</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Rev. Jesse Jackson's son quit a
summer internship in Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.'s junk bond
department because he was ``bombarded'' with calls from reporters,
a Jackson spokesman said Wednesday.
   Jonathan Luther Jackson, 23, a business student, started working
May 15 in the much-publicized division once run by indicted Wall
Street financier Michael Milken.
   He resigned Tuesday, said Frank Watkins, spokesman for Jackson's
Rainbow Coalition in Washington, D.C.
   ``He's a young man, he was simply trying to work and learn
something about the world of finance and all of a sudden he's
bombarded with press calls,'' Watkins said. ``His work was being
disrupted.''
   Reporters' calls to that Drexel office invariably are referred
to a company spokesman in New York. Drexel spokesman Steve Anreder
said Tuesday that Jackson resigned for unspecified personal reasons.
   Anreder said Wednesday the firm began receiving calls from
reporters about Jackson last Friday. ``I don't know what prompted
it but we were starting to get a lot of calls,'' he said.
   Jackson's Drexel employment was reported in last Friday's issue
of Grant's Interest Rate Observer, an investor newsletter covering
credit markets.
   The younger Jackson, who helped introduce his father at the
Democratic National Convention last year, has a business degree
from North Carolina Agricultural &amp; Technical University and plans
to enroll in a master's program in business at Northwestern
University in Chicago in the fall, Watkins said.
   His internship was in the credit research department, which
studies companies planning to sell high-risk, high-yield bonds
through Drexel.
   In last year's presidential campaign, Jesse Jackson railed
against ``merger-maniacs'' he said were costing jobs. Drexel has
played a major role in financing corporate takeovers this decade,
many through its junk bond division.
   Drexel last year agreed to pay the government $650 million and
plead guilty to six felonies to settle insider trading and
securities fraud charges. Milken took a leave of absence earlier
this year after he was indicted on 98 counts of racketeering and
fraud.
   Drexel also figures in current ethics imbroglios involving two
prominent Democrats.
   House minority whip Tony Coelho of California, who announced he
would resign because of controversy, bought a $100,000 Drexel junk
bond with a loan from Columbia Savings of Beverly Hills that didn't
require him to put up any of his own money.
   The Securities and Exchange Commission and the Justice
Department are investigating whether Los Angeles Mayor Tom Bradley
received preferential treatment in buying junk bonds through Drexel.
</TEXT>
