<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   05-31 0221</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Most Crop Futures Sink On Rain Forecasts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices closed mostly
lower Wednesday on the Chicago Board of Trade as forecasts for more
rain in the Corn Belt quieted fears of a second year of drought.
   ``The midday forecasts were for a continued rainy type of
situation here for another five days and maybe longer,'' said Dale
Gustafson, a grain-market analyst in Chicago with Drexel Burnham
Lambert Inc.
   The heaviest precipitation is expected in Illinois and Iowa, two
key corn-and-soybean states that have only partially recovered from
last year's disastrous drought.
   Prices had opened higher on perceptions that the losses of
recent weeks had been overdone, but the midday weather forecasts
``weakened the strongest portion of the market,'' Gustafson said.
   Since May 1, soybeans for July delivery have dropped from about
$7.45 a bushel to less than $7.15, and July corn has fallen from
about $2.75 a bushel to about $2.60.
   At the close, wheat was unchanged to 5 cents lower with July at
$3.87 a bushel; corn was unchanged to 1{ cents lower with July at
$2.60} a bushel; oats were 1{ cents to 2{ cents higher with July at
$1.66} a bushel; soybeans were 4{ cents lower to { cent higher with
July at $7.13 a bushel.
