<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market was higher in moderate
afternoon trading today, boosted by strengthening bond prices.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 11.03 points to
2,486.58 at 3 p.m. EDT. The blue-chip indicator was 10.48 points
higher at 2 p.m. New York time.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by a margin of about 3 to
2 on the New York Stock Exchange, with 870 issues up, 571 down and
491 unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board totaled 132.34 million shares.
   Stock prices retraced today's earlier losses after an afternoon
rally in the bond market, analysts said.
   Stocks had seesawed through the morning session after the
government released two economic reports for April.
   Prices rose early after the Commerce Department reported that
its chief economic forecasting gauge, the Index of Leading Economic
Indicators, shot up 0.8 percent in April after declining during the
previous two months.
   Analysts said April's upturn, which had been widely anticipated,
was consistent with the view that while the economy is slowing, the
economy is still strong enough to power the record peacetime
expansion through its seventh year without new fears about
inflation.
   Later, however, stocks declined briefly as the dollar and bonds
lost some of their earlier strength following a government report
that showed orders to U.S. factories rose 2.7 percent in April.
   It was the best showing in four months, leading some economists
to speculated that the Federal Reserve might not lower interest
rates any time soon as earlier suggested.
   Expectations had grown over the last several days that the Fed
might lower interest rates to stem the rising dollar. But analysts
said after the factory orders report that such a move by the Fed is
unlikely given its concerns about inflation.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks was
up 0.97 to 179.08.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index had risen
1.36 to 355.77.
   Among blue-chip stocks, IBM led the rally, up 1} to 110 after
the company announced it had produced the world's fastest
experimentla million-bit memory chip.
   Digital Equipment was up 1 to 92{, AT&amp;T was up \ to 35~ and
Unisys advanced { to 26{.
   Time Inc., meanwhile, was down 6\ to 128}, Union Carbide was off
{ to 26~ and Texaco was down [ to 51].
