<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     05-31 0348</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street Closing,0362</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market finished higher in moderate
trading today after bobbing up and down throughout the session.
   The market opened weak after Tuesday's losses but quickly
rebounded after the government reported that its chief economic
forecasting gauge, the Index of Leading Economic Indicators, shot
up 0.8 percent in April following declines during the previous two
months.
   Analysts said April's upturn, which had been widely anticipated,
was consistent with the view that while the economy is slowing, the
economy is still strong enough to power the record peacetime
expansion through its seventh year without new fears about
inflation.
   The market lost steam by mid-morning, however, as the dollar
slipped from earlier levels and bonds declined following a second
government report that showed orders to U.S. factories rose 2.7
percent in April, the best showing in four months.
   Analysts said the report prompted speculation that the Federal
Reserve might not lower interest rates as earlier suggested.
   Recent expectations were that the Fed might lower interest rates
to stem the rising dollar. But analysts said after the factory
orders report that such a move by the Fed is unlikely given its
concerns about inflation.
   The impact was brief as the dollar continued its upward trend
despite Tuesday's discount rate hike by the Japanese. The dollar
closed mixed in European and U.S. trading. Bond prices firmed
behind the dollar and stocks followed the bond market.
   Analysts said the stock market's ability to break Tuesday's fall
as well as today's rebound shows an underlying strength in the
market.
   ``The lift in the bond market and the fact that the stock market
resisted yesterday's chance to go lower says we still have upside
momentum,'' said Alfred E. Goldman, vice president of A.G. Edwards
&amp; Sons Inc.
   Also helping prices late in the session was a report that the
Federal Reserve has come up with a new indicator of inflationary
pressures based on the money supply and economic growth. Analysts
said the new indicator, although experimental, suggests that the
Fed has room to ease monetary policy.
</TEXT>
