<FIRST>u f AM-AlleghenyInternational     05-31 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Allegheny International,Bjt,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plan Filed For Sunbeam Unit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Allegheny International Inc. said Wednesday it
has filed a plan of reorganization for its Sunbeam Corp. subsidiary
in an attempt to extract the profitable small appliance maker from
bankruptcy court.
   It is the fifth plan the company has filed since entering
Chapter 11 reorganization in February 1988, and an attorney for
unsecured creditors who are owed $220 million gave the latest plan
about the same chances of success and the previous four.
   ``I don't give it much chance,'' said Robert Sable of Pittsburgh.
   If approved by U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Joseph Cosetti, the plan
would pay cash to settle all of the approximately $240 million in
claims pending against the Sunbeam subsidiary. It would leave the
Pittsburgh-based parent still in bankruptcy court to haggle with
creditors over settling their claims.
   Allegheny International also said Cosetti was so aggravated with
the collapse of the fourth reorganization plan that he suspended
the payment of most fees to attorneys and accountants involved in
the case.
   To emphasize his disappointment that no reorganization plan was
submitted for the parent company, Cosetti also invited the U.S.
Trustee to file a request that he appoint a trustee to run the
company, Allegheny International said.
   ``The judge is trying to do something to get some movement in
the case,'' Sable said.
   But because some of the attorneys are paid by banks and
insurance companies, not the debtor, ``all it does is put pressure
on some people, not necessarily the people who can do anything
about it,'' Sable said.
   The unsecured creditors oppose the latest plan and are very
close to finishing their own plan of reorganization, he said. They
are also considering asking Cosetti to appoint a trustee.
   The fourth plan collapsed after investment firm Donaldson,
Lufkin &amp; Jenrette discovered that Allegheny International was
falling short of its earnings goals. The New York investment bank
lowered its takeover bid by $70 million to $687 million,
rreflecting its reliance on earnings estimates to raise takeover
funds.
   The Sunbeam subsidiary encompasses virtually all of the parent's
consumer products businesses.
   Allegheny International said it is confident of raising the
estimated $250 million needed to reorganize Sunbeam. It has already
begun discussions to find a new chief executive for the subsidiary,
which would also get an independent board of directors under the
latest plan.
</TEXT>
