<FIRST>r f AM-Mexico-United     05-31 0228</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-United,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>United Plans Washington-Mexico City Service; Not Buying Mexicana</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   United Airlines plans a new Washington-Mexico
City route this year that will be the first daily non-stop service
connecting the two capitals, Stephen Wolf, chairman of parent
company UAL Inc., said Wednesday.
   Meanwhile, Wolf dashed speculation that the Chicago-based
company was considering buying part of the state-owned Mexicana
Airlines.
   ``It is our intention to grow United Airlines without equity
participation in other airlines,'' he told reporters. ``We want to
continue our close working relationship with Mexicana Airlines, but
only as a marketing partner, not as a buyer.''
   Mexicana's director, Manuel Sosa de la Vega, was quoted in
Wednesday's financial daily El Financiero as saying that if the
carrier were sold, it would be because of political rather than
financial reasons.
   ``There are politicial reasons for all that,'' he said.
   Sosa said that under Mexico's new foreign investment
regulations, a foreign investor would be able to purchase up to 49
percent of Mexicana, which he described as economically healthy.
   Wolf called the liberalization of foreign investment as a ``a
very progressive step'' and said that ``in the case of United
Airlines, it is a very positive background which will encourage us
to put more flights into Mexico.''
   Wolf said service between Washington and Mexico City would begin
later this year pending U.S. government approval.
</TEXT>
