<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 2135EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-USX-Roderick     05-31 0325</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-USX-Roderick,0337</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pivotal USX Chairman Retires</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   USX Corp. Chairman David M. Roderick retired
Wednesday after a 10-year term in which he made USX more of an oil
company than a steel company.
   Roderick, 65, a native of Pittsburgh's rough-and-tumble North
Side and a Marine Corps veteran, rose through the company's finance
department.
   In 1979, Roderick succeeded Edgar B. Speer, a steel operator who
as chairman, it was said, was not above questioning a blast furnace
foreman on the telephone if his unit's production fell behind
schedule.
   Roderick is succeeded by President Charles A. Corry, who
presided over the company's Diversified Group, which produced $6
billion by selling assets in transportation, real estate and other
businesses.
   Speer, Roderick and now Corry reflect the company's
transformation from an oversized, muscle-bound steelmaker, then
called U.S. Steel Corp., to a diversified energy and steel
corporation known today as USX.
   One of Roderick's first moves as chairman was to scrap plans to
build a planned mammoth steel plant on the shore of Lake Erie at
Conneaut, Ohio.
   USX officials sighed with relief that the company did not have
to carry the additional debt and production capacity into the
industry debacle that followed in the 1980s.
   USX under Roderick wrote off $3 billion in assets, mostly in
steel, and closed 140 steel facilities. Companywide employment
plunged from nearly 172,000 in 1979 to fewer than 59,000 in 1988, a
loss of around 113,000 jobs, most of them in steel.
   He has often said his most difficult task as chairman was to
preside over the steel shutdowns because of the pain they caused in
mill towns, including the nearby Monongahela Valley where he was
raised.
   In the meantime, USX spent $10 billion to acquire Marathon Oil
Co. and Texas Oil &amp; Gas Corp., whose $9.9 billion in sales in 1988
accounted for nearly two-thirds of the company's $16.9 billion in
sales. Steel contributed $5.8 billion, or about a third.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
