<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     05-31 0269</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil PricesMixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices were mixed in lackluster
trading Wednesday as June contracts closed for unleaded gasoline
and heating fuel.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the July contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil, fell 5
cents to finish at $19.90 a barrel. Other contracts also declined.
   Among refined products, the June contract for unleaded gasoline
closed 0.83 cent higher at 67.44 cents a gallon, while other
contracts also showed gains.
   The heating oil contract for June delivery fell 0.44 cent to
48.17 cents a gallon. Other contracts also fell.
   ``The major feature today was the expiration of the June
products,'' said Andrew Lebow, an analyst with E.D.&amp;F. Man
International Futures Inc. ``Gasoline went out strong, heating oil
weak.''
   Lebow and other analysts said the oil futures market was slow in
anticipation of next week's meeting of the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries in Vienna.
   Analysts said gasoline futures prices were strong following the
heavy Memorial Day driving weekend and expected strong demand over
the summer months.
   ``I think that market is strong,'' said Mary Haskins, an
assistant vice president with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   The eight-member OPEC price monitoring committee is scheduled to
meet Friday to discuss recent problems, including quota cheating by
some cartel members, followed by a meeting of all 13 oil ministers
Monday.
   The primary focus of next week's meeting is expected to be
whether to raise or retain the cartel's 18.5 million barrel-a-day
quota. OPEC agreed last November to keep the level for the first
six months of 1989.
</TEXT>
