<DOCNO> AP890531-0295 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 1748EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-ComparativeAdvertising     05-31 0640</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Comparative Advertising,0661</SECOND>
<HEAD>Naming Competitors In Advertisements Is Risky Business, Companies
Find</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Jartran Inc. ran ads touting its rental
trucks, it put U-Haul's competing trucks in the background, so they
looked small. But the ploy backfired: a court ruled the ads were
``deliberately false'' and ordered them halted.
   Jartran is one of dozens of companies that have learned the hard
way that mentioning a competitor's product in an advertisement, a
hard-nosed tactic that has become common since 1985, is
increasingly risky.
   ``Every competitive advertiser should be ready to go to court,''
marketing experts Bruce Buchanan and Doron Goldman warned in the
May-June issue of Harvard Business Review. ``Once your competitor
files suit, you can do little to stop the process.''
   Congress may have accelerated the lawsuits last year by
strengthening the fair advertising laws. In addition, companies
suffering real or imagined slights by competitors have grown testy
and are now quick to shoot back, both in counter-ads and lawsuits.
   Even if they lose in court, they figure, they may dissuade
someone else from trying the same thing.
   Under the Trademark Law Revision Act of 1988, anyone who
misrepresents ``his or her or another person's'' goods or services
is liable for damages.
   That wording closed a loophole in the 43-year-old Lanham Act,
which prohibited false claims about one's own products but did not
mention ``another person's.''
   Buchanan and Goldman, who are researchers at New York
University's Stern School of Business, say it is too early to tell
whether the tougher law will lead to a rash of lawsuits.
   But they maintain there was no shortage of such actions under
the old law. They counted more than 60 judicial decisions in
comparative advertising cases, including 30 since the trend picked
up four years ago.
   Even that number is conservative, they say, because many more
cases undoubtedly were settled out of court or did not result in a
judicial opinion.
   In some cases, companies have found to their chagrin, they do
not even have to name a competiting product to get sued.
   When a Tropicana orange juice ad showed Olympic decathlon winner
Bruce Jenner squeezing oranges into a carton, the message was that
Tropicana, unlike other brands, was not made from concentrate.
   But a competitor complained, and a court ruled that the ad was
false, because Tropicana juice is not, in fact, squeezed directly
from oranges into the carton. It is pasteurized and sometimes
frozen first.
   Even claims with more than a shred of truth behind them have
been challenged successfully.
   R.J. Reynolds, for example, got in trouble when it said its Now
cigarettes had ``the lowest tar of all'' brands on the market, with
only 2 milligrams of tar apiece.
   That was true, at least for comparable king-size brands. But
Carlton 70, a shorter brand, had only 1 milligram. Its maker,
American Brands, went to court and won.
   In many cases, a successful suit merely leads to an injunction
banning the offending ads from the airwaves or print media. But if
the plaintiff can show harm, the claims can be expensive. U-Haul
International Inc., for example, was able to prove that it lost
sales and faced higher advertising costs, and it was awarded $20
million in compensatory damages and another $20 million in punitive
damages from Jartran.
   Still, advertising agencies say the tactic is more popular than
ever, with manufacturers of pain relievers, pickup trucks and soft
drinks constantly going head-to-head.
   ``You have to be very, very sure of your claims,'' said Mary
McElyea, a spokeswoman for Chevrolet trucks, which has been
pounding Ford in comparative ads since late 1987.
   ``But if you're careful, it can be very effective. The name of
the game is, cut through the clutter and make it clear to the
customer why your product is better.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890531-0296 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 1815EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     05-31 0571</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0595</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls, Gold Mixed</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar slumped Wednesday amid speculation
about central bank maneuvering.
   There were rumors that the Federal Reserve and possibly other
central banks were selling dollars more discreetly than they have
in the past.
   During most of the dollar's recent run-up the central banks
tried to gain extra psychological impact by allowing their market
interventions to become public. That strategy did not appear to
work.
   Several times Wednesday the dollar appeared to be under downward
pressure even though dealers could not pinpoint anyone who was
selling, said Jerry Egan, chief currency dealer for the Bank of
Boston.
   ``A sudden supply of dollars from an unknown source is very
disconcerting to most participants,'' Egan said. The central banks
``certainly haven't had much success with their name in lights,''
he said.
   Central banks have tried to rein in the dollar because a high
dollar threatens to increase the U.S. trade deficit by making
American-made goods more costly in world markets. It could also
increase inflation abroad.
   Speculation continued Wednesday that the West German central
bank would raise interest rates or that the U.S. Federal Reserve
would lower them. However, many market participants said they
considered those steps unlikely.
   Adding to the choppiness were end-of-the-month dealings to even
up currency accounts and the absence of some senior dealers, who
were attending an annual foreign-exchange meeting in Lisbon,
Portugal.
   The lone currency against which the dollar rose in New York was
the Japanese yen. In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's
business day begins, the dollar fell 0.40 yen to a closing 142.70
yen. Later, in London, it was quoted at 142.30 yen. In New York the
dollar rose to 142.90 yen from 142.75.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.5682 to buy one pound, more expensive than $1.5570 late Tuesday.
In New York, the pound rose to $1.5735 from $1.5710.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Tuesday's rates, included: 1.9815 West German marks, down from
1.9960; 1.7098 Swiss francs, down from 1.7345; 1.2072 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.2075; 6.7195 French francs, down from 6.7635;
and 1,434 Italian lire, down from 1,440.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Tuesday's
rates, included: 1.9755 West German marks, down from 2.0100; 1.7055
Swiss francs, down from 1.7545; 6.6855 French francs, down from
6.8085; 2.2460 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2630; 1,443.00 Italian
lire, down from 1,452.50; and 1.2061 Canadian dollars, up from
1.2055.
   Gold prices fell in New York after having been up in Asia and
Europe.
   In Hong Kong, gold rose $1.95 a troy ounce to a bid of $364.68.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of $363.50 a troy ounce,
compared with $362.25 late Tuesday. In Zurich, gold rose to $363.43
from $362.10.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery fell to $363.30 a troy ounce from $365.70 on Tuesday.
   Later, Republic National Bank of New York said gold was bid at
$361 an ounce as of 4 p.m. EDT, down from $364.45 on Tuesday.
   Silver bullion prices held steady on the London market where the
metal was trading at a late bid price of $5.20 a troy ounce,
unchanged from Tuesday. On New York's Comex, silver bullion for
current delivery fell to $5.16 an ounce from $5.23.
