<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     05-31 0682</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0705</SECOND>
<HEAD>Coffee Futures Slide On Dim Outlook For New Marketing Pact</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Coffee futures prices sank Wednesday on New York's Coffee, Sugar
&amp; Cocoa Exchange amid growing pessimism about next week's special
meeting of the International Coffee Organization.
   On other markets, precious metals slid lower; grains and
soybeans were mostly lower; energy futures were mixed; cattle
futures were mixed and pork futures advanced.
   Coffee settled 2 cents to 4.08 cents lower with the contract for
delivery in July at $1.3068 a pound.
   The sell-off was prompted by a report that John Rosenbaum, the
U.S. chief delegate to the International Coffee Organization,
remained determined not to attend the talks in London unless coffee
producers first offer a proposal acceptable to the United States.
   The five-day meeting of most of the world's largest
coffee-producing and coffee-consuming nations is aimed at producing
a new International Coffee Agreement to replace the six-year pact
that expires on Sept. 30.
   The United States, the organization's largest consumer member,
is resisting a push to simply extend the existing agreement,
calling instead for tighter restrictions on sales of coffee at
discount prices to countries that are not members of the
International Coffee Organization.
   Wednesday's sharp decline in prices suggests an abrupt change of
attitude among traders who had grown optimistic about a new
agreement following a meeting last week in Florida between
Rosenbaum and coffee-producer representatives from Brazil, Colombia
and Central America.
   ``I'd say the odds for an agreement are 50-50, and it's unlikely
that anything will be hammered out until it comes down to the wire
in September,'' said Sandra Kaul, a market analyst in New York with
Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Analyst Arthur Stevenson of Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in
New York said the selling was also a reflection of the mild weather
in Brazil, the world's largest coffee producer, at the beginning of
the South American winter season.
   ``The market will be increasingly trading off the weather in
Brazil,'' Stevenson said.
   Silver fell to a 33-month low and gold prices also slipped on
New York's Commodity Exchange despite some weakening of the
dollar's value against other major currencies.
   The decline indicated a continuing lack of investor interest in
precious metals as an inflation hedge.
   Gold settled $2.40 to $3.20 lower with June at $363.30 a troy
ounce; silver was 7 cents to 7.7 cents lower with June at $5.16 a
troy ounce, the lowest spot silver price since Aug. 29, 1986.
   Most grain and soybean futures prices retreated on the Chicago
Board of Trade as forecasts for more rain in the Corn Belt quieted
fears of a second year of drought.
   After the close, the National Weather Service issued a
six-to-10-day forecast calling for normal rainfall in most of the
Midwest during the middle of next week.
   Wheat settled unchanged to 5\ cents lower with July at $3.87{ a
bushel; corn was unchanged to 1\ cents lower with July at $2.60} a
bushel; oats were 1{ cents to 2\ cents higher with July at $1.66} a
bushel; soybeans were 4 cents lower to \ cent higher with July at
$7.14 a bushel.
   Crude-oil futures prices notched lower while futures prices for
refined products ended mixed on the New York Mercantile Exchange in
choppy activity fueled by conflicting statements from various OPEC
ministers regarding oil production and demand.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 5 cents to 10 cents
lower with July at $19.90 a barrel; heating oil was .44 cent lower
to .08 cent higher with June at 48.71 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .28 cent lower to .83 cent higher with June at 67.44
cents a gallon.
   On the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, live cattle settled .45 cent
lower to .30 cent higher with June at 68.90 cents a pound; feeder
cattle were .10 cent lower to .05 cent higher with August at 76.45
cents a pound; live hogs were unchanged to .65 cent higher with
June at 47.92 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .20 cent to
.43 cent higher with July at 29.90 cents a pound.
</TEXT>
