<HEAD>Stock Prices End Higher</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA C. MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stocks seesawed Wednesday but ended mostly
higher, supported by a late recovery in the bond market.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials rose 4.60 points to
close at 2,480.15.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by a margin of about 8 to
5 in nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks,
with 896 up, 558 down and 505 unchanged.
   After a weak opening, stocks rebounded following a government
report that its chief economic forecasting gauge shot up 0.8
percent in April. The Index of Leading Economic Indicators had
declined during the previous two months and economists had warned
that a third consecutive decline would signal a recession.
   The market quickly lost ground, however, as the dollar slipped
and bonds declined following a second report from the Commerce
Department that showed orders to U.S. factories rose 2.7 percent in
April, the best showing in four months.
   That report indicated the economy is still going strong,
prompting speculation that the Federal Reserve might not loosen its
hold on interest rates.
   The impact was brief, though, as fear of Fed tightening faded
and the dollar recovered from earlier sluggishness, lifting bond
prices and inciting some late-afternoon buying on Wall Street.
   ``The main factor was the bond market because of the dollar and
growing confidence that the economy is slowing down and that
interest rates are going to come down,'' said Alfred E. Goldman,
vice president of A.G. Edwards &amp; Sons Inc.
   Late word that the Bundesbank might not raise its discount rate
also firmed prices before a last-minute selling spree eliminated
much of the gains in the final minutes of trading.
   The market lost ground in the final minutes of trading.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board totaled 162.53 million
shares, up from 151.78 million shares Tuesday.
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trades in those stocks on regional exchanges and in the
over-the-counter market, totaled 190.68 million shares.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market rose $13.102 billion, or 0.49
percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks rose
0.74 to 178.85.
   Among blue-chip stocks, IBM led the rally closing up 1] at 109|.
Digital Equipment closed ] higher at 91~, Motorola advanced 1| to
56] and Philip Morris gained 1[ to 139[.
   Time Inc. tumbled 8 to 127. It had risen sharply over the last
couple of weeks on speculation that a bidder would emerge to derail
its planned merger with Warner Communications but no bidder turned
up. Warner rose ~ to 51}.
   Texaco fell ] to 51[, Union Carbide dropped | to 26} and Pan Am
lost [ to 4|.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index gained 1.54 to 367.84, and
S&amp;P's 500-stock composite index rose 1.47 to 320.52.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market rose
1.96 to 446.17. At the American Stock Exchange, the market value
index closed at 356.66, up 2.25.
