<SECOND>AM-New Cigarette,0212</SECOND>
<HEAD>Philip Morris Test-Marketing Low-Nicotine Cigarette</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Philip Morris Cos. is test-marketing a new,
virtually nicotine-free cigarette that the company believes has as
much flavor as regular cigarettes.
   Published reports said Philip Morris was testing the cigarette,
but the company refused to confirm or deny the reports Wednesday,
saying it does not comment on product testing.
   However, a source, who asked not to be identified, said the
reports were correct.
   The lower nicotine levels in the new cigarette _ which will be
sold under the names Merit Free and Next from Merit _ are achieved
through a process similar to the decaffeination of coffee.
   The cigarette's competitors, which include American Brands
Inc.'s Carlton and RJR Nabisco Inc.'s Now, use a different
technology that affects the taste of the tobacco.
   The new cigarette will contain 0.1 milligram of nicotine, the
same amount as in Carlton and Now.
   Low-nicotine cigarettes appeal to smokers who are trying to cut
down their intake of harmful substances contained in tobacco smoke.
   The prospect of a new, potentially successful product apparently
appealed to investors Wednesday. Philip Morris stock rose $1.12{ a
share to close at $139.12{ in New York Stock Exchange composite
trading.
</TEXT>
