<FIRST>r f AM-HollyFarms     05-31 0550</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Holly Farms,0573</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tyson Challenged in Delaware Court to Raise Bid for Holly Farms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If Tyson Foods Inc. is so eager to buy the
Holly Farms Corp., it should simply raise its $1.1 billion offer, a
lawyer for a competing bidder told a Chancery Court judge Wednesday
in Delaware.
   ``Why doesn't Tyson open its pocketbook?'' said Franklin
Balotti, a lawyer representing ConAgra Inc. of Omaha, Neb.
   Balotti's comment came at a hearing before Vice Chancellor
Maurice Hartnett in Wilmington, Del., on a request from Tyson to
block a proposed merger announced May 20 between ConAgra and Holly
Farms.
   After listening to arguments from lawyers representing Holly
Farms, Tyson, ConAgra and Holly Farms shareholders, Hartnett
retired to consider Tyson's motion. He did not say when he would
rule, but Balotti said it could take up to two weeks.
   Tyson has offered $1.1 billion in cash for Holly Farms' stock,
while Tyson would acquire Holly Farms in a stock swap valued at
about $1.3 billion.
   Tyson lawyer Rodman Ward said Holly Farms managers have
improperly favored ConAgra throughout a buyout squabble that began
last year.
   ``This battle has been bruising and expensive,'' Ward said.
   Balotti said ConAgra and Holly have a legitimate agreement
calling for a shareholder vote on the merger, and Bruce McNew, a
lawyer for Holly shareholders, asked Hartnett to allow that voting.
   Tyson, based in Springdale, Ark., can top ConAgra's offer if it
wants Holly shareholders to reject the merger, McNew said.
   ``Tyson doesn't want to compete,'' he said.
   A shareholders vote on the proposed merger is expected in July.
   The merger, to be accomplished through a stock swap, would be
worth $74.81 a share or $1.3 billion to Holly shareholders based on
the value of ConAgra shares at the time the agreement was announced.
   Lawyers told Hartnett, however, that the deal likely would be
worth about $68 a share based on the longterm expected value of
ConAgra stock.
   Tyson has issued a cash tender offer for $63.50 a share or $1.1
billion for all of Holly Farms stock.
   Tyson, the nation's largest poultry processor, has been trying
to take over Holly Farms since last October, and the battle has
been tied up in Hartnett's court since Holly and ConAgra announced
a previous merger proposal last November.
   Holly shareholders rejected that proposal in April, but an
``asset option agreement'' included in the plan still is at issue
in the continuing debate.
   The asset agreement allows ConAgra to purchase about a third of
Holly Farms if the company is bought by someone else.
   Tyson's challenge of the asset agreement is expected to go to
trial, but no trial date has been set.
   Observers of the Holly Farms battle say the Memphis company
likely would function as an independent subsidiary with ConAgra,
while the same would not be true with Tyson.
   Holly Farms is a diversified company heavily dependent on fresh
fryer sales. ConAgra specializes in agricultural services and food.
   Although ConAgra is considered a friendly suitor for Holly
Farms, Holly lawyer Kenneth Nachbar said Tyson and ConAgra were
dealing behind the scenes until shortly before the proposed merger
was announced.
   Tyson offered to pay ConAgra $50 million to step aside but an
agreement based on that offer fell apart at the last minute,
Nachbar said.
</TEXT>
