<FIRST>u f AM-Bilzerian     05-31 0455</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bilzerian,0473</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bilzerian Resumes Testimony</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer Co. Chairman Paul A. Bilzerian resumed
testifying at his federal securities fraud trial Wednesday, but
only after his lawyers revamped their case to compensate for an
unfavorable ruling by the judge.
   On Tuesday, U.S. District Robert J. Ward ruled that if Bilzerian
testified that he didn't believe he was breaking the law in two
takeover attempts, it would open up a line of questioning to
prosecutors about what his lawyers told him at the time.
   Such lawyer-client conversations are usually confidential under
the so-called attorney-client privilege.
   When Ward ruled that privilege would be waived if Bilzerian was
asked and answered certain questions by his defense lawyers, they
asked for an adjornment to re-consider their strategy.
   ``We have determined an your honor,'' defense attorney Arthur
Mathews told Ward at the beginning of Wednesday's session ``that we
do not intend to pursue anything upon the direct examination of Mr.
Bilzerian that would waive the attorney-client privilege.''
   Mathews added later: ``We have restructured our planned
examination of Mr. Bilzerian.''
   Under Mathews' questioning, Bilzerian described his acquisition
of stock in H.H. Robertson Co. manufacturing and construction
concern and apparel-maker Cluett, Peabody &amp; Co., two transactions
listed in the indictmet against him.
   His testimony was to continue Thursday.
   Bilzerian, 38, of Tampa, Fla., is accused of conspiracy,
violating securities and tax laws and making false statements in
connection with four failed takeover attempts in 1985 and 1986.
   None of the charges involve Bilzerian's $1.06 billion takeover
of Singer last year.
   In two of those four transactions _ the 1985 purchase of Cluett
Peabody &amp; Co. shares and the 1986 purchase of Hammermill Paper Co.
stock _ the government contends Bilzerian falsely claimed to be
using millions of dollars of his own money, when most of the money
actually was raised by others.
   But the defense has contended Bilzerian acted in ``good faith''
and did not believe he was breaking the law in filing misleading
documents with the Securities and Exchange Commission.
   In statements he made to the SEC in 1988, Bilzerian said he was
merely following his then-lawyers' advice when he supplied
misleading information on SEC forms.
   Ward, however, said by taking the witness stand and invoking
that ``good faith'' defense under questioning by his own lawyers,
Bilzerian was waiving the attorney-client privilege and prosecutors
could ask on cross examination what was the basis for his belief
that he was not breaking any laws _ more specifically _ what had
his lawyers told him at the time.
   Bilzerian was not required to testify.
   If convicted, Bilzerian faces a maximum penalty of five years in
jail and a $250,000 fine on each count.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890531-0304 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-05-31-89 2343EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-CableLicensing     05-31 0607</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cable Licensing,0628</SECOND>
<HEAD>FCC Recommends Abolition of Copyright System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications is recommending to
Congress that it abolish a 13-year-old copyright system that allows
cable television operators to pay a percentage of their income to
retransmit over-the-air TV programs, officials said Wednesday.
   The commission, in a ruling it made Tuesday and released
Wednesday, said cable TV companies should negotiate with
broadcasters and producers on a case-by-case basis for programs.
   Critics of that approach say it would be very costly for cable
operators to negotiate for every program individually and could
result in fewer programs being made available to cable subscribers
or cause subscription costs to go up.
   Congress in 1976 compelled broadcasters and program owners to
allow cable operators to retransmit their programs. In return for
this ``compulsory license,'' cable companies were required to pay a
specified percentage of their revenues to the U.S. Copyright
Office. The office's Copyright Royalty Tribunal decides how to
allocate the fees among broadcasters, program owners and entities
such as sports franchises.
   In establishing the rules, Congress reasoned that the costs of
working out contracts for every program would stymy the infant
cable TV industry.
   The cable industry last year paid $188 million in compulsory
license fees, according to Lynn McReynolds, a spokeswoman for the
National Cable Television Association.
   FCC Chairman Dennis Patrick said the current system ``impedes
the efficient functioning of the market'' and ``weakens the
incentives of producers to respond'' to consumers' tastes and
programming preferences.
   He said it also subsidizes program acquisition by cable
operators and disadvantages competitive alternatives to cable.
   But James Mooney, president of the cable association, said the
FCC ``seems to be a little off the deep end.''
   Mooney noted that Congress last year extended the present
copyright system to companies that package TV programs for delivery
to backyard satellite dish owners rather than making those
packagers negotiate for shows one at a time.
   ``Congress and the commission seem not to share the same view on
these matters,'' Mooney said in a statement.
   The commission last year made a preliminary decision to
recommend repeal of the compulsory license rules for programs that
come from stations located outside local viewing areas.
``Superstations'' such as WTBS in Atlanta and WGN in Chicago are
examples of these so-called distant signals.
   Cable operators use satellites or microwave systems to relay
these signals around the nation and then pipe them into homes
locally.
   In its new decision, the FCC recommended that the rules be
repealed for all signals, both from distant broadcasters and from
local broadcasters such as channels 4, 7, 9 and so on.
   Commissioner Patricia Dennis concurred with Patrick in the
ruling. Commissioner James Quello concurred with repealing the
distant signal provision, but he argued for keeping the compulsory
license for local signals.
   ``It is conceivable that under full copyright liability cable
operators may choose not to carry local broadcast signals due to
the costs'' of obtaining rights to retransmit the programs, Quello
said.
   He said the FCC should, instead, recommend that Congress
reimpose rules requiring cable systems to carry all local broadcast
stations. He said these ``must-carry'' rules shouldn't exist
without compulsory license for local signals.
   He also disputed the agency staff's contention that costs of
negotiating contracts were lower today, per subscriber, than in
1976.
   Mooney said it was ``surprising'' the commission was
recommending repeal of the rules for local signals.
   He said that would create a situation in which ``cable could not
even retransmit local signals by joint agreement _ the original
rights owners in Hollywood would have to consent too, presumably
for a price.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
