<FIRST>u f AM-Mexico-Development     05-31 0560</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mexico-Development,0579</SECOND>
<HEAD>Salinas Presents Six-Year Blueprint For Mexico; Calls For 6 Percent
Growth</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Carlos Salinas de Gortari on
Wednesday unveiled an ambitious plan to transform Mexico's
stagnant, debt-burdened economy into a robust modern engine
generating a steady 6 percent growth a year.
   The National Development Plan for 1989-1994 proposes the
``modernization of the nation in all its aspects'' during Salinas'
six-year term of office.
   The Salinas administration's 164-page blueprint touches on
everything from drinking water to foreign policy, but the
centerpiece is economics.
   ``The economic strategy of the plan has two priority goals:
achieving a growth rate of around 6 percent a year and ...
maintaining stability so price increases are comparable to those of
our commercial partners,'' Salinas said in a ceremony at the
National Palace unveiling the plan.
   Salinas' prescription for economic health includes cutting debt
payments, keeping inflation down and prices stable, encouraging
productivity, savings and investment and modernizing finance,
technology and industry.
   One of the most critical elements is renegotiating the $107.4
billion foreign debt, the second-largest in the developing world
after Brazil's. Mexico paid $9 billion in interest and $5 billion
in principal in 1988 and servicing costs were expected to reach $16
billion this year.
   But Salinas warned against blaming the debt for all of Mexico's
problems. It will take more than stemming the financial hemorrhage,
he said, to transform the nation.
   ``Let's not fall into thinking that once this obstacle has been
overcome, we will have resolved all our problems,'' he warned.
``The internal effort to produce and produce better is
irreplaceable.''
   The plan, which the Constitution requires every president to
present during his first six months in office, reiterates Salinas'
election campaign and inaugural address promises of economic
recovery in a more democratic Mexico with a higher standard of
living.
   Salinas was able to point to substantial progress since his Dec.
1 inauguration. Mexico has liberalized its rules on foreign
investment, won concessions and credits from international
creditors, kept the lid on inflation, eased its dependence on oil
and sold off some state-owned industries.
   On Tuesday, the Treasury Department announced an agreement with
the Club of Paris, a group of 16 creditor nations, designed to cut
the debt by $2.6 billion and refinance 80 percent of the interest
over the next decade.
   Last week, the International Monetary Fund said it had approved
a $4.1 billion credit line to Mexico, 40 percent of which can be
used to pay off the foreign debt.
   The 41-year-old president stressed the importance of creating
jobs and fostering a work force that compete in world markets in
both productivity and quality.
   He said Mexico must keep pace with a changing world where
competition and technology are critical and commercial markets are
interdependent.
   The Salinas reforms follow decades of protectionism that saw the
Mexican economy grow by an impressive 6 to 7 percent each year but
also fostered inefficient industry dependent on government
subsidies and import barriers.
   They also are an antidote to the economic crisis that began in
1982, when the oil boom crashed and Mexico, a heavy borrower,
suddenly went from riches to rags.
   The buying power of the average worker is now half what it was
in 1982 and the party that has ruled Mexico since 1929 barely won
the 1988 presidential election.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
