<FIRST>u f AM-Eastern 1stLd-Writethru f0275 05-31 0735</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Eastern, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0275,0755</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eastern Plans 221 Flights By July</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Eastern-Tourism, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: INSERTS new grafs 10-12 to UPDATE with report that examiner
expected to report no viable offers for Eastern; picks up 10th graf pvs,
`Eastern said ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN WINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastern Airlines said Wednesday it will expand from
79 daily flights in June to 221 in July, the company's largest
increase in service since a strike began March 4.
   Eastern said it will serve 27 cities in June and 52 in July as
it moves toward a new full schedule of 600 flights by the end of
the year.
   ``This is a significant part of a multi-phase plan to establish
Eastern as a competitive, dependable, full-service airline,'' said
George Brennan, vice president for marketing.
   Striking unions scoffed at Eastern's announcement. Hank Weber, a
spokesman for the pilots union, said the company won't have enough
pilots in July to make 221 flights daily.
   ``It's all flap and no throttle,'' Weber said. ``Unless they
actually do it, it's just talk.''
   Weber said Eastern has been flying 92 to 112 flights daily since
the beginning of the strike. The company has fewer than 250 pilots,
he said.
   Wally Haber, a spokesman for the Machinists union, said an
expanded schedule would be of little help to the carrier.
   ``Travel agents are not booking Eastern now because they're not
dependable,'' Haber said. ``Eastern is going to be flying a lot of
empty airplanes.''
   Miami-based Eastern filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection
from its creditors March 9, five days after the start of a strike
by Machinists that has been supported by pilots and flight
attendants.
   David I. Shapiro, the court-appointed bankruptcy examiner for
Eastern, is expected to report at a hearing Thursday that no viable
offers have been made for the airline, The New York Times reported
in Thursday's editions.
   Eastern's unions have recently supported proposed buyout
proposals from two investor groups, one led by former Piedmont
Airlines chairman William Howard and the other by Chicago
commodities trader Joseph Ritchie. Shapiro has challenged the two
groups to put at least $100 million of their own cash at risk.
   Management, on the other hand, is proceeding with a plan to
rebuild Eastern as a smaller carrier and sell $1.8 billion of its
assets separately.
   Eastern said the expanded schedule will allow the company to
recall by July more than 1,700 non-union workers placed on ``no
work'' status when the airline curtailed service shortly after the
strike started. Eastern said it has 5,000 employees now and
eventually will have about 17,000, compared with a pre-strike total
of around 30,000.
   Eastern was operating 1,000 flights daily before the strike and
has 110 now. Sixty daily flights currently are part of Eastern's
Northeast shuttle business that has been sold to developer Donald
Trump. The shuttle business is not included in figures for flights
planned in June and July, Eastern said.
   In Atlanta, Eastern's largest hub, the airline will launch 82
daily flights to 26 cities by July 2. New York-Bermuda service
begins June 9. Service from Miami to Caracas, Venezuela, will
resume June 1. Eastern also plans to increase flights between Miami
and New York during the summer.
   The carrier said it will continue its 200 weekly flights between
Miami and 14 cities in Latin America and the Caribbean. Eastern
said it will add about 614,000 seats in July.
   ``Eastern's comeback this summer will feature bargain fares
normally associated with the introduction of new service,'' Brennan
said in a news release.
   ``With $39 to $139 domestic fares, our customers can take
advantage of the lowest fares in the sky _ without restrictive
penalties or length-of-stay requirements.''
   For a limited time, Eastern also will offer first-class tickets
at prices below normal economy-class fares to attract business
travelers.
   ``Because of the turmoil here,'' company spokeswoman Karen
Ceremsak said, ``we'll need to use price as an incentive to get
customers to try us again.''
   On June 9, Eastern said, it will resume or add service from
Atlanta to Washington; New York; Miami; Orlando, Fla.; Tampa, Fla.;
and Newark, N.J.
   On July 2, service from Atlanta will be restored to Boston; Los
Angeles; New Orleans; Denver; Chicago; Philadelphia; Pittsburgh;
Seattle; San Francisco; Milwaukee; St. Louis; Indianapolis;
Buffalo, N.Y.; Huntsville, Ala.; Charlotte, N.C.; Fort Lauderdale,
Fla.; West Palm Beach, Fla.; Sarasota, Fla.; Fort Myers, Fla.; and
Greenville, S.C.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
